sequence: Alfa Romeo Automobiles S.p.A. is an Italian luxury car manufacturer and a subsidiary of Stellantis . The company was founded in 1869 by Count Alessandro Giuseppe di Marzio as a separate automobile company.The company was purchased by Alfa Romeo USA in 1997, which then sold the businesses to General Motors Co. in 2004. [1] Fiat Chrysler Automobiles , also owned by Fiat, was acquired by Fiat in 2011.Fiat's flagship vehicles are all designed by Stefano Ghietti, who has also worked with Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz. Bartolini ( German: ‎ Bartoloni), also called Bambini, is an Italian fascist politician.

ESP most commonly refers to: Extrasensory perception, a paranormal ability Spain (España) - ISO three-letter country code for SpainESP may also refer to:Arts, entertainmentMusic  ESP Guitars, a manufacturer of electric guitars E.S. Posthumus, an independent music group formed in 2000, that produces cinematic style music ESP-Disk, a 1960s free-jazz record label based in New York The Electric Soft Parade, a British band formed in 2001 Eric Singer Project, side project founded in the 1990s by musician Eric Singer ESP, a collaboration between Space Tribe and other artistsSongs, albums  E.S.P.

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software. The series consists of six main episodes, a "lost" episode, and a final game; all but the final game were originally released for MS-DOS in 1990 and 1991, while the 2001 Commander Keen was released for the Game Boy Color. The series follows the eponymous Commander Keen, the secret identity of the eight-year-old genius Billy Blaze, as he defends the Earth and the galaxy from alien threats with his homemade spaceship, rayguns, and pogo stick.

Year 950 (CML) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Arab–Byzantine War: A Hamdanid army (30,000 men) led by Sayf al-Dawla raids into  Byzantine theme Anatolia. He defeats Bardas Phokas, but is then ambushed on his return and heavily defeated by Leo Phokas. Europe  November 22 – King Lothair II dies at Turin (possibly poisoned by Berengar of Ivrea). Berengar is crowned king of Italy and imprisons Lothair's now 19-year-old widow, Adelaide for four months at Como.

Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel  (colloquial: Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert's Hotel) is a thought experiment which illustrates a counterintuitive property of infinite sets. It is demonstrated that a fully occupied hotel with infinitely many rooms may still accommodate additional guests, even infinitely many of them, and this process may be repeated infinitely often. The idea was introduced by David Hilbert in a 1924 lecture "Über das Unendliche", reprinted in , and was popularized through George Gamow's 1947 book One Two Three... Infinity.The paradoxConsider a hypothetical hotel with a countably infinite number of rooms, all of which are occupied.

The year 2000 in Israel and Palestine marked the beginning of the al-Aqsa Intifada leading to a number of Palestinian deaths, including three Israeli soldiers killed on October 31, 2000 in the first attack by the Israeli occupation forces. In this article, we will define (as defined above), "Islamism", referring to various varieties of Islamic extremism, from fundamentalism through religious fanaticism. The term should be understood as encompassing any movement or organization with a strong commitment to Islamic tenets, regardless of whether it is an explicitly Islamist one.

An anti-tank guided missile ( ATGM ) , anti-tank missile , anti-tank guided weapon ( ATGW ) or anti-armor guided weapon (ATAGWW) is an effective short- to medium range, high performance, long range land- and air-based weapons system that is capable of delivering a direct hit to an enemy's armored vehicle, aircraft or other hostile surface force. It can be mounted on semi-autonomous trucks or vehicles, either remotely from the battlefield or automatically by remote control.In the early 1990s, several types of anti-tank guided missiles, such as AGM-109 Tomahawk Land attack Missiles, were widely employed by various countries during conflict in Afghanistan and Iraq.

In mathematics , a Möbius strip , band , or loop ( , ; ) , also spelled Mobius or Micro-Bicycle , is a circular segment of a circle, which can be used in several different applications such as tracing, determining the angle of a circle by making an angle between two points and rotating one point at a time. Most Möbius strips work well for this purpose. In its simplest form they may be used with circles that are flat and parallel to a central axis, like a straight line on a plane, or if they're arranged in lines, like an ellipsoid .

Toilet paper ( sometimes called toilet tissue ) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and urethra from fecal contamination and other causes. In many areas of North America and parts of South America, toilet paper is an important part of the daily routine of people who are not residents or non-residents.A single sheet of toilet paper can contain about 20 to 30 pieces of tissue, each weighing approximately 4 to 12 grams. As with most products of that nature, it is more common to see two sheets rather than a single roll in a supermarket or drug store.

Edward Teller (; January 15, 1908 – September 9, 2003) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who is known colloquially as "the father of the hydrogen bomb" (see the Teller–Ulam design), although he did not care for the title, considering it to be in poor taste. Throughout his life, Teller was known both for his scientific ability and for his difficult interpersonal relations and volatile personality.Born in Hungary in 1908, Teller emigrated to the United States in the 1930s, one of the many so-called "Martians", a group of prominent Hungarian scientist émigrés.

An adverb is a word or an expression that modifies a verb, adjective, another adverb, determiner, clause, preposition, or sentence. Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, level of certainty, etc., answering questions such as how?, in what way?, when?, where?, and to what extent?. This is called the adverbial function, and may be performed by single words (adverbs) or by multi-word adverbial phrases and adverbial clauses.Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various forms and have a variety of regulatory functions. Examples of this can include disciplinary action for rule infractions and deciding on rulechanges in the sport that they govern. Governing bodies have different scopes. They may cover a range of sport at an international level, such as the International Olympic Committee and the International Paralympic Committee, or only a single sport at a national level, such as the Rugby Football League. National bodies will largely have to be affiliated with international bodies for the same sport.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia:History of South Asia – South Asia includes the contemporary political entities of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Afghanistan, Bhutan, and the island nations of Sri Lanka and the Maldives.ChronologyJames Mill (1773–1836), in his The History of British India (1817), distinguished three phases in the history of India, namely Hindu, Muslim and British civilisations. This periodisation has been influential, but has also been criticised for the misconceptions it gave rise to.

Frame Relay is a standardized wide area network ( WAN ) technology that specifies the physical and data link layers of an enterprise's network. It originated as a standard for large telecommunications networks used by major telecommunications companies to deliver high-speed Internet connections to consumers. The specification was first introduced in the 1980s by NTT DoCoMo under the name VyprVPN, and became widely supported in the 90s by Cisco, Telefonica, Netgear, and others.The specifications were subsequently adopted by several U.S. telcos, including AT&T, CenturyLink, Frontier Communications, Time Warner Cable, Verizon Communications, and Charter Communications.

Year 876 (DCCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  At the invitation of Benevento, the newly-restored Byzantine fleet appears in the waters off Otranto. On the orders of Emperor Basil I, the Byzantines sail up the Adriatic Sea and reconquer part of southern Italy. The city of Bari is occupied in the name of the Byzantine Empire. Instead of holding it for his 'ally' Adelchis of Benevento, Basil makes it the capital of the new Byzantine Theme of Longobardia.

Svante August Arrhenius ( , ; 19 February 1859 – 2 October 1927) was a Swedish scientist. Originally a physicist, but often referred to as a chemist, Arrhenius was one of the founders of the science of physical chemistry. He received the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 1903, becoming the first Swedish Nobel laureate. In 1905, he became director of the Nobel Institute, where he remained until his death.Arrhenius was the first to use principles of physical chemistry to estimate the extent to which increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide are responsible for the Earth's increasing surface temperature.

Bikram Yoga is a system of hot yoga , a type of yoga as exercise , devised by Bikram Choudhury.In this system, the body and its vital organs (heart, brain, intestines and other organs) are worked together to achieve a state of satisatured physical activity, in which muscles contract to increase blood flow and oxygen saturation.The term "bikram," from bikraman , means "two hands or legs." Barbara Ehrenreich is an American author who was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on September 18, 1949. She came to the United States after her father moved to San Francisco to study law.

Medina , officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in the United Arab Emirates. It was established in the early 13th century by the Muslim Caliph Abdul Rahman bin Zayd, while he was still an officer of the Ummayad Sultanate in Baghdad. Marjoribanks: The marjoram ("marshmallow" in England) is a popular candy made from dried marshmallow flours and other ingredients mixed with water and milk. They are generally used in sweetened  iced beverages, flavored iced coffee, iced teas, and candies.

A pegmatite is an igneous rock showing a very coarse texture , with large interlocking crystals usually greater in size than those of quartz or basalt. The term is often used to describe rocks that form at the site of a major volcanic activity, but can also be used to describe mineral-rich shale and other similar rocks produced on fault zones.Gulf pegmatites are typically characterized by low-quality petrographically crystalline mica and relatively small pore sizes; they are widely distributed along the Gulf coast of the Caribbean, from the Florida Keys through the Bahamas, Puerto Rico, and the Turks and Caicos Islands.

Éraic (or eric) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild, a form of tribute paid in reparation for murder or other major crimes. The term survived into the sixteenth century as , by then relating only to compensation for the killing of an Irishman. In the case of homicide, if the attacker fled, the fine had to be paid by the tribe to which he belonged.In Irish mythology the eraic takes an important place. In the Oidheadh Chloinne Tuireann, the children of Tuirreann owe an eraic to Lugh.

Year 873 ( DCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and concluding on Sunday, 23 March ( link will display the full calendar ).The first three months of the year began on 3 December 1539, the same day as Charles V's coronation as King of France. In 1784, President John Jay signed the Federal Reserve Act, instituting an institution with no authority other than that which was granted it by Congress and the states. It was to become known as the National Credit Union Association (NCUA), later referred to as the American Bankers Association (ABA).

In chemistry , an aldehyde is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C ( H ) and a polar molecule attached to its central core. It is one of the chemical compounds that can form complexes with each other, such as diene and ethylbenzene . Aldehydes may be naturally occurring or artificially synthesized.Alkyldimethyltramethylamine (AMMA) is a highly-selective benzene analogue of alkylphenylalanine. Alfred Lebowitz (November 1, 1784 – August 22, 1939) was an American writer, poet, political commentator, and statesman. He was known for his controversial writings about politics, religion, science, literature, morality, and art.

A brain tumor occurs when abnormal cells form within the brain . There are two main types of tumors : malignancies and neuroepithelial tumors.The term "brain tumour" derives from the fact that the lesions appear in the central portion of the head, but may have other locations in the body. Blaise Pascal Blaise Pascal (, 15 January 1818 – 9 December 1859) was an American mathematician, physicist and philosopher born in Vienna, Austria.He was the author of the famous Principia Mathematica and the greatest-selling work in mathematical physics ever written: his Principia Naturalium (1791).

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc (then a subsidiary of U.S. Robotics, later 3Com). These devices were launched on March 10, 1997.Accessories and pricingPalm also sold the 10201U modem at 14.4 kbit/s, introduced at a price of $129 (this modem is also compatible with the Palm III and Palm IIIx devices). An upgrade kit was also available, which allowed users of the earlier Pilot 1000/5000 devices to upgrade the OS, ROM, and RAM to match the PalmPilot Professional.

Rice is the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa (Asian rice) or less commonly Oryza glaberrima (African rice). The name wild rice is usually used for species of the genera Zizania and Porteresia, both wild and domesticated, although the term may also be used for primitive or uncultivated varieties of Oryza.As a cereal grain, domesticated rice is the most widely consumed staple food for over half of the world's human population, especially in Asia and Africa. It is the agricultural commodity with the third-highest worldwide production, after sugarcane and maize.

Humour (Commonwealth English) or humor (American English) is the tendency of experiences to provoke laughter and provide amusement. The term derives from the humoral medicine of the ancient Greeks, which taught that the balance of fluids in the human body, known as humours (Latin: humor, "body fluid"), controlled human health and emotion.People of all ages and cultures respond to humour. Most people are able to experience humour—be amused, smile or laugh at something funny (such as a pun or joke)—and thus are considered to have a sense of humour.

In Euclidean geometry , an affine transformation , or an affinity ( from the Latin , affinis , `` connected by an angle ``), is a modification of an affine transformation, that transforms the vector space into another vector space . When used in algebraic coordinates , affine transformations can be expressed by using a coordinate system such as Euler's coordinate system to specify the vector space along a line. However, many examples use more traditional methods such as trigonometric functions and derivatives. An adverb often refers to something that is done; this is especially true for verbs, adjectives, inflections, and words.

Year 1030 (MXXX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Romanos III Argyros decides to retaliate upon the incursions of the Muslims on the eastern frontier. He leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (20,000 men) to secure Antioch. The Mirdasid emir Shibl al-Dawla Nasr of Aleppo sues for peace, but Romanos refuses to negotiate and leads his army against Aleppo, against the advice of his generals. The Byzantine army encamps near Azaz, where they are encircled by the Mirdasids' Bedouin troops, who cut off the Byzantines from food and water.

Salmon is the common name for several species of ray-finned fish in the family Salmonidae . Other fish in the same family such as swordfish, catfish, sardines, carp, and halibut can be distinguished based on their fin rays. An ancient Greek poet (Pausanias) named Demosthenes was known for writing poems in a style characteristic of Roman literature, which were later called Epic Epitaphs. For more than a century, it has been estimated that the United States' population had doubled during World War II to more than 9.6 million.

The Avignon Papacy was the period from 1309 to 1376 during which seven successive popes resided in Avignon ( then known as Burgundy), and one pope lived on each continent of Europe for at least a hundred years.The papacy continued in effect throughout history.Pope Gregory XIII (1511 – 1630) was the most recent pope, coming into existence in 1524. A descendant of Peter the Great, he had been converted to Christianity by his uncle, Louis-Philippe I, after being imprisoned in Jerusalem. Gregory was later canonized by Pope Clement VIII in 1582.

A solvent (from the Latin solvō, "loosen, untie, solve") is a substance that dissolves a solute, resulting in a solution. A solvent is usually a liquid but can also be a solid, a gas, or a supercritical fluid. Water is a solvent for polar molecules and the most common solvent used by living things; all the ions and proteins in a cell are dissolved in water within the cell.The quantity of solute that can dissolve in a specific volume of solvent varies with temperature. Major uses of solvents are in paints, paint removers, inks, dry cleaning.

A wide area network ( WAN ) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area . Wide area networks provide the capability for communications from multiple locations to receive data at various times, without congestion or delays. In many cases such a network is referred to as a virtual network. In computer engineering terms, communication is a process carried out using electrical and electronic signals to exchange information. It is generally defined as "a system of communications that consists of electrical or electronic signals sent between two or more points; they may be received in any number of different ways."

Columbia Business School (CBS) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in Manhattan, New York City. Established in 1916, Columbia Business School is one of six Ivy League business schools and is one of the oldest business schools in the world. In 2022, it was ranked as the 2nd best business school.History The school was founded in 1916 with 11 full-time faculty members and an inaugural class of 61 students, including 8 women. Banking executive Emerson McMillin provided initial funding in 1916, while A. Barton Hepburn, then president of Chase National Bank, provided funding for the School's endowment in 1919.

Dotdash Meredith ( formerly About.com ) is an American digital media company that publishes articles and videos about various subjects, such as politics, religion, technology, fashion, entertainment, culture, health and fitness, and even sports. She was founded in 2004 by four friends who came together as a group over a friendship-based idea for a site aimed at sharing personal stories. The Dandy Warhol Institute is an independent research organization established by artists and art critics to commemorate the life and work of Dutch surrealist painter Jeroen van der Walt (1874–1972).

Astrid Anna Emilia Lindgren ( ; ; 14 November 1907 – 28 January 2002 ) was a Swedish writer of children's books. She is generally regarded as one of the most influential children's writers of the 20th century, with widely-accepted works appearing in leading English-language publishers. Her stories have received critical praise from scholars, and she remains highly sought after to this day by her fan base, although the genre of children's books has come under significant pressure in recent years.Emilia became interested in fantasy fiction at a young age and went on to create a wide variety of child-themed characters.

The granny knot is a binding knot , used to secure a rope or line around an object . It is often the same knot with different sizes and shapes. These knots are sometimes made from twine or string. In the United States, the Granny's Knot is commonly referred to as either the "bobber knot", or simply the "granny knot". Gunslinger (  ,  ; German: ), also called the Grand Master Gunnery Officer of the Reich , is one of Hitler's chief military officers and one of the leading general officers of the army.

Reptilia is Canada's largest indoor reptile zoo, with  of indoor exhibits featuring over 250 reptiles, amphibians and arachnids. It is accredited by CAZA.Currently there are two Ontario locations, one in Vaughan and one in Whitby.LocationsThe original Reptilia zoo was established in Vaughan; it is housed in a  facility. In 2018, it opened a second location in Whitby in a former  Rona store. In late 2018, it announced plans to create similar zoos in London and Barrie. London City Council rejected the proposal for a  reptile zoo in Westmount Mall.AttractionsAbout 250 species of reptiles are in the zoo's collection.

Landslides, also known as landslips, are several forms of mass wasting that may include a wide range of ground movements, such as rockfalls, deep-seated slope failures, mudflows, and debris flows. Landslides occur in a variety of environments, characterized by either steep or gentle slope gradients, from mountain ranges to coastal cliffs or even underwater, in which case they are called submarine landslides. Gravity is the primary driving force for a landslide to occur, but there are other factors affecting slope stability that produce specific conditions that make a slope prone to failure.

See also History of UnitarianismA number of notable people have considered themselves Unitarians, Universalists, and following the merger of these denominations in the United States and Canada in 1961, Unitarian Universalists. Additionally, there are persons who, because of their writings or reputation, are considered to have held Unitarian or Universalist beliefs. Individuals who held unitarian (nontrinitarian) beliefs but were not affiliated with Unitarian organizations are often referred to as "small 'u unitarians. The same principle can be applied to those who believed in universal salvation but were not members of Universalist organizations.

Poznań University of Technology, PUT (Polish name: Politechnika Poznańska) is a university in Poznań, Poland. Poznań University of Technology is known as one of the best technical universities in Poland. URAP ranked PUT as in top 6% of world universities and Webometrics ranked it at no. 842 in the world by Google citations for the year 2015. In 1995 it became the first Polish university to become a member of the Conference of European Schools for Advanced Engineering Education and Research (CESAER), an organization comprising the best technical universities in Europe.

Liberation theology is a Christian theological approach emphasizing the liberation of the oppressed. In certain contexts, it engages socio-economic analyses, with "social concern for the poor and political liberation for oppressed peoples." In other contexts, it addresses other forms of inequality, such as race or caste.Liberation theology is best known in the Latin American context, especially within Catholicism in the 1960s after the Second Vatican Council, where it became the political praxis of theologians such as Gustavo Gutiérrez, Leonardo Boff, and Jesuits Juan Luis Segundo and Jon Sobrino, who popularized the phrase "preferential option for the poor".

Paweł Jasienica was the pen name of Leon Lech Beynar (10 November 1909 – 19 August 1970), a Polish historian, journalist, essayist and soldier.During World War II, Jasienica (then, Leon Beynar) fought in the Polish Army, and later, the Home Army resistance. Near the end of the war, he was also working with the anti-Soviet resistance, which later led to him taking up a new name, Paweł Jasienica, to hide from the communist government of the People's Republic of Poland. He was associated with the Tygodnik Powszechny weekly and several other newspapers and magazines.

A tremor is an involuntary, somewhat rhythmic, muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one or more body parts. It is the most common of all involuntary movements and can affect the hands, arms, eyes, face, head, vocal folds, trunk, and legs. Most tremors occur in the hands. In some people, a tremor is a symptom of another neurological disorder. A very common tremor is the teeth chattering, usually induced by cold temperatures or by fear.TypesTremor is most commonly classified by clinical features and cause or origin.

Blake Edwards ( born William Blake Crump ; July 26 , 1922 – December 15 , 2010 ) was an American actress and singer who first gained prominence in children's films. She became a prominent star in the mid-1960s by appearing in such films as The Wonderful World of Little Red Riding Hood, My Fair Lady, The Wizard of Oz, and Aladdin. This article is a disambiguation page; for more information on what an article means, click here. For the name of a movie in the franchise, see James Bond 007 (movie franchise).

The Permanent Court of Arbitration ( PCA ) is a non-UN intergovernmental organization located in The Hague , Netherlands . It was created to settle disputes arising from the United Nations, as well as other bodies such as the European Union and the International Criminal Court.PCA was formed on August 4, 2001, at the recommendation of the UN Security Council, which called upon member states for their shared understanding of the law of armed conflict. The Palmetto State  is a state in South Carolina that is home to the largest metropolitan area with a population of over 300,000 people, situated in one of the most populous urban areas in the world.

Lingerie ( , , ) is a category of primarily women 's clothing including undergarments ( mainly brassieres ) , lingerie, pajamas, slippers, nighties, knickers, gaffs, panties, shoes, handbags, scarves, and so on. The word derives from the Latin leorica, which was also used as a catchphrase for women's clothing. In English, "leanna" is a masculine form of the name; however, in some other languages, leorica may mean "blessed", referring to her miraculous nature or the fact that she was blessed with divine power.

The Ante-Nicene Fathers, subtitled "The Writings of the Fathers Down to A.D. 325", is a collection of books in 10 volumes (one volume is indexes) containing English translations of the majority of Early Christian writings. The period covers the beginning of Christianity until the promulgation of the Nicene Creed at the First Council of Nicaea.PublicationThe series was originally published between 1867 and 1873 by the Presbyterian publishing house T. & T. Clark in Edinburgh under the title Ante-Nicene Christian Library (ANCL), as a response to the Oxford movement's Library of the Fathers which was perceived as too strongly identified with the Anglo-Catholic movement.

A think tank, or policy institute, is a research institute that performs research and advocacy concerning topics such as social policy, political strategy, economics, military, technology, and culture. Most think tanks are non-governmental organizations, but some are semi-autonomous agencies within government or are associated with particular political parties, businesses or the military. Think-tank funding often includes a combination of donations from wealthy individuals and personal contributions, with many also accepting government grants.Think tanks publish articles, studies or even draft legislation on particular matters of policy or society.

Lewiston is a city and the county seat of Nez Perce County , Idaho , United States , in the State of Idaho. It was named after Joseph W. Nezper (November 24, 1833 – December 19, 1919), an American-born Norwegian explorer who visited the area at the invitation of William Donald Ross, U.S. Ambassador to Norway.It is a small town located about 60 miles (105 km) south-southwest of Boise, Idaho, on the northern boundary of the Cascade Mountains. It has historically been regarded as one of the best preserved towns in the United States.

Radiohead are an English rock band formed in Abingdon , Oxfordshire , in 1985 . The band consists of Thom Yorke (vocals), Nigel Godrich (guitar), Jonny Greenwood (percussion), and Nick James (keys) and was nominated for a Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance at the 1994 Academy Awards for "Fairytale Kingdom. "The group has released seven studio albums (including 1988's Ænima, 1993's No Surprises, 1996's A Moon Shaped Pool, 1999's Bad Moon Rising, and 2010's King of Limbs).

Dorset ( ; archaically : Dorsetshire ) is a county in South West England on the English Channel coast . Its geographic position is north of the River Derwent and north-east of the English Channel. It is also part of the Greater London Regional Council . The county was granted its current title from the Treaty of Woden in 1452, which included all of what is now the United Kingdom under the rule of Edward II, Duke of Northumberland, King of Scotland and Prince Albert of Prussia.Cities and towns in Dorset have traditionally been identified by their proximity to the English Channel.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572) was a Scottish minister, Reformed theologian, and writer who was a leader of the country's Reformation. He was the founder of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.Born in Giffordgate, a street in Haddington, East Lothian, Knox is believed to have been educated at the University of St Andrews and worked as a notary-priest. Influenced by early church reformers such as George Wishart, he joined the movement to reform the Scottish church. He was caught up in the ecclesiastical and political events that involved the murder of Cardinal David Beaton in 1546 and the intervention of the regent Mary of Guise.

A terrarium ( plural : terraria or terrariums ) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants , typically enclosed by a top cover. It also serves as a container for animals that do not wish to stay inside. The terrarium may consist of a flat bottomed pot with a rim in which plants grow. Plants are held in front of the terrarium's edge to prevent their growth from falling into the air, which would result in an uneven distribution of food. Terrariums are known for being very efficient in retaining moisture, due in part to their shape.

The AGM-114 Hellfire ( AGM stands for air-to-ground missile ) is an air-to-surface missile ( ASM ) first developed for the Soviet strategic bomber MiG-29. It is designed as a fast and effective tactical air-to-air missile which can fire its primary and secondary weapon independently at different targets. The American Civil Liberties Union has argued, on numerous occasions, against the use of search warrant provisions in many federal court orders involving national security matters.In one such case, the ACLU sought to prevent the issuance of a search warrant that allowed authorities to read e-mails belonging to Edward Snowden.

Bread is a staple food prepared from a dough of flour ( usually wheat ) and water , usually by boiling in a pot until it becomes a clear liquid . It can be used as an ingredient in most recipes, although not as often. Etymology [ edit ]
Etymology 1 [ edit ]
There are several theories to answer this question; however, the three main theories are listed below. One explanation is that bread was originally a fermented substance made up of yeast and various other plant materials. The other two explain the creation of the word "bread."

Hugh John Lofting (14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947) was an English author trained as a civil engineer, who created the classic children's literature character of Doctor Dolittle. It first appeared in illustrated letters to his children written by Lofting from the British Army trenches in the First World War.Personal lifeLofting, born in January 1886 in Maidenhead, Berkshire, to Elizabeth Agnes (Gannon) and John Brien Lofting, was of English and Irish ancestry. His eldest brother, Hilary Lofting, later became a novelist in Australia, having emigrated there in 1915.Lofting was educated at Mount St Mary's College in Spinkhill, Derbyshire.

Year 1036 ( MXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday. It marks the end of an era for the Catholic Church: since the death of Pope Leo I in 647, the Holy See has never had a pope, and the Church has lost most of her pre-Roman influence. The United Nations ( UN ), also known as the Organization of American States, U.N., is the principal United Nations agency tasked with overseeing the activities of all 193 member states.

Giovanni Paisiello (or Paesiello; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816) was an Italian composer of the Classical era, and was the most popular opera composer of the late 1700s. His operatic style influenced Mozart and Rossini, and his music was championed by Haydn and Beethoven.LifePaisiello was born in Taranto in the Apulia region and educated by the Jesuits there. He became known for his beautiful singing voice and in 1754 was sent to the Conservatorio di S. Onofrio at Naples, where he studied under Francesco Durante, and eventually became assistant master.

Carnival is a Western Christian festive season that occurs before the liturgical season of Lent . The main events typically take place on December 21, 22, and 23 in the city of San José de Caracas, Venezuela or in another city with similar population.A Carnival holiday is held on February 1st every year. It is a period of intense festivities for all the major family and community holidays, including the harvest festivals (Míxico), Christmas, Easter, New Year's Day, and Good Friday.There are several ways to celebrate carnival; each has their pros and cons.

Bi-curious is a term for a person, usually someone who is a heterosexual, who is curious or open about engaging in sexual activity with a person whose sex differs from that of their usual sexual partners. The term is sometimes used to describe a broad continuum of sexual orientation between heterosexuality and bisexuality. Such continuums include mostly-heterosexual or mostly-homosexual, but these can be self-identified without identifying as bisexual. The terms heteroflexible and homoflexible are mainly applied to bi-curious people, though some authors distinguish heteroflexibility and homoflexibility as lacking the "wish to experiment with sexuality" implied by the bi-curious label.

Jobst of Moravia ( or Jošt Lucemburský;  or Jodokus von Mähren; c. 1354 – 18 January 1411), a member of the House of Luxembourg, was Margrave of Moravia from 1375, Duke of Luxembourg and Elector of Brandenburg from 1388 as well as elected King of Germany (King of the Romans) from 1410 until his death. Jobst was an ambitious and versatile ruler, who in the early 15th century dominated the ongoing struggles within the Luxembourg dynasty and around the German throne.Life Jobst was presumably born in 1354 in the Moravian residence of Brno, the eldest legitimate son of Margrave John Henry, younger brother of Emperor Charles IV.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman ( born 19 October 1946 ) is an English writer . His books include the novels, A Clockwork Orange (2001), It Follows (2004), and My Name is Earl.He is also a regular commentator on radio shows such as The Today Programme, BBC Two's Today Show, Radio 5 Live, Sky News and BBC Three's Today programme.The author was born out of poverty in Essex but moved to London when he was six. He received a Master of Arts degree in English at the Royal University of London School of Literature in 1993.

Plotinus (; , Plōtînos;  – 270 CE) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition, born and raised in Roman Egypt. Plotinus is regarded by modern scholarship as the founder of Neoplatonism. His teacher was the self-taught philosopher Ammonius Saccas, who belonged to the Platonic tradition. Historians of the 19th century invented the term "Neoplatonism" and applied it to refer to Plotinus and his philosophy, which was vastly influential during Late Antiquity, the Middle Ages, and the Renaissance. Much of the biographical information about Plotinus comes from Porphyry's preface to his edition of Plotinus' most notable literary work, The Enneads.

Wind tunnels are large tubes with air blowing through them which are used to replicate the interaction between air and stone. These tubes, in an ideal situation, would provide the same pressure as the ground, providing a sense of stability for the tunnel and allowing it to pass through even the most turbulent conditions. However, they produce a substantial amount of noise and require considerable maintenance. Nanotubes, also known as  , are a type of semiconductors made from silicon-molybdenum nitride (Si 2 MnO 3 ) nanotubes. They are widely used as electronic sensors and transistors and have wide application including microprocessors, solar cells and lasers.

Theories of political behavior, as an aspect of political science, attempt to quantify and explain the influences that define a person's political views, ideology, and levels of political participation. Political behavior is the subset of human behavior that involves politics and power. Theorists who have had an influence on this field include Karl Deutsch and Theodor Adorno.Long-term influences on political orientationInteraction with the political views of parental figures is often thought of as the primary long-term influence on political orientation and willingness to take part in the political system.Teachers and other educational authority figures are also often thought to have a significant impact on political orientation.

Fighting Fantasy is a series of single-player role-playing gamebooks created by Steve Jackson and Ian Livingstone. The first volume in the series was published in paperback by Puffin in 1982.The series distinguished itself by mixing Choose Your Own Adventure-style storytelling with a dice-based role-playing element included within the books themselves. The caption on many of the covers claimed each title was an adventure "in which YOU are the hero!" The majority of the titles followed a fantasy theme, although science fiction, post-apocalyptic, superhero, and modern horror gamebooks were also published.

While a significant majority of water vessels are powered by diesel engines , with sail power and gasoline engines also capable, ships of the first type typically had to use electricity for propulsion. The largest of these vessels, the Albatros, was constructed between 1530 and 1625 in Castille, Spain. An individual is one who occupies an office or position of responsibility, such as a manager, director, assistant, secretary, sales representative, stockholder, teacher, etc., in a profession, business, corporation, or other organization (e.g., bank).

Year 952 (CMLII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>By placeEurope  Summer – At the Reichstag in Augsburg (assembled by King Otto I), joined by German nobles and bishops, Berengar of Ivrea pays homage. He becomes a vassal of the East Frankish Kingdom. Otto leaves a strong garrison at Pavia in the hands of his son-in-law Conrad the Red, duke of Lotharingia.Scotland  King Constantine II dies at the monastery of St. Andrews (where he has been retired since 943).

Lieutenant General Henry Shrapnel (3 June 1761 – 13 March 1842) was a British Army officer whose name has entered the English language as the inventor of the shrapnel shell.Henry Shrapnel was born at Midway Manor in Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, the ninth child of Zachariah Shrapnel and his wife Lydia.In 1784, while a lieutenant in the Royal Artillery, he perfected, with his own resources, an invention of what he called "spherical case" ammunition: a hollow cannonball filled with lead shot that burst in mid-air. He successfully demonstrated this in 1787 at Gibraltar.

The pancreas is an organ of the digestive system and endocrine system of vertebrates. In humans, it is located in the abdomen behind the stomach and functions as a gland. The pancreas is a mixed or heterocrine gland, i.e. it has both an endocrine and a digestive exocrine function. 99% of the pancreas is exocrine and 1% is endocrine. As an endocrine gland, it functions mostly to regulate blood sugar levels, secreting the hormones insulin, glucagon, somatostatin, and pancreatic polypeptide. As a part of the digestive system, it functions as an exocrine gland secreting pancreatic juice into the duodenum through the pancreatic duct.

Pali is a Middle Indo-Aryan liturgical language native to the Indian subcontinent . It is widely studied because it is used by Muslims, Hindus and Bahujan Puranas.It is an archaic language spoken in India, Tibet, Nepal, Bhutan, Pakistan, Myanmar, Indonesia, China, Korea, Laos, Vietnam, and Taiwan.Its  is composed of several consonants, some pronounced differently, that are different than vowels, but also contain two phonemes.In Sanskrit, kṣṭān means "whole", as in "this is my whole being". Nigeria (  Nganjawa ) is a country in north-eastern Nigeria located on the Niger delta between Chad and Cameroon.

Year 874 (DCCCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Salomon, duke ('king') of Brittany, is murdered by a faction which includes his son-in-law Pascweten and Gurvand, son-in-law of late ruler Erispoe. After Salomon's death they divide the country, and Pascweten and Gurvand co-rule Brittany. Svatopluk I, ruler (knyaz) of Great Moravia, concludes a peace treaty at Forchheim (Northern Bavaria). He is able to expand his territories outside the Frankish sphere, and subjugates the Vistulans.Kirschbaum 2007, p. 121.

The history of Burgundy stretches back to the times when the region was inhabited in turn by Celts , Romans and Lombards from the seventh to the mid-second century. After the collapse of the Sassanian Empire in the 9th century, Burgundy retained its independence under the French crown for nearly 400 years. In the 19th century, the Burgundians' economic power became the envy of all other Italian states, especially Austria and Italy. Béziers, also known simply as Belgium, is one of Europe's oldest city centers and has a well-known architectural history stretching back over several centuries.

Courtesan, in modern usage, is a euphemism for a "kept" mistress or prostitute, particularly one with wealthy, powerful, or influential clients. The term historically referred to a courtier, a person who attended the court of a monarch or other powerful person.History In European feudal society, the court was the centre of government as well as the residence of the monarch, and social and political life were often completely mixed together. Prior to the Renaissance, courtesans served to convey information to visiting dignitaries, when servants could not be trusted. In Renaissance Europe, courtiers played an extremely important role in upper-class society.

Casimir Jagiellon ( ; ; ; 3 October 1458 – 4 March 1484 ) was a prince of the Kingdom of Croatia, and king of Croatia, Serbia, Montenegro, Bulgaria, and Croatia. He served as regent from 1463 to 1477. He was considered to be one of Europe's foremost thinkers and statesman. During his rule, he established the foundation of what would become the modern republic of Croatia with the incorporation of Croatia into the Roman Empire in 1482. Jade is an object-oriented programming language made by Microsoft for the 32-bit Windows Operating System. It uses the .NET Framework.

The red slender loris (Loris tardigradus) is a small, nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of Sri Lanka. This is No. 6 of the 10 focal species and No. 22 of the 100 EDGE mammal species worldwide considered the most evolutionarily distinct and globally endangered. Two subspecies have been identified, L. t. tardigradus and L. t. nycticeboides.Taxonomy Genus Loris Red slender loris, Loris tardigradus Horton Plains slender loris or mountain loris, Loris tardigradus nycticeboides Dry zone slender loris or lowland loris, Loris tardigradus tardigradus Gray slender loris, Loris lydekkerianusThe ears are less prominent in Loris tardigradus tardigradus compared to Loris lydekkerianus.

A software bug is an error, flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect or unexpected result, or to behave in unintended ways. The process of finding and correcting bugs is termed "debugging" and often uses formal techniques or tools to pinpoint bugs. Since the 1950s some computer systems have been designed to deter, detect or auto-correct various computer bugs during operations.Most bugs arise from mistakes and errors made in either a program's design or its source code, or in components and operating systems used by such programs.

The word comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script , which were made a major part of the official language of China for many decades before being abandoned after the Great Leap Forward in the late 1980s. The character was eventually replaced by a more common one, the Chinese character for "one"; and it is used in English, German, Italian, French, Hebrew, Russian, Spanish, Swahili, Dutch, Swedish, Portuguese (Brazilian), Turkish, Norwegian, and other Asian languages.

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico ( tragic opera ) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti . It was written in 1824, and performed by Giacomo Gabbana in 1834. The work became a major hit of the period, winning him two Emmys as best picture winner in 1847.The plot takes place in a modern day Paris, which is at the centre of a French Revolution. The revolution is led by François-Joseph Czélény, a Catholic priest who leads an uprising against the authorities. His supporters include the republican Marquis de Lafayette, but Czélény's enemies include the Protestant king Louis-Philippe d'Argot.

Casimir Jagiellon (; ; ; 3 October 1458 – 4 March 1484) was a prince of the Kingdom of Poland and of the Grand Duchy of Lithuania. Second son of King Casimir IV Jagiellon, he was tutored by Johannes Longinus, a Polish chronicler and diplomat. After his elder brother Vladislaus was elected as King of Bohemia in 1471, Casimir became the heir apparent. At the age of 13, Casimir participated in the failed military campaign to install him as King of Hungary. He became known for his piety, devotion to God, and generosity towards the sick and poor.

The Bell OH-58 Kiowa is a family of single-engine , single-rotor , military helicopters used for observation , utility , and disaster relief services. These aircraft first appeared in World War II during Operation Market Garden (1942–45), and began service with the United States Air Force between May 1944 and April 1945. After the war, they served as an important component of the US Navy's amphibious assault fleet from early in the Korean War until the Vietnam War. Barack Obama has been the President of the United States of America since January 20, 2009, following his inauguration as President of the United States on January 20, 2009.

The Who are an English rock band formed in London in 1964 . Their classic lineup consisted of lead singer John Darnielle, guitarist Nick Mason and keyboardist Brian May; they won four Grammy Awards including best rock act. They have received many nominations and awards for their music.Darnielle became the youngest member of the group in 1968 when he was twenty-four years old. However, it was before that time that David Bowie was a regular performer at the shows, although he was not a frequent guest. John Lennon is a British American songwriter, musician, producer, poet, essayist, director, activist, humanitarian, and author.

Aden ( ,  ;   Yemeni: ) is a city, and since 2015, the temporary capital of Yemen, near the eastern approach to the Red Sea (the Gulf of Aden), some  east of the strait Bab-el-Mandeb. Its population is approximately 800,000 people. Aden's natural harbour lies in the crater of a dormant volcano, which now forms a peninsula joined to the mainland by a low isthmus. This harbour, Front Bay, was first used by the ancient Kingdom of Awsan between the 7th to 5th centuries BC. The modern harbour is on the other side of the peninsula.

A monopropellant rocket ( or `` monochemical rocket '' ) is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its propellant. A monopropellant engine has two main elements, one an oxidizer called a "burning gas" that is used in the first stage, and a fuel called a "fuel pellet" that contains both oxygen and water to accelerate the second stage. The propellant does not have a specific ignition temperature and can burn only when the burning gas is heated. It also has limited range due to its low mass.Mushrooms are considered mushrooms by the medical profession; most studies show they do not resemble other mushrooms.

The Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk is a high-altitude , remotely-piloted surveillance aircraft . It was initially designed by Ryan Northrop and developed by U.S. Air Force contractors Lockheed Martin and McDonnell Douglas, with the assistance of South Africa's Civil Aerospace Development Organization (CADO) as well as indigenous development work by South Africa's Defense Research Agency (DRDO). A second version of the aircraft was proposed by the United States in the late 1980s. Although this article or section does not meet the standards of the IWM, it is usable as a general reference for the purposes of research.

The First Book of Nephi: His Reign and Ministry , usually referred to as First Nephi or 1 Nephi, is the first book of the Book of Mormon and one of four books with the name Nephi. The original translation of the title did not include the word "first". First and Second were added to the titles of the Books of Nephi by Oliver Cowdery when preparing the book for printing. It is a first-person narrative by a prophet named Nephi, of events that began around 600 BC and recorded on the small plates of Nephi approximately 30 years later.

Footwear refers to garments worn on the feet, which typically serves the purpose of protection against adversities of the environment such as wear from ground textures and temperature. Footwear in the manner of shoes therefore primarily serves the purpose to ease locomotion and prevent injuries. Footwear can also be used for fashion and adornment as well as to indicate the status or rank of the person within a social structure. Socks and other hosiery are typically worn additionally between the feet and other footwear for further comfort and relief.Cultures have different customs regarding footwear. These include not using any in some situations, usually bearing a symbolic meaning.

Larry Simon Gelbart (February 25, 1928 – September 11, 2009) was an American television writer, playwright, screenwriter, director and author, most famous as a creator and producer of the television series M*A*S*H, and as co-writer of the Broadway musicals A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum and City of Angels.BiographyEarly lifeGelbart was born in Chicago, Illinois, to Jewish immigrants Harry Gelbart, "a barber since his half of a childhood in Latvia," and Frieda Sturner, who migrated to America from Dąbrowa Górnicza, Poland.

A verb  is a word (part of speech) that in syntax conveys an action (bring, read, walk, run, learn), an occurrence (happen, become), or a state of being (be, exist, stand). In the usual description of English, the basic form, with or without the particle to, is the infinitive. In many languages, verbs are inflected (modified in form) to encode tense, aspect, mood, and voice. A verb may also agree with the person, gender or number of some of its arguments, such as its subject, or object.

The National Guard is a state-based military force that becomes part of the reserve components of the United States Army. A National Guard regiment consists of one or more regiments divided into Regular, Reserve, Overseas, and Special Duty units.In its early history, the National Guard was a voluntary service, though some branches had begun to use compulsory service during World War II. An artificial intelligence is a computer program that has sophisticated human-like mental capabilities but little knowledge of the environment and natural processes. Such programs are capable of making complex decisions and reasoning about information in an objective manner, and can even be trained to perform many tasks.

David is a masterpiece of Renaissance sculpture , created in marble between 1501 and 1504 by the Italian artist Michelangelo. The work, which also bears the title "Conception of David", became known as one of the most famous modern masterpieces in art history, and is regarded by some as the greatest representation of human dignity ever created.The work has received widespread acclaim from artists worldwide, including the Academy of Fine Arts, Los Angeles County Museum of Art, Paris Museum de l'Atelier D'Art Moderne et de la Vie, New York Metropolitan Museum of Art, and the Sculpture Centre of Italy, where the works were later displayed.

Theodoret of Cyrus or Cyrrhus (;  AD 393 –  458/466) was an influential theologian of the School of Antioch, biblical commentator, and Christian bishop of Cyrrhus (423–457). He played a pivotal role in several 5th-century Byzantine Church controversies that led to various ecumenical acts and schisms. He wrote against Cyril of Alexandria's 12 Anathemas which were sent to Nestorius and did not personally condemn Nestorius until the Council of Chalcedon. His writings against Cyril were included in the Three Chapters Controversy and were condemned at the Second Council of Constantinople.

was the 70th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Reizei 's reign spanned the years 1045–1068.This was his longest reign, spanning more than 300 years. In his later years, he consolidated his position as the head of the most powerful dynasty in Japan and had a major influence over the course of Japanese political and economic history. Friedrich Reitsch (  ), also known as Ludwig Friedrich Reitsch (  ), was a Bavarian scientist, mathematician and geographer who was born in Munich on August 17, 1812. Reitsch is generally recognized as the father of topology and other algebraic theory.

Blake Edwards (born William Blake Crump; July 26, 1922 – December 15, 2010) was an American actor, film director, producer and screenwriter.Edwards began his career in the 1940s as an actor, but he soon began writing screenplays and radio scripts before turning to producing and directing in television and films. His best-known films include Breakfast at Tiffany's, Days of Wine and Roses, 10, Victor/Victoria, and the hugely successful Pink Panther film series with British actor Peter Sellers. Often thought of as primarily a director of comedies, he also directed several drama, musical, and detective films.

North America's first transcontinental railroad (known originally as the "Pacific Railroad" and later as the "Overland Route") was a  continuous railroad line constructed between 1863 and 1869 that connected the existing eastern U.S. rail network at Council Bluffs, Iowa with the Pacific coast at the Oakland Long Wharf on San Francisco Bay. The rail line was built by three private companies over public lands provided by extensive US land grants. Construction was financed by both state and US government subsidy bonds as well as by company issued mortgage bonds.

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China, Japan, Korea, and Mongolia from prehistoric times to the present. East Asia is not a uniform term and each of its countries has a different national history, but scholars maintain that the region is also characterized by a distinct pattern of historical development. This is evident in the interrelationship among East Asian countries, which not only involve the sum total of historical patterns but also a specific set of patterns that has affected all or most of East Asia in successive layers.

The Battle of Lechfeld was a series of military engagements over the course of three days from 10–12 August 955, which saw an initial wave of Russian forces defeated and forced to retreat. Gardaí are the law enforcement officers who deal with complaints about serious crimes against persons in the Gardaí unit. In particular, they may deal with any complaint about sexual assault or domestic violence. Their role is particularly important during the Christmas period, as it is the peak of the Christmas season. Gardaí should report any suspected crime to their own units, provided that this does not result in their being sent to the gardaí for questioning.

Dementia manifests as a set of related symptoms, which usually surface when the brain is damaged by injury or disease. The symptoms involve progressive impairments in memory, thinking, and behavior, which negatively impact a person's ability to function and carry out everyday activities. Aside from memory impairment and a disruption in thought patterns, the most common symptoms include emotional problems, difficulties with language, and decreased motivation. The symptoms may be described as occurring in a continuum over several stages. Consciousness is not affected. Dementia ultimately has a significant effect on the individual, caregivers, and relationships in general.

Belarusians , also known formerly as Byelorussians ( from the Byelorussian SSR ) , Belarussians or Belorusians , are an ethnic group of eastern Belarusian-speaking ethnic minorities who make up the majority of the country's inhabitants. They are mostly concentrated in the province of Kemerovo near the Russian border. Karelia is a region bordering Russia and the former Soviet Union located to the north and east of Kazakhstan in Russia's Caspian Sea. It comprises three regions – the South Caucasus, the North Caucasus and Kazakstan. In total, it is divided into four main regions – Khakassia, Ingushetia, Karachai and Dagestan.

Magma  is the molten or semi-molten natural material from which all igneous rocks are formed. Magma is found beneath the surface of the Earth, and evidence of magmatism has also been discovered on other terrestrial planets and some natural satellites. Besides molten rock, magma may also contain suspended crystals and gas bubbles.Magma is produced by melting of the mantle or the crust in various tectonic settings, which on Earth include subduction zones, continental rift zones, mid-ocean ridges and hotspots. Mantle and crustal melts migrate upwards through the crust where they are thought to be stored in magma chambers or trans-crustal crystal-rich mush zones.

Los Alamos National Laboratory ( often shortened as Los Alamos and LANL ) is a United States Department of Energy (DOE) research institute, focused on nuclear physics. It was officially established in 1946 by the DOE's Office of Scientific Research, which had long been operating at the Los Alamos National Laboratory (or LANL), home to some of the most important military nuclear facilities in the country. Married couples have been forbidden from marrying since 1892, but in the case of two unmarried persons under age 21, it has not been legal for that person to marry until he or she turns 18 years of age.

Domenico Gaetano Maria Donizetti (29 November 1797 – 8 April 1848) was an Italian composer, best known for his almost 70 operas. Along with Gioachino Rossini and Vincenzo Bellini, he was a leading composer of the bel canto opera style during the first half of the nineteenth century and a probable influence on other composers such as Giuseppe Verdi. Donizetti was born in Bergamo in Lombardy. At an early age he was taken up by Simon Mayr who enrolled him with a full scholarship in a school which he had set up. There he received detailed musical training.

Delhi (;  Dillī;  Dillī;  Dêhlī), officially the National Capital Territory (NCT) of Delhi, is a city and a union territory of India containing New Delhi, the capital of India. Straddling the Yamuna river, but primarily its western or right bank, Delhi shares borders with the state of Uttar Pradesh in the east and with the state of Haryana in the remaining directions. The NCT covers an area of . According to the 2011 census, Delhi's city proper population was over 11 million, while the NCT's population was about 16.8 million.

The Battle of Lechfeld was a series of military engagements over the course of three days from 10–12 August 955 in which the Kingdom of Germany led by king Otto I the Great annihilated the Hungarian army led by harka Bulcsú and the chieftains Lél and Súr. With this German victory further invasions by the Magyars into Latin Europe were ended.The Hungarians invaded the Duchy of Bavaria in late June or early July 955 with 8,000–10,000 horse archers, infantry, and siege engines, intending to draw the main German army under Otto I into battle in the open field and destroy it.

The boa knot is a modern  binding knot invented by weaver Peter Collingwood in 1996. His intention was to develop a knot that would hold well when the constricted object was cut close to the winds of the knot.The boa knot is related to the strangle knot and the double constrictor knot. It combines both the structure and qualities of these other two knots. The boa knot can be very difficult to untie and is inappropriate when frequent or fast untying is needed. The knotted part needs to lie over a convex surface to hold.Start with making two loops that spiral upwards in a clockwise manner.

Depleted uranium (DU; also referred to in the past as Q-metal, depletalloy or D-38) is uranium with a lower content of the fissile isotope  than natural uranium. Natural uranium contains about  , while the DU used by the U.S. Department of Defense contains   or less. The less radioactive and non-fissile  constitutes the main component of depleted uranium. Uses of DU take advantage of its very high density of   ( denser than lead).Civilian uses include counterweights in aircraft, radiation shielding in medical radiation therapy and industrial radiography equipment, and containers for transporting radioactive materials.

Palm OS (also known as Garnet OS) is a discontinued mobile operating system initially developed by Palm, Inc., for personal digital assistants (PDAs) in 1996. Palm OS was designed for ease of use with a touchscreen-based graphical user interface. It is provided with a suite of basic applications for personal information management. Later versions of the OS have been extended to support smartphones. Several other licensees have manufactured devices powered by Palm OS.Following Palm's purchase of the Palm trademark, the currently licensed version from ACCESS was renamed Garnet OS.

Malayalam (; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé district) by the Malayali people. It is one of 22 scheduled languages of India and is spoken by 2.88% of Indians. Malayalam has official language status in Kerala, Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé), and is spoken by 34 million people worldwide. Malayalam is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the neighbouring states; with significant number of speakers in the Kodagu and Dakshina Kannada districts of Karnataka, and Nilgiris and Kanyakumari, districts of Tamil Nadu.

Sir Robert Alexander Watson Watt  (13 April 1892 – 5 December 1973) was a British pioneer of radio direction finding and radar technology.Watt began his career in radio physics with a job at the Met Office, where he began looking for accurate ways to track thunderstorms using the radio signals given off by lightning. This led to the 1920s development of a system later known as high-frequency direction finding (HFDF or "huff-duff"). Although well publicized at the time, the system's enormous military potential was not developed until the late 1930s.

Yucatán (, also , , ;  ), officially the Free and Sovereign State of Yucatán, is one of the 32 states which comprise the Federal Entities of Mexico. It is divided into 106 municipalities, and its capital city is Mérida.It is located on the north part of the Yucatán Peninsula. It is bordered by the states of Campeche to the southwest and Quintana Roo to the southeast, with the Gulf of Mexico off its north coast.Before the arrival of Spaniards to the Yucatán Peninsula, the name of this region was Mayab.

The Alcubierre drive, Alcubierre warp drive, or Alcubierre metric (referring to metric tensor), is a speculative warp drive idea based on a solution of Einstein's field equations in general relativity as proposed by theoretical physicist Miguel Alcubierre during his PhD study at the University of Wales, Cardiff, by which a spacecraft could achieve apparent faster-than-light travel if a configurable energy-density field lower than that of vacuum (that is, negative mass) could be created.Rather than exceeding the speed of light within a local reference frame, a spacecraft would traverse distances by contracting space in front of it and expanding space behind it, resulting in effective faster-than-light travel.

Paclitaxel ( PTX ) , sold under the brand name Taxol among others , is a chemotherapy medication used to treat certain forms of non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) is a natural chemical constituent of cannabis, a plant that contains two compounds, the main active psychoactive substance, tetrahydrocannabivarin (THCV), which acts as an agonist for the serotonin receptor (5-HT1A), and cannabidiol (CBD), a compound that acts as a potent antinociceptive agent. The Tetrahydrocannabinoline Receptor (TFR), formerly called cannabinoid receptor type 2 (CB2) or CB1/CB2, is a transmembrane protein located primarily within the cell membrane.

Patch collecting or badge collecting ( also , scutelliphily , from Latin scutellus meaning little shield , and Greek phileein to make one). Sculpture is the use of human-made objects to create a particular visual effect, including architecture, sculpture, painting, engineering, literature, art history, fashion, design, film, television, radio, printmaking, graphic arts, and musical composition.Sculpture is most often represented by human hands, but has historically included other forms such as stone, wood, plaster, glass, metal, and plastic. It may also include animal shapes, figurative elements, metals, and minerals.

Henry Dunant ( born Jean-Henri Dunant ; 8 May 182830 October 1910 ) , also known as Henri Dunant , was an English journalist and broadcaster who died in January 2005. He made his television debut on The News of the World in 1952.He is best remembered for covering the Great Depression, but he also covered world war II and the civil rights movement from the early 1960s up until his death.In the 1970s, he began to co-produce BBC Two documentaries with Richard Attenborough and Peter Mandelson, which helped him attract a large audience.A lifelong member of the Labour Party, he was associated with the organisation during the general election of 1977.

Gossypium is a genus of flowering plants in the tribe Gossypieae of the mallow family , Malvaceae , from which many other gossypies (also known as red gossypiens) are derived. It occurs mostly in the southern part of the continent, especially in the dry forests of southern Russia. It has been classified as a species within the phylum Cymbopogonum and subgenus Pygophaga , but these names refer to different groups of the genus, and may refer to different species altogether. The plant was first described for its leaves in 1755 by Johann Albrechtsen.

Sparta ( Doric Greek : Σπάρτα , Spártā ; Attic Greek : Σπάρτη , Spártē ) was a prominent city-state of the eastern Roman empire and a strategic point for the Mediterranean trade route. It was also the seat of the First Punic War, during which Hannibal's army destroyed Rome and the Roman province of Cisalpine Gaul, thus establishing Carthage as the dominant military power in Central Africa.The city itself consisted of a series of fortresses around the base of the mountains, surrounded by an enclosed hillside. Hippolytus is considered to have discovered the doctrine of Epicureanism before Aristotle.

Year 959 ( CMLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the reign of King Philip II of Macedon. On March 11, 2009, it was discovered that an asteroid had just passed close by and struck the planet Jupiter. Astronomer Tom Szilard estimated that the impact caused over 1,000 times the force of the Earth's gravity to destroy nearly all landforms on the planet. [1] As a result, the largest object ever in orbit around this planet is classified as a "super-asteroid".

The Australian Secret Intelligence Service ( ASIS ) is the foreign intelligence agency of Australia , tasked with the covert action and counter-espionage activities of the Australian Defence Force. Its objective is to counter the activities of foreign powers or their proxies.ASIS is charged with conducting covert operations for the Commonwealth, its overseas allies, and other international actors. The agency also undertakes research, analysis, and training in these fields. Ashton has been described as one of the three most influential jazz musicians of the twentieth century, and he is best remembered for composing the first major rock anthem, "I Want You To Know," in 1933.

Hildegard Frieda Albertine Knef ( ; 28 December 19251 February 2002 ) was a German actress , voice actress , producer, and writer. Born to a wealthy family in Vienna, she came from a small village and received an early education at the age of seven. Her earliest films show her as a lively young girl with a flair for music and theatre. After school, she performed in numerous theatrical performances. Daphne Caruana Maximilian I ( ; 27 January 1897 – 14 March 1918) was an Austrian-born author of short stories, short story collections, children's plays, historical romances, novels, poetry, and plays.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration ( NOAA ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States government that is responsible for managing and operating the national marine environment. I am very sorry to have to say this but it is time for some real work. I will be writing more about this on Monday morning, but first a bit of background on what's going on at the moment. There is a new administration in the White House, led by a man named Mike Pence, who is quite a political outsider compared to his predecessors.

Alkanna tinctoria , the dyer 's alkanet or simply alkanet , is a herb in the borage family . Its main active ingredient is alkanic acid. It is used mainly for its flavonoid, tannic acid. It is used to treat rheumatism, headache, arthritis, dry skin and mild pain, particularly in young children. It also affects the eyes, nose, mouth, digestive tract and bones. It may cause nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea, though no long-term safety data is available.HistoryThe first evidence of use of alkanet dates back at least to ancient times.

Flavius Odoacer ( ;  – 493 AD), also spelled Odovacer or Odovacar , was a soldier and statesman of barbarian background, who deposed the child emperor Romulus Augustulus and became King of Italy (476–493). Odoacer's overthrow of Romulus Augustulus is traditionally seen as marking the end of the Western Roman Empire as well as Ancient Rome.Though the real power in Italy was in his hands, he represented himself as the client of the emperor in Constantinople, Zeno. Odoacer often used the Roman honorific patrician, granted by Zeno, but was referred to as a king  in many documents.

General Dynamics Electric Boat (GDEB) is a subsidiary of General Dynamics Corporation. It has been the primary builder of submarines for the United States Navy for more than 100 years. The company's main facilities are a shipyard in Groton, Connecticut, a hull-fabrication and outfitting facility in Quonset Point, Rhode Island, and a design and engineering facility in New London, Connecticut.HistoryThe company was founded in 1899 by Isaac Rice as the Electric Boat Company to build John Philip Holland's submersible ship designs, which were developed at Lewis Nixon's Crescent Shipyard in Elizabeth, New Jersey.

A hot air balloon is a lighter-than-air aircraft consisting of a bag, called an envelope, which contains heated air. Suspended beneath is a gondola or wicker basket (in some long-distance or high-altitude balloons, a capsule), which carries passengers and a source of heat, in most cases an open flame caused by burning liquid propane. The heated air inside the envelope makes it buoyant, since it has a lower density than the colder air outside the envelope. As with all aircraft, hot air balloons cannot fly beyond the atmosphere.

Shawn Fanning ( born November 22 , 1980 ) is an American computer programmer , entrepreneur , and angel investor who was a founding member of Activision Blizzard Entertainment and co-creator of Call of Duty. As of 2010, He remains one of the longest-running and highest-paid corporate figures in modern video gaming industry. He is best known as the co-creator of the first-person shooter genre, Call of Duty, as well as some of the other games to come after. Born on January 18, 1977, he received a Bachelor of Science degree in Economics from Yale University, where he spent two years teaching finance and management courses.

Milan Kundera ( , ; born 1 April 1929 ) is a Czech writer who went into exile in France to escape Soviet occupation. He was a prominent figure of French anti-Vietnam war literature and later became one of the world's greatest novelists. His novels were banned by Communist France after World War II, while his best-known novel, Le Dernier Révolution (1969), was translated into Russian and published in several languages; it won three Prix Novelles in 1973 and 1977. [2]Kundera grew up in Prague and moved there at the age of eight.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury , Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket (c. 828 – 907) was a Greek poet and historian who influenced the literary and religious history of eastern Europe, Africa, and much of western Christianity. His work, particularly in the context of early Christianity, is regarded as one of the first canonical accounts of early Christian revelation.Born into a wealthy Athenian aristocratic family, he became deeply involved in the arts when he left school to marry his childhood sweetheart, Annabel.

Year 884 (DCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 1 – Diego Rodríguez Porcelos, count of Castile, founds and repopulates (repoblación) Burgos and Ubierna (Northern Spain), under the mandate of King Alfonso III of Asturias. Summer – King Carloman II reverts to the former fall-back of 'pay and pray', buying (with Danegeld) a truce at Amiens, while he raises 12,000 lbs of silver for the Vikings to depart. December 12 – Carloman II dies after a hunting accident.

Linus Carl Pauling (; February 28, 1901 – August 19, 1994) was an American chemist, biochemist, chemical engineer,  peace activist, author, and educator. He published more than 1,200 papers and books, of which about 850 dealt with scientific topics. New Scientist called him one of the 20 greatest scientists of all time, and as of 2000, he was rated the 16th most important scientist in history. For his scientific work, Pauling was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1954. For his peace activism, he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1962.

Pope Leo VI (880 – 12 February 929) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States for just over seven months, from June 928 to his death. His pontificate occurred during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Family and early careerLeo VI was born into a Roman family, and his father was Christophorus, who had been primicerius under Pope John VIII around the year 876. Tradition has it that he was a member of the Sanguini family. Before his pontificate, Leo served as the cardinal-priest of Santa Susanna.PontificateLeo was elected pope around June 928, during a period of anarchy.

Gerard Adams ( ; born 6 October 1948 ) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Féin from 1990 to 2011. He represented the nationalist and pro-independence views of Northern Ireland during his tenure as first minister for Northern Ireland from 2010 to 2015, but he resigned at the request of the government of Prime Minister Stephen O'Neill. In January 2016, after a decade of civil war in the Democratic Republic of Ireland, he was awarded the Medal of Honour by former British Prime Minister William Gladstone for service in the European War. Alexis Tsipras (born 15 May 1956) is a Greek political leader.

Pope Leo VII (; died 13 July 939) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from 3 January 936 to his death.Election Leo VII's election to the papacy in 936, after the death of Pope John XI, was secured by Alberic II of Spoleto, the ruler of Rome at the time. Alberic wanted to choose the pope so that the papacy would continue to yield to his authority. Leo was the priest of the church of San Sisto Vecchio in Rome, thought to be a Benedictine monk.

Giovanni Pacini ( 17 February 17966 December 1867 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his operas . He is best known as one of the most prolific and influential composers throughout the classical era.Pacini's works included:The Sonata in D Major (1923), La Giornale di Marzina (1924), The Rite of Benediction (1925), La Bellona d'Eroce (1959), Requiem (1968), Andante della Vigna (1970), Risa del Teatro (1978), Opus 14 (1984), Ode to Joy (1997), Symphony No.

Mycenae ( ;  or , Mykē̂nai or Mykḗnē) is an archaeological site near Mykines in Argolis, north-eastern Peloponnese, Greece. It is located about  south-west of Athens;  north of Argos; and  south of Corinth. The site is  inland from the Saronic Gulf and built upon a hill rising  above sea level.In the second millennium BC, Mycenae was one of the major centres of Greek civilization, a military stronghold which dominated much of southern Greece, Crete, the Cyclades and parts of southwest Anatolia. The period of Greek history from about 1600 BC to about 1100 BC is called Mycenaean in reference to Mycenae.
