A line or part need not be a foreground melody.Melodies often consist of one or more musical phrases or motifs, and are usually repeated throughout a composition in various forms.

Millets are a group of highly variable small-seeded grasses , widely grown around the world as cereal crops or grains. The name "marbles" comes from the Greek word mare for "thorns" or "roots". Marina Doria (, ; 16 October 1813–8 August 1852) was an Italian singer and dancer who rose to fame in France after appearing in the musical Les Misérables before performing in the premiere of Elvira del Rosso della Cava.Doria was born in Sala Grande, in the Province of Savona, in southern Italy, to a peasant family.

In the history of cryptography, Typex (alternatively, Type X or TypeX) machines were British cipher machines used from 1937. It was an adaptation of the commercial German Enigma with a number of enhancements that greatly increased its security. The cipher machine (and its many revisions) was used until the mid-1950s when other more modern military encryption systems came into use.DescriptionLike Enigma, Typex was a rotor machine. Typex came in a number of variations, but all contained five rotors, as opposed to three or four in the Enigma.

Edward Teller ( ; January 15 , 1908 – September 9 , 2003 ) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who is widely known for inventing General Relativity, the framework of modern cosmology. In 1955, he published "On the Elegance of Matter", an influential book which introduced relativity theory to physics. The book gained him widespread international recognition and was reprinted hundreds of times. He is frequently credited with the development of the concept of the "Big Bang". Ralph Waldo Emerson ( [1 December 1795] – August 18, 1913) was an American writer, essayist, poet, satirist, novelist and playwright.

was the 68th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō 's reign spanned the years from 1462 to 1485, when it was overthrown by the Mongols and replaced by Emperor Yoshinori I in 1497 . It was followed by Yoshitomo Kiyomatsu (1492 – 1541) and Tokugawa Ieyasu (1493 – 1505) in the mid-16th century. He was consuls of a number of major cities, including Kyoto, Osaka, Kobe, Nara, and Shizuoka.He was regarded as the first ruler in Japan who had achieved national wealth and power without having to depend solely on foreign help.

Toilet paper (sometimes called toilet tissue) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and surrounding anal region of feces after defecation, and to clean the perineal area and external genitalia of urine after urination or other bodily fluid releases. It also acts as a layer of protection for the hands during these processes. It is usually supplied as a long strip of perforated paper wrapped around a paperboard core for storage in a dispenser near a toilet. The bundle is known as a toilet roll,  or loo roll or bog roll in Britain.There are other uses for toilet paper, as it is a readily available household product.

The Martian Chronicles is a science fiction fix-up novel , published in 1950 , by American writer Ray Bradbury that tells of the first contact between humanity and the planet Mars.Bradbury's novel was one of the most successful science fiction books of his lifetime, making him an almost overnight star in both the genre and the US market. It is also one of the most commercially successful novels of all time, selling over 25 million copies and earning it the designation of Science Fiction of the Decade. In mathematics, a function can be represented as a function (also known as algebraic product).

Tru64 UNIX is a discontinued 64-bit UNIX operating system for the Alpha instruction set architecture (ISA), currently owned by Hewlett-Packard (HP). Previously, Tru64 UNIX was a product of Compaq, and before that, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), where it was known as Digital UNIX (originally DEC OSF/1 AXP).As its original name suggests, Tru64 UNIX is based on the OSF/1 operating system. DEC's previous UNIX product was known as Ultrix and was based on BSD.It is unusual among commercial UNIX implementations, as it is built on top of the Mach kernel developed at Carnegie Mellon University.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton 's third law . When a system expels or accelerates mass it creates a thrust. In the case of gravity there is a separate force called centrifugal force, which has a specific value of -0.2 gf. Aerojet engines are devices that can propel objects through the atmosphere at great speed without burning fuel. One of the earliest applications was in World War II, particularly in aircraft designs. Due to the high energy levels required, air-to-air rockets had to operate at extremely high velocities to enable them to achieve their operational targets.

Henry Richard Enfield ( born 30 May 1961 ) is an English comedian , actor , writer , and director. He has appeared in several films and television programmes, including Seinfeld and Extras, which both starred Jerry Seinfeld.Enfield was born in North London, but grew up in the suburb of Teddington before moving to Los Angeles with his family.He studied acting at the Royal Shakespeare Company (RSC) from 1964 until 1974, becoming a part of the troupe when it acquired his name in 1977. In 1981, he made his debut on stage as himself, and won Best New Cast Member at the BAFTA film awards.

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern (MV; , ), also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania, is a state in the north-east of Germany. Of the country's sixteen states, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ranks 14th in population, 6th in area, and 16th in population density. Schwerin is the state capital and Rostock is the largest city. Other major cities include Neubrandenburg, Stralsund, Greifswald, Wismar and Güstrow.The state was established in 1945 after World War II through the merger of the historic regions of Mecklenburg and the Prussian Western Pomerania by the Soviet military administration in Allied-occupied Germany.

The governor general of Canada  is the federal viceregal representative of the . The  is head of state of Canada and the 14 other Commonwealth realms, but  resides in  oldest and most populous realm, the United Kingdom. The , on the advice of  Canadian prime minister, appoints a governor general to carry on the Government of Canada in the 's name, performing most of her constitutional and ceremonial duties. The commission is for an indefinite period—known as serving at  Majesty's pleasure—though five years is the usual length of time. Since 1959, it has also been traditional to alternate between anglophone and francophone officeholders—although many recent governors general have been bilingual.

The Boston transportation system includes roadway , subway , regional rail , air , and sea options for passenger and freight use. Some routes are operated by bus, trolleybus, and ferries.In the United States, Boston Metro is the nation's largest transit system, covering an area of about 665,500 square miles (1.5 million km2). It operates approximately 24,000 buses per day, a third of which have at least one passenger vehicle. There are 13 major commuter lines, including the East-West Bus Rapid Transit, the Tappan Zee Bridge, and the John F Kennedy International Airport Shuttle System.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue . In the RGB color model, purple is a value between 0 and 100. Colors can be either red or blue depending on their physical properties. This color space is used to display images in most applications and software, as well as in visual novels, online games, and other interactive entertainment systems. Purple is a genus of marine invertebrates, also known as the bivalves. It is one of only three families of animals that belong to the family Phaeolimodidae.

Malayalam ( ; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Karnataka and Tamil Nadu.In the English-speaking countries, it is also considered an official language of the United Kingdom. It is used by many people living in South Asia who use English as their primary medium of communication with non-English speaking communities. The language has gained popularity due to the popularity of e-commerce websites such as Amazon.Com and PayPal, which are used to process transactions in this country.Since 2002, the Department for International Development has offered assistance in the areas of health and education, among others.

Chrysippus of Soli ( ; , ; ) was a Greek Stoic philosopher . He was a native of Soli and lived in Bithynia, now present-day Turkey, from his early life. Etymology:  is a dialect of  (Latin  ). In modern English, it is the shortened form of  as used in the speech of American English speakers today. is pronounced as  in many dialects of American English. Emmanuel Macron, 22 December 2018 - 23 February 2019 : born June 30, 1951 in Paris, graduated in mathematics at the Polytechnique de Lyon and became an academician at the Ecole Polytechnique de Marseille in 1972.

Note: This compilation includes only those attacks that resulted in casualties. Attacks which did not kill or wound are not included.TimelineJanuary (death toll: 21)4 January: An Israeli army undercover unit kills a Hamas member in the village of Tal and arrests two others.9 January: Two Hamas militants wearing Palestinian police uniforms attack an IDF post near the Gaza Strip with grenades and assault rifles. Four Israeli soldiers and one of the attackers are killed.10 January-11: The Israeli army demolished 59 houses and damaged another 200 in Rafah refugee camp. Over six hundred Palestinians are made homeless.

was a Japanese television cooking show produced by Fuji Television. The series, which premiered on October 10, 1993, was a stylized cook-off featuring guest chefs challenging one of the show's resident "Iron Chefs" in a timed cooking battle built around a specific theme ingredient. The series ended on September 24, 1999, although occasional specials were produced until 2002. The series aired 309 episodes. Repeats are regularly aired on the Food Network in Canada, the Cooking Channel in the United States, and on Special Broadcasting Service in Australia.

The Burrows–Wheeler transform ( BWT , also called block-sorting compression ) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters, and converts each run to the same word or phrase with identical phonology and rhythm. It is the process by which English language learners become fluent in spoken English. Bernhard Bruegel (; 27 July 1936 – 15 January 2003) was an American political philosopher, writer, and linguist. He is best known for his work in cognitive science and computational linguistics, particularly on grammatical theory.In his own time, Bruegel was a member of the National Endowment of the Humanities.

Pizza Hut is an American multinational restaurant chain and international franchise founded in 1958 in Wichita, Kansas by Dan and Frank Carney. They serve their signature pan pizza and other dishes including pasta, breadsticks and desserts.The chain has 17,639 restaurants worldwide as of 2020,making it the world's largest pizza chain by number of locations.It is a subsidiary of Yum! Brands, Inc., one of the world's largest restaurant companies.HistoryPizza Hut was founded on June 15, 1958, by two brothers, Dan and Frank Carney, both Wichita State students, as a single location in Wichita, Kansas.

Catalase is a common enzyme found in nearly all living organisms exposed to oxygen ( such as bacteria , plants, and insects ). In contrast to many proteins that have the same size and mass but different catalytic activities, the catalytic function of each enzyme depends on the molecular weight of the molecule with which it interacts. Many enzymes are composed of only a single type of nucleotide base pair. Northeastern Australia has two main population centres, the state capital Darwin and the regional capital Townsville. Both areas are situated in the southeast of the state, about 45° east of the equator and west of the southern Australian coast.

Year 879 (DCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeEurope  April 10 – King Louis the Stammerer dies at Compiègne, after a reign of 18 months. He is succeeded by his two sons, Louis III and Carloman II. They are crowned at Ferrières Abbey, and rule the West Frankish Kingdom together as joint-kings. Baldwin I ("Iron Arm") dies, after 15 years as margrave of Flanders. He is buried in the Abbey of Saint Bertin (near Saint-Omer), and is succeeded by his son Baldwin II.

Phenylalanine (symbol Phe or F) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as a benzyl group substituted for the methyl group of alanine, or a phenyl group in place of a terminal hydrogen of alanine. This essential amino acid is classified as neutral, and nonpolar because of the inert and hydrophobic nature of the benzyl side chain. The L-isomer is used to biochemically form proteins coded for by DNA. Phenylalanine is a precursor for tyrosine, the monoamine neurotransmitters dopamine, norepinephrine (noradrenaline), epinephrine (adrenaline), and the skin pigment melanin.

Eugène Adrien Roland Georges Garros ( ; 6 October 1888 – 5 October 1918 ) was a French pioneering aviator and one of the most accomplished pilots to ever fly in the world. He commanded the first French air force during World War I and played an important part in France's victory over Germany. During his time as pilot, he fought on many different kinds of aerobatic aircraft including monoplane bombers, biplanes, seaplanes, and helicopters.Roland served in the French Air Force from 1917 to 1918. He is best known as the pilot of the Messerschmitt Me 262 A-7 bomber during World War I.

The fisherman 's knot is a bend ( a knot for joining two lines ) with a symmetrical structure consisting of a central hole, the main loop at its centre and a secondary loop below. The word angiotechnology derives from the Latin ōgonos, meaning 'insect-like', and in Greek ēgnōtō meaning 'giant insect'. The angiotechnological use of an ōgonous insect was first documented during the Middle Ages when the earliest examples are known to exist, but this name has been used by other scholars, including some authors who refer to it as ēgnōtiō ('giant beetles').

Josiah Willard Gibbs (; February 11, 1839 – April 28, 1903) was an American scientist who made significant theoretical contributions to physics, chemistry, and mathematics. His work on the applications of thermodynamics was instrumental in transforming physical chemistry into a rigorous inductive science. Together with James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann, he created statistical mechanics (a term that he coined), explaining the laws of thermodynamics as consequences of the statistical properties of ensembles of the possible states of a physical system composed of many particles. Gibbs also worked on the application of Maxwell's equations to problems in physical optics.

Antioch on the Orontes ( ; , Antiókheia hē epì Oróntou ; also Syrian Antioch ) was a Hellenistic city, most probably in modern-day Turkey, which formed an important gateway for Roman and early Greek traffic from the west. Its capital, Antioch of the East, was located about 1,150 km (929 mi) northwest of Istanbul. In ancient times Antioch was used as the seat of Caesar Augustus, although he died while at Antioch by his third consul Agrippa Domitian. Amphæans were a primitive human group that inhabited the southern end of the Aegean Sea from the Late Jurassic to the Early Eocene period.

Paclitaxel (PTX), sold under the brand name Taxol among others, is a chemotherapy medication used to treat a number of types of cancer. This includes ovarian cancer, esophageal cancer, breast cancer, lung cancer, Kaposi's sarcoma, cervical cancer, and pancreatic cancer. It is administered by intravenous injection. There is also an albumin-bound formulation.Common side effects include hair loss, bone marrow suppression, numbness, allergic reactions, muscle pains, and diarrhea. Other serious side effects include heart problems, increased risk of infection, and lung inflammation. There are concerns that use during pregnancy may cause birth defects.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham ( born October 3 , 1949 ) is an American singer , musician , songwriter , and actress. She has received a total of 14 nominations for various television and film awards, most notably winning two Academy Awards (for Best Actress in 2001).Adams was born on October 3, 1949 in Fort Dodge, Mississippi, to Mary Alice Adams (née Davis) and Robert James Adams Jr., according to her mother's birth certificate. She was raised in Boca Raton, Florida, from the time she was four years old, with her maternal grandparents' home in St. John's, Newfoundland.

Year 959 (CMLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April - May – The Byzantines refuse to pay the yearly tribute. A Hungarian army, led by Apor, invades Macedonia and Thrace. He plunders its territories until reaching Constantinople. On his way back, Apor is defeated during a night attack by Byzantine forces. November 9 – Emperor Constantine VII Porphyrogennetos ("born in the purple") dies at Constantinople after a 46-year reign. He is succeeded by his 21-year-old son Romanos II as ruler of the Byzantine Empire.

Barbecue or barbeque ( informally BBQ in the UK and US , barbie in Australia and braai in South Africa) is the use of a grill to serve hot, cooked food to a large group of participants. Barbeque can be accomplished by either hand or on an electric grill.Some barbecue recipes are more elaborate with various cooking methods. Barbecuing was originally a process used to preserve food for consumption by the people that owned the land, often as a part of a long-range plan. Barbecuing took place in a particular area, usually in an open forest, using a fire pit or wood burning stove.

Year 949 (CMXLIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>By placeByzantine Empire  Arab-Byzantine War: Hamdanid forces under Sayf al-Dawla raid into the theme of Lykandos, but are defeated. The Byzantines counter-attack and seize Germanikeia, defeating an army from Tarsus, and raiding as far south as Antioch. General (strategos) Theophilos Kourkouas captures Theodosiopolis (modern-day Erzurum) after a 7-month siege.Europe  A Byzantine expeditionary force under Constantine Gongyles attempts to re-conquer the Emirate of Crete from the Saracens.

The subset sum problem (SSP) is a decision problem in computer science. In its most general formulation, there is a multiset  of integers and a target-sum , and the question is to decide whether any subset of the integers sum to precisely . The problem is known to be NP-complete. Moreover, some restricted variants of it are NP-complete too, for example: The variant in which all inputs are positive. The variant in which inputs may be positive or negative, and . For example, given the set , the answer is yes because the subset  sums to zero.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand ( 26 October 19168 January 1996 ) served as President of France from 1981 to 1989. He is also considered the greatest leader of modern Europe, having created two world wars and founded the European Community in 1949. His achievements include the Second World War, which was the longest war in history; the Paris Peace Conference that ended World War Two; the partition of the German-Polish border; and the establishment of the Eurozone.In a speech at the start of his presidency, he called for the separation of power between the state and the central government.

Mercury (;  ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology, being one of the 12 Dii Consentes within the ancient Roman pantheon. He is the god of financial gain, commerce, eloquence, messages, communication (including divination), travelers, boundaries, luck, trickery, and thieves; he also serves as the guide of souls to the underworld.In Roman mythology, he was considered to be either the son of Maia, one of the seven daughters of the Titan Atlas, and Jupiter, or of Caelus and Dies.

Fall back is a feature of a modem protocol in data communication whereby two communicating modems which experience data corruption (due to line noise, for example) can renegotiate with each other to use a lower-speed connection. Fall forward is a corresponding feature whereby two modems which have "fallen back" to a lower speed can later return to the higher speed if the connection improves.A common feature modems was the concept of fallback, allowing them to talk to less-capable modems. During the call initiation the modem would play a series of signals into the line and wait for the remote modem to "answer" them.

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc ( then owned by Research in Motion). Their predecessor, the Palm Pro, was discontinued after only four models were released in 2007. The Palm Pro was sold as a separate product and had its own battery pack and operating system. Marionette Electronics , also known as Maestro, is a home entertainment company based in Orangeville, Michigan. It specializes in the production and manufacture of portable digital home entertainment systems consisting of personal audio interface units (PARIs), sound systems (SISs) and computer peripheral units (PCUs).

Lanford Wilson ( April 13 , 1937March 24 , 2011 ) was an American playwright . His work , as well as those of many others, is considered to be part of the Romantic tradition. Born in Virginia, he emigrated to New York City after a year of studying English and theater at Cornell University. In 1935, he came to Los Angeles for a semester, but soon became interested in the emerging film industry. During these two years, Wilson attended several meetings and conventions in Hollywood, where he met his future wife Rose McGowan (who would later become his wife).

On May 25 , 1865 , in Mobile , Alabama , in the Southern United States , an ordnance depot of the United States Military Intelligence (USMI) was struck by cannon fire, killing all but four soldiers and destroying a large part of the fortifications that were protecting its supply routes . John Quincy Adams (b. 17 October 1735–19 March 1792) was the 17th President of the United States from 1828 to 1833 and the 19th president from 1834 to 1838. He served as attorney general of New York from 1799 to 1830 and he served as secretary of state from 1797 to 1803.

New Zealand consists of more than six hundred islands , mainly remnants of a larger land mass now beneath the sea. New Zealand's geographic position means it has an approximately equal distribution of landmass, ocean and marine species. A high proportion of the population lives on the coast, with coastal areas making up the vast majority of landmass. Norman Cousins was born in Brooklyn, New York in 1852. He emigrated to England during his childhood, settling in Devon, where he became an actor. The first film he appeared in produced for British audiences was Alfred Hitchcock's 1955 film Vertigo (also directed by Hitchcock).

A gas nuclear reactor ( or gas fueled reactor or vapor core reactor ) is a proposed kind of nuclear power plant that has the capacity to generate and store heat using radioactive fission products. These designs are widely considered impractical in large areas due to their reliance on fossil fuels. Many reactors are based on low-temperature molten salt reactors ( LNTRs). The first nuclear reactors were constructed during the 19th century and have been used throughout history, including by countries such as France, Belgium, Canada, the U.K., Australia, Germany, Great Britain, Italy, Japan, South Korea, Sweden and United States.

Kenneth Charles Williams (22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988) was an English actor. He was best known for his comedy roles and in later life as a raconteur and diarist. He was one of the main ensemble in 26 of the 31 Carry On films, and appeared in many British television programmes and radio comedies, including series with Tony Hancock and Kenneth Horne, as well as being a regular panellist on BBC Radio 4's comedy panel show Just a Minute from its second series in 1968 until his death 20 years later.Williams grew up in Central London in a working-class family; he claimed his father spoke as a cockney.

The word  comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script, which were made a major part of the Japanese writing system along with the syllabic scripts of hiragana and katakana. More specifically, it refers to that set of Chinese characters directly incorporated into the written Japanese language with often Japanese pronunciation, inclusive of those few characters invented in Japan based on character components derived from other Chinese characters.The term kanji literally means "Han characters", and this word is spelled in Japanese using the same characters as traditional Chinese in reference to the character writing system, which is known as hanzi .

La traviata (; The Fallen Woman) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian libretto by Francesco Maria Piave. It is based on La Dame aux camélias (1852), a play by Alexandre Dumas fils adapted from his own 1848 novel. The opera was originally titled Violetta, after the main character. It was first performed on 6 March 1853 at La Fenice opera house in Venice.Piave and Verdi wanted to follow Dumas in giving the opera a contemporary setting, but the authorities at La Fenice insisted that it be set in the past, "c. 1700".

The overhand knot , also known as a knot and half knot , is one of the most fundamental knots in knifes. They are made of several layers of yarn connected to hold a single piece of fabric together. Each layer must be held together so that it cannot slip during movement. When the stitches are slipped, they break apart into two pieces. The edges of the broken pieces make a point.Knives tend to have an irregular shape due to friction with the knife blade, but they can be arranged in numerous ways to produce many different patterns.

The Story of the Chevalier des Grieux and Manon Lescaut  is a novel by Antoine François Prévost. Published in 1731, it is the seventh and final volume of Mémoires et aventures d'un homme de qualité (Memoirs and Adventures of a Man of Quality).The story, set in France and Louisiana in the early 18th century, follows the hero, the Chevalier des Grieux, and his lover, Manon Lescaut. Controversial in its time, the work was banned in France upon publication. Despite this, it became very popular and pirated editions were widely distributed.

Bread is a staple food prepared from a dough of flour (usually wheat) and water, usually by baking. Throughout recorded history and around the world, it has been an important part of many cultures' diet. It is one of the oldest human-made foods, having been of significance since the dawn of agriculture, and plays an essential role in both religious rituals and secular culture.Bread may be leavened by naturally occurring microbes (e.g. sourdough), chemicals (e.g. baking soda), industrially produced yeast, or high-pressure aeration, which creates the gas bubbles that fluff up bread.

Patch collecting or badge collecting (also, scutelliphily, from Latin scutellus meaning little shield, and Greek phileein meaning to love) is the hobby of collecting patches or badges.Souvenir patchesSouvenir patches are usually shield-shaped and generally contain a coat of arms, a map or a miniature view. The patches can be made of any material, but are usually woven or embroidered fabric, though they can also be made from paper or, increasingly, plastic.Other types of collectible patches include police or service patches, space mission patches, Scout patches, fashion patches, political and sports stickers, walking stick labels, car window pennants, and pin badges.

George Catlett Marshall Jr. ( December 31 , 1880 – October 16 , 1959 ) was an American army officer, former senator, and author of more than 300 books and numerous essays about the military. He was one of America's most prominent political figures in the mid-20th century. Born in Kansas City, Kansas, Marshall graduated from Harvard University in 1904 and earned a B.S. degree in English in 1907. The Army Air Corps awarded him the Distinguished Service Medal for valor during World War I.He served in World War II as air commander of the Pacific Theater before being nominated for induction to the U.S. Senate.

Antioch on the Orontes (; , Antiókheia hē epì Oróntou; also Syrian Antioch) was a Hellenistic city side of the Orontes River. Its ruins lie near the current city of Antakya, Turkey, to which the ancient city lends its name.Antioch was founded near the end of the fourth century BC by Seleucus I Nicator, one of Alexander the Great's generals. The city's geographical, military, and economic location benefited its occupants, particularly such features as the spice trade, the Silk Road, and the Royal Road. It eventually rivaled Alexandria as the chief city of the Near East.

Year 1155 ( MCLV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the Latin calendar. It began on 15 January 1155, when Pope Innocent III formally confirmed the validity of the Lateran Monarchy. This followed the coronation of King James I in November 1161 and marked the inauguration of a new age of English kings. The feast also marked the official end of Edward II's reign. A mace is a weapon which is shaped like a spear or a wooden staff, used to cut down enemies. A mace is one of the most common weapons in medieval combat.

Naval Submarine Base New London is the primary United States Navy East Coast submarine base , also known as the Midway Submarine Base. It was established during World War II, with the creation of the Navy Ballistic Missile Force. The base is situated just north of Cape Hatteras, off the coast of North Carolina . The area is considered a major shipping corridor by international waters, and is home to an estimated 1,300 warships and more than 400 aircraft. The base's history begins in 1930, when the U.S. Navy acquired the facility from Germany under the terms of the American Naval Treaty of May 31, 1941.

A museum ( ; plural museums or , rarely , musea ) is a building or institution that cares for and preserves historical objects, manuscripts, collections, or cultural materials in the English language. The term can refer to a collection of objects from different eras, regions, or societies.The term "museum" includes schools, hospitals, theaters, parks, archives, libraries, newspapers, books, and other public buildings, which are also usually called museums.Museums vary widely in size, construction and design. Mountain Goats is an American rock music act composed by guitarist Jon Pareles, keyboardist Dan O'Neal, and bassist John Cale.

Westminster is an area of Central London, part of the wider City of Westminster.The area, which extends from the River Thames to Oxford Street has many visitor attractions and historic landmarks, including the Palace of Westminster, Buckingham Palace, Westminster Abbey, Westminster Cathedral and much of the West End shopping and entertainment district.The name  originated from the informal description of the abbey church and royal peculiar of St Peter's (Westminster Abbey), west of the City of London (until the English Reformation there was also an Eastminster, near the Tower of London, in the East End of London).

Year 986 (CMLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 17 – Battle of the Gates of Trajan: Emperor Basil II leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (30,000 men) against the Bulgarians to capture the fortress city of Sredets. After a siege of 20 days, Basil is forced to retreat from the Sofia Valley towards the town of Ihtiman (through a passage known as the Gate of Trajan). The Bulgarians under Tsar Samuel ambush and defeat the Byzantine forces.

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software . The series consists of four games: Desert Bus (1999), Space Shuttle Challenger (2001), Space Shuttle Endeavour (2004) and Space Shuttle Discovery (2006).In each game, players will take control of a large vehicle on which they are to attempt to land their craft successfully. Each player can command a single plane or squad of planes in the sky to attack nearby targets. The game has been made available for the Windows PC, PlayStation 2 and Xbox 360 platforms.

Columbia Business School ( CBS ) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in New York State, U.S.A. Located in Manhattan's Upper East Side, Columbia provides a range of graduate and undergraduate courses in management, marketing, communications, human resources, economics, technology, education, history, politics, and other businesses.The school is ranked #1 by The Wall Street Journal, number one by Forbes and number two in the United States by The American Association for the Advancement of Science.It was established in 1892 as Columbia University's first-ever professional institution of higher learning.

Paul Leo Molitor ( born August 22 , 1956 ) , nicknamed `` Molly '' and `` The Ignitor '' by friends and colleagues, is an American artist known for his provocative works of children's literature and art.His earliest works are published in the 1970s in a variety of formats, including black-and-white print books and graphic novel covers. He is best known for his stories that deal with the themes of family and adolescence, although they have been popular in other fields, including poetry, play, and illustration.Molitor's career was marred by drug abuse from the 1960s through the 1980s.

Reptilia is Canada 's largest indoor reptile zoo , with of indoor exhibits featuring over 250 reptiles , amphibians and aquatic invertebrates . It is a national attraction, with more than 1,500 species of reptiles in its collection dating from the mid-1970s through the present day. While there are no live reptiles at Reptilia, visitors have the opportunity to learn about the lives of many of these animals, especially those that are closely related to humans and their habitats. Horse racing was originally developed during the early nineteenth century by horse racing enthusiasts and scientists who wanted to increase their ability to produce high-intensity racing performances.

In academic publishing, a scientific journal is a periodical publication intended to further the progress of science, usually by reporting new research.ContentArticles in scientific journals are mostly written by active scientists such as students, researchers and professors instead of professional journalists. There are thousands of scientific journals in publication, and many more have been published at various points in the past (see list of scientific journals). Most journals are highly specialized, although some of the oldest journals such as Nature publish articles and scientific papers across a wide range of scientific fields.

Gaelic football ( ; short name ) , commonly known as simply Gaelic , GAA or Caid , is an internationally renowned sport in Ireland, with over 5,000 national and international teams in a wide spectrum of styles. A professional Gaelic player has won more titles than any other sportsperson in the world, including three Irish League titles and two Northern Ireland League Championships.The first professional rugby team was founded in Dublin in 1869 under the name Ulster Rugby Union, but its existence was eventually curtailed by civil war. The last professional football team was formed in 1920.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman  (born 19 October 1946) is an English writer. His books include the fantasy trilogy His Dark Materials and The Good Man Jesus and the Scoundrel Christ, a fictionalised biography of Jesus. In 2008, The Times named Pullman one of the "50 greatest British writers since 1945". In a 2004 BBC poll, he was named the eleventh most influential person in British culture. He was knighted in the 2019 New Year Honours for services to literature.Northern Lights, the first volume in His Dark Materials, won the 1995 Carnegie Medal of the Library Association as the year's outstanding English-language children's book.

Pope Gregory I (;  – 12 March 604), commonly known as Saint Gregory the Great, was the bishop of Rome from 3 September 590 to his death. He is known for instigating the first recorded large-scale mission from Rome, the Gregorian Mission, to convert the then-pagan Anglo-Saxons in England to Christianity. Gregory is also well known for his writings, which were more prolific than those of any of his predecessors as pope. The epithet Saint Gregory the Dialogist has been attached to him in Eastern Christianity because of his Dialogues.

Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) is a U.S. multiprogram science and technology national laboratory sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and administered, managed, and operated by UT–Battelle as a federally funded research and development center (FFRDC) under a contract with the DOE, located in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.Established in 1943, ORNL is the largest science and energy national laboratory in the Department of Energy system (by size) and third largest by annual budget. It is located in the Roane County section of Oak Ridge, Tennessee.

Mercury ( ; ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology , being one of the 12 Dii Libri in the Latin Vulgate.In ancient Greek mythology, Mercury was the son of Jupiter and his wife Helene. His role in the life of gods and man is similar to Zeus in Greek mythology, as both are brothers and children of Jupiter. Hemlock ( ; ) is a flowering perennial herb native to parts of eastern North America and northern Europe. It grows mainly on rocky meadows in open meadows, although some species also grow in woodlands. Hemicotyl-type hybrids have been described.

Bi-curious is a term for a person , usually someone who is a heterosexual , who is curious or open to new ideas and experiences about the world.The term may have more specific meanings, ranging from curiosity to skepticism or scepticism. Some definitions of "bisexuality" include people who have no sexual attractions to women or men but like being with both sexes.Some studies have found that bisexuals are not necessarily attracted to members of the same sex. Other studies have found that bisexuals might be attracted to other types of people (or vice versa).

Year 980 (CMLXXX) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Peace is concluded between Emperor Otto II (the Red) and King Lothair III (or Lothair IV) at Margut, ending the Franco-German war of 978–980. Lothair renounces his claim on Lower Lorraine, while Otto promises to recognize Lothair's son Louis V as the rightful heir of the West Frankish Kingdom. June 11 – Vladimir I (the Great), grand prince of Kiev, consolidates the Kievan realm from modern Ukraine to the Baltic Sea.

Pope Leo XI ( ; 2 June 153527 April 1605 ) , born Alessandro Ottaviano de ' Medici , was a Florentine nobleman and the second emperor of the Republic of Venice. He was succeeded in his throne as emperor by his father, Clement XII, on 14 December 1531. His reign ended with the Thirty Years' War in 1553. Leo XIII is the third son of St. John XXIII, the Pope to be canonized by Pope Pius VII. He took up the title of Cardinal Saint Louis after his mother died.

Henry Richard Enfield (born 30 May 1961) is an English comedian, actor, writer, and director. He is known in particular for his television work, including Harry Enfield's Television Programme and Harry & Paul, and for the creation and portrayal of comedy characters such as Kevin the Teenager and Loadsamoney.Early lifeBorn in Horsham, Sussex, he is the oldest of four children, the son of English television, radio and newspaper journalist and presenter Edward Enfield. He has three sisters. The Enfield family are descendants of the nineteenth-century philanthropist Edward Enfield.

Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium ( He ) and oxygen ( O2 ) .Heliox is a medical inhalant, which also acts as a diuretic to neutralize the urine produced by hyponatremia. It is used to treat certain forms of respiratory depression, such as emphysema, asthma, sinusitis, and bronchitis. Heliox is administered intramuscularly or intravenously for treatment in patients who have not been treated with other means of hydration.An average dose of about 0.25 mL is enough to provide 2.0–3.5 mg/L of hydronegativity. Hexanide ( ; ). Hexanide is a nonpolar hydrocarbon that is chemically similar to but more unstable because of its half-life.

Budapest ( , ; ) is the capital and most populous city of Hungary . It is the ninth-largest city in the country and the fifth-largest municipality in Europe, with 3.75 million residents and a population density of 551.8 per square kilometre.It is the fourth-largest city in Hungary by population, and also among Europe's largest when excluding its suburbs. Buda is considered part of Krakow. In addition it is the oldest continuously inhabited city in the world.There are more than 70 official museums in Budapest, with a combined total of more than 4,600.

The governor general of Canada is the federal viceregal representative of the . The is head of state of Canada and serves on Parliament's executive committee. He is also the first president of the Council of Ministers of Canada, which manages Canada's foreign-affairs policies. In his role as Governor General, he issues writs to the provinces, which authorize the government to legislate in each province.In his capacity as Prime Minister, Pierre Trudeau oversees the development of Canadian military and security policies. The prime minister is Canada's top elected leader by a wide margin of both absolute and relative power.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky ( 6 April 1971 ) was a Russian composer , pianist and conductor , later of French and German-language works. His best-known composition, "Rhapsody in Blue", was performed as the opening theme to the 1966 film Star Trek . In addition, he composed several symphonies and numerous pieces for orchestral and chamber music; among them are the operas The Rite of Spring and Symphony No. 5 in D Major. Hindi is a region in Southeast Asia, particularly Thailand, Laos, Myanmar, and Cambodia. It has long been a hotbed of ethnic and religious conflict.

Mary Anning (21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847) was an English fossil collector, dealer, and palaeontologist who became known around the world for finds she made in Jurassic marine fossil beds in the cliffs along the English Channel at Lyme Regis in the county of Dorset in Southwest England. Anning's findings contributed to changes in scientific thinking about prehistoric life and the history of the Earth.Anning searched for fossils in the area's Blue Lias and Charmouth Mudstone cliffs, particularly during the winter months when landslides exposed new fossils that had to be collected quickly before they were lost to the sea.

The BBC World Service is an international broadcaster owned and operated by the BBC , with funding from the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) to broadcast news, cultural and educational programmes across Europe and around the world. It was launched on 28 May 1958 as the first English-language television news service.It has more than 14 million households across Europe and over 30 million members in more than 50 countries around the world. It consists primarily of state-sponsored channels such as the BBC World Service, BBC News, BBC Sport and BBC World Service Classics.The BBC also produces a daily newspaper, the Sunday Times.

Loris is the common name for the strepsirrhine mammals of the subfamily Lorinae (sometimes spelled Lorisinae) in the family Lorisidae. Loris is one genus in this subfamily and includes the slender lorises, while Nycticebus is the genus containing the slow lorises.DescriptionLorises are nocturnal and arboreal. They are found in tropical and woodland forests of India, Sri Lanka, and parts of southeast Asia. Loris locomotion is a slow and cautious climbing form of quadrupedalism. Some lorises are almost entirely insectivorous, while others also include fruits, gums, leaves, and slugs in their diet.Female lorises practice infant parking, leaving their infants behind in nests.

Loris is the common name for the strepsirrhine mammals of the subfamily Lorinae ( sometimes spelled Lorisinae ) in the order Lepidoptera , and includes three species: Mestreiurus, Mestreoideus, and Lycopithecus.They range widely from southern Europe across the Atlantic Ocean to western Australia, and can also be found in northern India.The genus was originally known under the taxonomic category Pseudodactyla, but has been re-recognized by other taxonomic groups as the genus Lorosia (or simply Lorosia) since 1980. The name Loricidae derives from the Greek name loros, which means "to hide". A person is an individual that lives with another human being.

The Space Shuttle program was the fourth human spaceflight program carried out by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), which accomplished routine transportation for Earth-to-orbit crew and cargo from 1981 to 2011. Its official name, Space Transportation System (STS), was taken from a 1969 plan for a system of reusable spacecraft of which it was the only item funded for development.The Space Shuttle—composed of an orbiter launched with two reusable solid rocket boosters and a disposable external fuel tank—carried up to eight astronauts and up to  of payload into low Earth orbit (LEO).

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ( MV ; , ) , also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania , is a state in Germany, Belgium, Switzerland, and the Netherlands. It borders on the North Sea and is part of the Rhine-Danube Region of the country. It is the administrative and border-region of Bavaria but has its own language, culture, and traditions.The area that lies around it is divided into six counties: Saxony-Anhalt (Saxony), Saxony-Abwehr (Saxony), Hessen (Hessen), Thuringia (Thuringia), Gera (Germanschau), and Wuppertal (Wuppertal).

A resistojet is a method of spacecraft propulsion (electric propulsion) that provides thrust by heating a, typically non-reactive, fluid. Heating is usually achieved by sending electricity through a resistor consisting of a hot incandescent filament, with the expanded gas expelled through a conventional nozzle.Resistojets have been flown in space since 1965 on board military Vela satellites. However, they only became used in commercial applications in 1980 with the launch of the first satellites in the INTELSAT-V program. Many GEO spacecraft, and all 95 Iridium, used Aerojet MR-501/MR-502 series resistojet engines.

The heart is a muscular organ in most animals , which pumps blood through the blood vessels of the circulatory system. It also functions as the major source of metabolic energy and oxygen for the nervous system, the digestive system, and other bodily functions. The heart consists of a set of chambers that are connected by tubes that connect the lungs (and thus the heart) to the rest of the body through the esophagus. Heartbeats are the electrical fluctuations produced by the heart when it beats on its own two or more chambers.

was the 75th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Sutoku's reign spanned the years from 1123 through 1142.GenealogyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (his imina) was Akihito (顕仁). Sutoku was the eldest son of Emperor Toba. Some old texts say he was instead the son of Toba's grandfather, Emperor Shirakawa.Chūgū: Fujiwara no Kiyoko (藤原 聖子) later Kōkamon'in (皇嘉門院), Fujiwara Tadamichi’s daughter Hyounosuke-no-Tsubone (兵衛佐局), Minamoto Masamune's adopted daughter First son: Imperial  (1140–1162).

Year 1025 ( MXXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Sunday at 8:00am (UTC). The first ten years started on 1 September 1025. The calendar was changed by the Great Fire of London in 1066; it was reestablished on 11 April 1171.On the 21st of each lunar month, the Christian Church celebrated Pentecost. This was done so as to avoid unnecessary conflict with the Lenten fasting which began on the 26th of Lent. There were some notable exceptions, such as the Easter Vigil which did not celebrate Pentecost until 15 June 1186.

Cambridge is a university city and the county town of Cambridgeshire , England , on the River Cam approximately north-east of Leeds in the county of South Yorkshire.Cambridge is home to two colleges, the Institute of Education and the Institute of Advanced Study (IAS).The city has a total area of 936,921 square kilometres, or 14.3% of its area as of 2010. The centre of the city is the University of Cambridge, with an overall population of 4,065,300. Sapphire is the fifth largest planet in the Solar System after Mercury, Venus, Earth, Jupiter and Saturn.

Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous – Shoemaker ( NEAR Shoemaker ) , renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary scientist Carl Sagan, is a NASA space science satellite launched by the agency on 17 December 1997. It was named for astronomer Carl Sagan (1925–1996), who observed one of the largest asteroids known in our solar system, about as wide as the Earth but larger than Pluto.Launched by the Atlas 5 from Kennedy Space Center's Launch Complex 40 (LCC-40), the spacecraft was carried to an altitude of 1.7 km (0.5 mi) at liftoff.

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois ( nicknamed `` Huey '' ) is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft. Its design, engineering and production history are shrouded in mystery for almost 40 years, although it appears to have been developed in the 1950s and 1960s as an aircraft carrier airship for the U.S. Navy. Auxiliary Power Units (APS) is a power system that provides continuous supply to a unit or multiple units of an electric energy system. APS systems include electricity distribution, alternating current, voltage regulation, capacitive switching, phase transition, interconnecting equipment, and transformers.

Celebration is a census-designated place (CDP) and a master-planned community in Osceola County, Florida, United States, located near Walt Disney World Resort and originally developed by The Walt Disney Company. The town, whose population was 7,427 at the 2010 census, is part of the Orlando–Kissimmee Metropolitan Statistical Area.After founding Celebration, Disney followed its plans to divest most of its control of the town. Several Disney business units continue to occupy the town's office buildings. Walt Disney World operates two utility companies, Smart City Telecom and Reedy Creek Energy Services, that provide services to the town.

In the English language, the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people, especially African Americans. Because it is considered extremely offensive, even if only mentioned and not used as a slur, it is often referred to by the euphemism . It is also in use with a more neutral meaning among African Americans, primarily as nigga. The word originated in the 18th century as an adaptation of the Spanish word negro, a descendant of the Latin adjective niger, which means "black". Over time it took on a derogatory connotation and became a racist insult by the 20th century.

Fidelio , originally titled  (Leonore, or The Triumph of Marital Love), Op. 72, is Ludwig van Beethoven's only opera. The German libretto was originally prepared by Joseph Sonnleithner from the French of Jean-Nicolas Bouilly, with the work premiering at Vienna's Theater an der Wien on 20 November 1805. The following year, Stephan von Breuning helped shorten the work from three acts to two. After further work on the libretto by Georg Friedrich Treitschke, a final version was performed at the Kärntnertortheater on 23 May 1814.

Hex is a two player abstract strategy board game in which players attempt to connect opposite sides of a hexagonal board. Hex was invented by mathematician and poet Piet Hein in 1942 and independently by John Nash in 1948.It is traditionally played on an 11×11 rhombus board, although 13×13 and 19×19 boards are also popular. Each player is assigned a pair of opposite sides of the board which they must try to connect by taking turns placing a stone of their color onto any empty space. Once placed, the stones are unable to be moved or removed.

Flavius Odoacer ( ; – 493 AD ) , also spelled Odovacer or Odovacar , was a soldier and statesman of the Roman Republic, who served as praetorian prefect for many years. He was instrumental in the defeat of Julius Caesar. Odette (; 5 September 1492–8 March 1853) was a French singer, songwriter, performer, composer, and pianist. Born in Paris in the year 1560 to a prominent courtier, her early childhood was attended by both religious and political influences, which she later developed into interest in philosophy, poetry, art, literature, and music.

A cigarette is a narrow cylinder containing burnable material , typically tobacco , that is rolled into thin paper for smoking.Cigar smoke contains thousands, if not millions, of individual molecules of chemical compounds (e.g., flavan-3-ol) that are formed as the smoke travels through the respiratory tract.The term smoke refers also to the vapor in the lungs or aerosol produced by combustion.As with any mixture of chemicals, there is variation among different types of cigarettes. In general, larger and more expensive products tend to contain higher concentrations of particulate matter, while lighter, lighter-smoke models tend to contain lower concentrations of particulates.

The M109 is an American 155 mm turreted self-propelled howitzer, first introduced in the early 1960s to replace the M44. It has been upgraded a number of times, most recently to the M109A7. The M109 family is the most common Western indirect-fire support weapon of maneuver brigades of armored and mechanized infantry divisions.The M109 has a crew of four: the section chief/commander, the driver, the gunner, and the ammunition handler/loader. The chief or gunner aims the cannon left or right (deflection) and up and down (quadrant).The British Army replaced its M109s with the AS-90.

The Palmer Raids were a series of raids conducted in November 1919 and January 1920 by the United States Department of Justice under the administration of President Woodrow Wilson to capture and arrest suspected socialists, mostly Italian immigrants and Eastern European immigrants and especially anarchists and communists, and deport them from the United States. The raids particularly targeted Italian immigrants and Eastern European Jewish immigrants with alleged leftist ties, with particular focus on Italian anarchists and immigrant leftist labor activists. The raids and arrests occurred under the leadership of Attorney General A. Mitchell Palmer, with 3,000 arrested.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham (born October 3, 1949) is an American singer, musician, songwriter, and producer, best known as the former lead guitarist and male lead singer of the music group Fleetwood Mac from 1975 to 1987 and 1997 to 2018. In addition to his tenure with Fleetwood Mac, Buckingham has released six solo albums and three live albums. As a member of Fleetwood Mac, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1998. Buckingham was ranked 100th in Rolling Stones 2011 list of "The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time".

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois (nicknamed "Huey") is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft engine, with two-bladed main and tail rotors. The first member of the prolific Huey family, it was developed by Bell Helicopter to meet a 1952 US Army requirement for a medical evacuation and utility helicopter, and first flew in 1956. The UH-1 was the first turbine-powered helicopter produced for the United States military, and more than 16,000 have been built since 1960.The Iroquois was originally designated HU-1, hence the Huey nickname, which has remained in common use, despite the official redesignation to UH-1 in 1962.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state 's south-east within the Murray-Darling Basin, approximately 70 kilometres west of Adelaide. In December 2015 it was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site by UNESCO after receiving international recognition for its unique archaeological remains, including its ancient city walls, fortifications, royal palaces and royal gardens. There are about 5,200 permanent residents, 1,400 to 2,900 visitors and more than 400 tourists annually. It was established in the 17th century, shortly after the end of Roman rule.In 1801, Sydney became the capital of South Australia when William Howard Taft established a colony there.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton's third law. When a system expels or accelerates mass in one direction, the accelerated mass will cause a force of equal magnitude but opposite direction to be applied to that system.The force applied on a surface in a direction perpendicular or normal to the surface is also called thrust. Force, and thus thrust, is measured using the International System of Units (SI) in newtons (symbol: N), and represents the amount needed to accelerate 1 kilogram of mass at the rate of 1 meter per second per second.

Year 1107 ( MCVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Friday ( link is now gone) of the Roman calendar from 11 December to 1 January. The name was applied in some countries during the later middle ages, especially after the Council of Milan in 1215 that established a modified calendar as an international standard. From the Greek επικτία (krathātēma), meaning "day" in English, derived from the Hebrew term נִיעֹמֶר (kritis) which meant "day". The Jewish concept of Ḥokhta ("day-star") is also derived from it.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock, pop, jazz, or R&B music include a drummer for purposes including timekeeping and embellishing the musical timbre. The drummer's equipment includes a drum kit (or "drum set" or "trap set"), which includes various drums, cymbals and an assortment of accessory hardware such as pedals, standing support mechanisms, and drum sticks.Particularly in the traditional music of many countries, drummers use individual drums of various sizes and designs rather than drum kits.

The Stone Roses were an English rock band formed in Manchester in 1983 . One of the pioneering groups of the 80s, they were the first British rock bands to go head to head with the Beatles when they played their first ever gig in 1965 at Wembley Arena (now Wembley Stadium ). The band is currently one of the most successful and well-known rock bands in the world, with more than 150 million albums sold worldwide.During their early days, the Stone Roses were inspired by the folk rock scene of Britain, and many songs were written in the style of that period.

Pizza Hut is an American multinational restaurant chain and international franchise founded in 1958 in Wichita , Kansas by Dan Cathy. It has since grown into the most popular fast food chain in America, serving more than 70 million guests each year. In 2014, the company generated approximately US$3 billion in sales, a 6% gain over the previous year.It was started as a family-owned pizza establishment, and later became part of Pizza Hut's parent corporation, General Mills (later renamed KFC) after its acquisition by Yum Brands . The company went public on November 1, 1988.

The European Men 's Handball Championship is the official competition for senior men 's national handball teams of Europe and is played in association with the Federation Euroball. It takes place on five consecutive Saturdays throughout the year from 11 September to 20 November. John Lennon (  ; April 18, 1935 – July 24, 1975) was an American singer, songwriter, actor, producer, filmmaker, and activist who composed, sang, performed and recorded a variety of Beatles songs, including "White Christmas" and "She Loves You".

In quantum mechanics , counterfactual definiteness ( CFD ) is the ability to speak `` meaningfully '' of the definiteness of an event or thing, and to express its nature in a way that makes it clear how it could have occurred, or may have happened, in other circumstances. It's been a tough summer for the New Jersey Devils . In a season when the team has been forced to deal with injuries to three of its key players, including captain Henrik Sedin , the Devils lost out on goaltender Martin Brodeur , who underwent knee surgery at age 25.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez ( born 30 July 1948 ) , known as Jean Reno , is a French actor, known for his role as Pablo Escobar in the hit film Cartel Land. He is also known as Juan Manuel "Juan" Pérez Barrientos, who is also known as Joaquín Estrada, or simply "Jojo".Born in Barcelona on the 27th of September 1964, he was raised in Spain by his mother and grandmother. At age 10 years, he moved to London, England where he worked in films and television.

An airport is an aerodrome with extended facilities , mostly for commercial air transport . Airports often have facilities to handle larger planes. The United States is the largest and most developed state in the union with almost 3,200 airports. Air France (  :  ) was a regional airline of France. It operated direct flights from Paris-Rémy to London, as well as services to and from various terminals on the British continent. Air America (  : ), formerly Delta Air Lines Inc., is a privately held international passenger carrier. It owns, operates, and manages over 200 airports in North America.

Domenico Cimarosa ( ; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801 ) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school of music founded by Giovanni Giacometti. Born in Milan, Italy, at the age of 14 he studied under Giacometti, but did not have a particularly strong interest in music. He was born and trained in Venice, where he studied as an apprentice to Giacometti. ( ; 15 February 1773 – 29 June 1784) was an Italian composer who lived through the period known as the Renaissance. He composed works during the latter half of the fifteenth century, beginning with the work of his friend Francesco Rubellini .

Year 950 ( CML ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Australia. It is the sixth most populous state in Australia with more than 30 million inhabitants spread across an area of roughly 2.2 × 1.2 × 2,000 square kilometres. It is second to Tasmania in terms of urban population and third to NSW for per capita GDP, behind only Western Australia and Queensland. Contents show]
Early years Edit
The city of Pembroke became a city in A.D. 1799, when Charles Darwin purchased it from William Laudenbruch .

Tamar the Great ( , lit . `` King Tamar '' ) ( 1160 – 18 January 1213 ) reigned from 1212 to 1213. He succeeded his grandfather, Harpaz, who died on 24 December 1211. His mother, Amalekah, succeeded her as queen of Egypt after her brother's death in 1222 and ruled the country for a short period before abdicating in 1227.Tamar began building an economic empire around the Nile Valley that stretched into Mesopotamia and the Levant. He made important political contributions by developing a centralized system of civil service, appointing governors, consolidating the control of trade, and imposing strict laws for the maintenance of order.

`` The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas '' is a 1973 work of short philosophical fiction by American writer J.K. Rowling. It became the subject of a television show in the U.S.[1]Rowling was inspired to make the story about an orphan boy and his adoptive mother, who become separated during their marriage.The novel depicts the boy growing older and eventually becoming the father of a girl who later falls ill, though not before she discovers that there is a way to change the child's fate; she becomes the One Who Wakes.

Year 1155 (MCLV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Siege of Tortona: German forces capture the citadel of Tortona (after a two-month siege). The city is razed to the ground, including the graves. June 18 – King Frederick I (Barbarossa) is crowned as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire by Pope Adrian IV at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Arnold of Brescia is exiled by Adrian IV and forced to flee. He is arrested by imperial forces; hanged and his body burned at the stake in Rome.

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge, either by constitution, legislation, or judicial interpretation, without due process. Though the scope of the term differs between countries, civil liberties may include the freedom of conscience, freedom of press, freedom of religion, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, the right to security and liberty, freedom of speech, the right to privacy, the right to equal treatment under the law and due process, the right to a fair trial, and the right to life.

In economics , inflation refers to a general progressive increase in prices of goods and services in an economy . The rise in prices of items generally results from market-oriented increases in output that are caused by the increased consumption of consumer goods.The word inflation has also been applied to any decrease in real prices over time. This is sometimes known as short term interest rate inflation , long term inflation or permanent price inflation. Arithmetical proof (  ) is a mathematical process by which the solution to a particular equation can be proved with knowledge of all the previous solutions.

Hazardous waste is waste that has substantial or potential threats to public health or the environment.Characteristic hazardous wastes are materials containing radioactive isotopes, polychlorinated biphenyls, heavy metals, and chemicals. Gardener's Disease (GDS) is a rare neurological disease that affects humans who live in areas of low productivity. It affects many people, most often children. Symptoms of the disease may include severe weakness, muscle spasms, cognitive symptoms, and an inability to walk on their own.People with this disorder typically don't need medication.The cause of GDS is not known.

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one of a finite set of the same size. For example, it can be written:
Euler's Theorem  (e) Is the sum of three prime numbers that is an integer divisible by four and whose natural logarithm is less than 3. This conjecture is often known as "the elliptic curve" or "equation of the equinox". In modern mathematics, the conjecture has been proved for any sufficiently long sequence of integers, including the number of decimal digits in a digit-number representation of a floating-point number.

A bong ( also known as a water pipe ) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis , particularly in small quantities. Bongs come in various shapes and sizes depending on their type, size, age, style, etc. In most countries, they are available in different shapes, colors, materials, and sizes. Borla is an American rap group from the United States that formed in 1988. The group has released four studio albums and numerous songs since its formation. The group consists mainly of young musicians who began forming in their junior high school years.

The Illustrated Man is a 1951 collection of 18 science fiction short stories by American writer Ray Bradbury . A few of the stories were included as one-time collections for the Science Fiction Association of America in 1978, but only two of the stories have survived. The first story was "The Day That Never Comes" published in Time Travel magazine in January 1952, and the second was "The Devil in the White City" from February to December 1952. Lebanon (; ; ; ) , also called Lebanon, is an ethno-religious entity in the western Mediterranean region between Syria and the Lebanese coast.

Bristol  is a city, ceremonial county and unitary authority in England. Situated on the River Avon, it is bordered by the ceremonial counties of Gloucestershire, to the north; and Somerset, to the south. Bristol is the most populous city in South West England.The wider Bristol Built-up Area is the eleventh most populous urban area in the United Kingdom.Iron Age hill forts and Roman villas were built near the confluence of the rivers Frome and Avon, and around the beginning of the 11th century, the settlement was known as Brycgstow (Old English "the place at the bridge").

Porphyry (; , Porphyrios "purple-clad") may refer to: Porphyry (geology), an igneous rock with large crystals in a fine-grained matrix and important Roman building material  Porphyritic, the general igneous texture of a rock with two distinct crystal (phenocryst) sizes Porphyry copper deposit, a primary (low grade) ore deposit of copper, consisting of porphyry rocks Porphyry Island in Lake Superior  Porphyry Mountain in Alaska Porphyry (philosopher) (234–305), Neoplatonic philosopher Porphyry of Gaza (or "St. Porphyry of Gaza", 347–420), Bishop of Gaza Porfirije, Serbian Patriarch (b.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue. In the RGB color model used in computer and television screens, purples are produced by mixing red and blue light. In the RYB color model historically used by painters, purples are created with a combination of red and blue pigments. In the CMYK color model used in printing, purples are made by combining magenta pigment with either cyan pigment, black pigment, or both.Purple has long been associated with royalty, originally because Tyrian purple dye, made from crushed shells, was extremely expensive in antiquity.

Porphyry ( ; , Porphyrios `` purple-clad '' ) may refer to : Porphyry ( geology ) , an igneous rock from southwestern Europe that is older than the most recent volcanic systems, such as Gondwana. It was first brought to the Near East with the advent of agriculture. Proteins (  ), also called protein molecules, are a group of structural substances consisting of atoms or monomers in the nucleus of living cells. These proteins constitute about half the body's total energy stores, constituting approximately 50% of all cell mass.

Anthony John Hancock (12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1950s and early 1960s, he had a major success with his BBC series Hancock's Half Hour, first broadcast on radio from 1954, then on television from 1956, in which he soon formed a strong professional and personal bond with comic actor Sid James. Although Hancock's decision to cease working with James, when it became known in early 1960, disappointed many at the time, his last BBC series in 1961 contains some of his best-remembered work (including "The Blood Donor" and "The Radio Ham").

was the 69th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Suzaku's reign spanned the years from 1036 through 1045.This 11th-century sovereign was named after the 10th-century Emperor Suzaku and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Suzaku". The Japanese word "go" has also been translated to mean the "second one;" and in some older sources, this emperor may be identified as "Suzaku, the second" or as "Suzaku II.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia, and the Kingdom of Germany (Regnum Teutonicum), from the division of the Frankish Empire in 843 until the collapse of the German Empire in 1918.Note on titlesThe Kingdom of Germany started out as the eastern section of the Frankish kingdom, which was split by the Treaty of Verdun in 843. The rulers of the eastern area thus called themselves rex Francorum ("king of the Franks"), rex Francorum orientalium ("king of the East Franks"), and later just rex.

Year 881 (DCCCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 12 – King Charles the Fat, the third son of the late Louis the German, is crowned as Holy Roman Emperor by Pope John VIII at Rome. August 3 – Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu: The West Frankish kings Louis III, and his brother Carloman II, rout Viking raiders (near Abbeville). Britain  Battle of the Conwy: King Anarawd of Gwynedd (Wales) initiates a revenge attack on the Mercian armies, and defeats them on the River Conwy.

Albert the Magnanimous KG , elected King of the Romans as Albert II ( 10 August 139727 October 1439 ) and Emperor of the Romans as Constantine I ( 8 September 1441 ) by popular vote, became the first emperor of the Roman Empire to rule on a democratic system.In his early life, Albert was a nobleman who had been trained as a barber. His mother died when he was four years old, making him the only surviving son of Albert and Catherine of Burgundy . As a young man, Albert was educated at the Monasteries of Vienne and Beauvais.

Cranial nerves are the nerves that emerge directly from the brain ( including the brainstem ) , of which there are at least two types in the human body.The most significant type of nerve in the human body is the primary and secondary motor nerves. They are responsible for movement and range of motion, as well as pain sensation. The muscles of the upper limbs are also innervated by these nerves. Cranial nerves can be classified into three types:
Primary motor nociception (also known as  or   ). Nociceptive reflexes occur when the spinal cord is stimulated to produce involuntary movements of any kind.

Rubber, also called India rubber, latex, Amazonian rubber, caucho, or caoutchouc, as initially produced, consists of polymers of the organic compound isoprene, with minor impurities of other organic compounds. Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia are three of the leading rubber producers. Types of polyisoprene that are used as natural rubbers are classified as elastomers.Currently, rubber is harvested mainly in the form of the latex from the rubber tree (Hevea brasiliensis) or others. The latex is a sticky, milky and white colloid drawn off by making incisions in the bark and collecting the fluid in vessels in a process called "tapping".

This list of Anuran families shows all extant families of Anura . Anura is an order of animals in the family Aves (  ). It includes a number of other animals, although most are closely related and form part of the family Auroiidae. The family belongs to the Carnivora order, which has many species of vertebrates and several orders of insects.Anura was among the first mammalic groups to appear around 3.9 billion years old, shortly after the beginning of the Cambrian explosion about 3.5 billion years ago.The Anura genus contains nearly 500 species; they include birds, mammals, reptiles, amphibians, and invertebrates.

A complex system is a system composed of many components which may interact with each other . Examples of complex systems include electronic devices, sensors, computers, communications, electrical and mechanical systems, and the physical environment. The following are examples of basic complex systems that are generally used to describe an electronic circuit.An electronic circuit (sometimes also known as an integrated circuit) is a functional unit in an integrated circuit system which is part of a more complex electronic system. It may have multiple components and may be arranged as a single unit.

The unexpected hanging paradox or surprise test paradox is a paradox about a person 's expectations about the timing of events, including when events occur and how much time they take. In general, people's expectations may be too low. Hacking (also referred to as  'computer science hacking,' ) is any activity designed to make it difficult for another person to do an operation on the computer operating system used in a program to which the user has given permissions. If the intended recipient is also using the same operating system as the original program to which the data was written, the target software becomes unusable.

Nansen passports, originally and officially stateless persons passports, were internationally recognized refugee travel documents from 1922 to 1938, first issued by the League of Nations to stateless refugees. They quickly became known as "Nansen passports" for their promoter, the Norwegian statesman and polar explorer Fridtjof Nansen.HistoryThe end of World War I saw significant turmoil, leading to a refugee crisis. Numerous governments were toppled, and national borders were re-drawn, often along generally ethnic lines. Civil war broke out in some countries. Many people left their homes because of war or persecution or fear thereof.

Isis ( ; Ēse ; ; Meroitic : Wos [ a ] or Wusa ) was a major goddess in the ancient Near Eastern pantheon. In Judaism her name is Shem, although other versions include Shemoth, and Shem-el , meaning "Mother of Heaven".The origins of Islamic theology are unclear but she may have been part of the Jewish pantheon. Her name appears on the tomb stone of the first emperor of Persia (r. 462–47) at Khotan, where she is believed to have ruled. She was buried alongside other Persian gods.In the Book of Genesis, there are many references to Shem.

The Boeing CH-47 Chinook is a tandem rotor helicopter developed by American rotorcraft company Vertol and manufactured by Boeing Vertol under their subsidiary Aerojet Rocketdyne from 1980 until 1997. It is capable of operating up to 2,000 miles per hour (3,700 km/h). It was one of two commercial helicopters developed by Aerosoft for the U.S. Air Force.Boeing released its first three-rotor chopper in 1981 as the B-29 Superfortress, which could operate at speeds of 35 knots (50 kph) and has an impressive range of 7,500 miles (13,000 km). It was the second-best selling commercial helicopter ever sold after the Lockheed Martin T-38 trainer.

An ion thruster , ion drive , or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion and space flight, especially those in orbit around the Earth. It uses electricity generated during the combustion of fuel to push a small mass of propellant along an inertial control (IC) field. Ion thrusters have been used primarily for exploration purposes. A large-scale research effort was begun in the late 1980s by scientists at NASA Ames Research Center in Moffett Field, California, in response to concerns about the cost and environmental impact of developing such vehicles.

Relative density , or specific gravity , is the ratio of the density ( mass of a unit volume ) of a solid object to its relative density . The value can be defined as:where m is the length of a unit surface and λ is the area of a unit volume divided by 2.
