The equation for relative density at any point in space depends upon the physical properties of the object.A fluid is a gas that is incompressible at high pressure and temperature; thus it cannot be compressed to such a pitch as to be flowable. A fluid is also an insulator.

The RQ-3 DarkStar ( known as Tier III- or `` Tier three minus '' during development ) is an unmanned air reconnaissance aircraft produced by McDonnell Douglas. It represents a major step up in the operational capability of the RC-135S and its replacement, the DC-10. The aircraft is one of only a small number of military aircraft which can fly at high altitudes without being damaged beyond recognition. The vehicle's performance and design features combine to reduce its vulnerability to enemy air defense systems. [1]
Drake B-25G Thunderbolts
The B-25 has been the United States Air force's main airborne strike fighter for more than 60 years.

Year 1073 ( MLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) with a maximum of three days. The festival celebrated the resurrection of Saint Boniface from the dead, the return of saints to their former homes, and the reestablishment of the Roman Catholic Church in Rome after centuries of dissident movements. According to an 1884 article in the magazine "The American Literary Monthly" by J.D. MacNab, the day started on February 2, 1874, when Joseph Friese wrote: "Heaven, where art thou? Heaven, where art thou?

The M102 is a light, towable 105 mm howitzer used by the United States Army in the Vietnam War, the First Gulf War, and the Iraq War.Overview The M102 105 mm howitzer is used in air mobile (helicopter), attack plane, and light infantry operations. The weapon carriage is lightweight welded aluminum, mounted on a variable recoil mechanism. The weapon is manually loaded and positioned, and can be towed by a 2-ton truck or High Mobility Multipurpose Wheeled Vehicle (HMMWV), can be transported by UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters, or can be dropped by parachute with airborne units.

An infection is the invasion of an organism 's body tissues by disease-causing agents , their multiplication , and the spread or spread of the disease. It's no secret that we're dealing with some serious economic woes in the US right now, especially since the economy started to slow down more recently. However, this seems to have largely gone away in recent years, as the unemployment rate has dropped from 10.9% in September 2008 to 9.6% in November 2016. The world economy is dominated by industrial nations (i.e., developed and emerging economies), particularly the United States.

Paul Leo Molitor (born August 22, 1956), nicknamed "Molly" and "The Ignitor", is an American former Major League Baseball (MLB) player and former manager of the Minnesota Twins, who is in the Baseball Hall of Fame. During his 21-year baseball career, he played for the Milwaukee Brewers (1978–1992), Toronto Blue Jays (1993–1995), and Minnesota Twins (1996–1998). He was known for his exceptional hitting and speed. He made seven All-Star Game appearances, and was the World Series MVP in 1993.Molitor grew up in Minnesota and attended the University of Minnesota before beginning his MLB career.

Year 968 ( CMLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar )
In some languages the month of September or October is referred to in different ways than elsewhere. While English refers to the month in which the earth rotates, French and Italian call the months "August", "October", or "November" respectively, while the Roman Catholic Church names the months "September, October, November", "February, March". Tallulah Swisher, born August 11, 1950 in Detroit, Michigan, was an American actress, writer, model, and television host.

Mary Anning ( 21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847 ) was an English fossil collector , dealer , and author. He was born on 21 May 1799 in Prenton, Suffolk, to the Baroness Mary Anning and her two children. She studied at the University of Portsmouth and received a degree in natural science from the University of London before becoming a tutor in 1801. In 1807 he published his first collection of fossils in the Journal of the Geological Society.In 1814 Anning married Anne Broughton; by this time they had three children and were both educated at Trinity College, Cambridge.

Kannada ( ; ಕನ್ನಡ , ; less commonly known as Kanarese ) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the northern coastal states in south India. It is spoken primarily by an elite community of Tamil and Jain priests, many of whom have spent more than 300 years studying this language, to become teachers of other languages.The language's name means "heavenly language", and it is believed that it contains all aspects of divine knowledge and divinity.According to the Oxford English Dictionary, Kannada originated during the reign of Ramanuja ( 558-569 BC). The earliest recorded writing on Kannada comes from Vindaraṇḍananda's Kannadīya Brahmana, written circa 500 AD.

Year 878 (DCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Britain  January 6 – King Alfred the Great is surprised by a Viking attack at Chippenham. He is forced to flee, with his retinue, into the Somerset Levels for safety. From his headquarters at Athelney, Alfred wages a guerrilla war against the Vikings. May – Battle of Edington: Supported by all the levies of Somerset, Wiltshire and Hampshire, Alfred the Great decisively defeats the main body of Danish Vikings, led by King Guthrum, at present-day Edington (near Bratton Castle).

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death. He is one of the popes of the Byzantine Papacy. Described by a contemporary biographer as both just and learned, he is commemorated as a saint in the Roman Martyrology on 28 June (3 July, pre-1970 calendar).Early careerLeo was a Sicilian by birth, the son of a man named Paul. He may have ended up being among the many Sicilian clergymen in Rome due to the attacks of the Caliphate on Sicily in the mid-7th century.

Cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells . Cell division is the most important part of life.The number of dividing cells depends on their genetic makeup, growth rate, temperature, pH, environment and other factors. This can be done by altering the genetic material present in any cell. In genetics, the analysis of DNA (the sequence of nucleotide bases), RNA (a set of nucleotides) and protein (a chain of nucleotides) is considered to be at the center of biological information processing.

The putamen ( ; from Latin , meaning `` nutshell '' ) is a round structure located at the base of the ventral or inferior portion of the tragus that leads to the anteroposterior condyles. It is the second longest and most elongated phalanges in the penis and can extend from the scrotum to both sides of the external urethra. A typical putamen has a diameter ranging between 1.4 and 1.5 mm. Masturbating is one type of sexual activity in which sexual arousal is stimulated during masturbation. It is a voluntary act by the participant with the aim of relieving some physical pain caused by intercourse or oral sex.

Harriet Tubman ( born Araminta Ross , March 10 , 1913 ) was an American abolitionist and political activist .She was one of the most prominent United States abolitionists during the last decade of the nineteenth century. She was the first black person to serve in the House of Representatives, as a member of the House Unitarian Universalist Congregationalists from 1908 until her ouster in 1915. In that same year, however, she was arrested and imprisoned on various charges, including adultery, gambling, and domestic violence. After her release, Tubman sought refuge in Paris, where she became one of France's most prominent and best known figures.

Heavy Metal : F.A.K.K . 2 is a third-person shooter video game made by Ritual Entertainment in 2000 . The game focuses on the titular "Fatal Fury" which is a fictional fictional series of stories, loosely based on a real event that took place in the city of Moscow during the Soviet era.The game is set in a post-Soviet world and follows four main protagonists: Kolya, a journalist; Anton, a military intelligence operative; Yuri, a professor; and Mikhail, an engineer. They work for the same research company at the Institute of Military Science in Moscow.

East Malaysia , also known as Sabah, Sarawak and Labuan  or Malaysian Borneo, is the part of Malaysia on and near the island of Borneo, the world's third largest island. It consists of the Malaysian states of Sabah and Sarawak, as well as the Federal Territory of Labuan. Labuan is an island in a small archipelago near the coast of Sabah. East Malaysia lies to the east of Peninsular Malaysia (also known as West Malaysia), the part of the country on the Malay Peninsula. The two are separated by the South China Sea.East Malaysia is less populated and has less developed settlements than West Malaysia.

A monopropellant rocket (or "monochemical rocket") is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its propellant.Chemical-reaction monopropellant rocketsFor monopropellant rockets that depend on a chemical reaction, the power for the propulsive reaction and resultant thrust is provided by the chemical itself. That is, the energy needed to propel the spacecraft is contained within the chemical bonds of the chemical molecules involved in the reaction.The most commonly used monopropellant is hydrazine (N2H4), a chemical which is a strong reducing agent. The most common catalyst is granular alumina (aluminum oxide) coated with iridium.

Enriched uranium is a type of uranium in which the percent composition of uranium-235 (written 235U) has been increased through the process of isotope separation. Naturally occurring uranium is composed of three major isotopes:  uranium-238 (238U with 99.2739–99.2752% natural abundance), uranium-235 (235U, 0.7198–0.7202%), and uranium-234 (234U, 0.0050–0.0059%). 235U is the only nuclide existing in nature (in any appreciable amount) that is fissile with thermal neutrons.Enriched uranium is a critical component for both civil nuclear power generation and military nuclear weapons.

Year 874 ( DCCCLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) from the 6th day of October to the 25th day of November. It was divided into four days and included the feast of Saint Nicholas. John Paul II , who succeeded Benedict XVI in February 2003, is the fifth pontiff. The current pontiff holds the highest office in Catholic history: the title of Pontiff of the Catholic Church. He has become the world's sixth president of the Roman Catholic Church, and the third pope in a row when he took office in 2005.

was the 68th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō's reign spanned the years from 1016 through 1036.This 11th century sovereign was named after Emperor Ichijō and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Ichijō", or, in some older sources, may be identified as " Emperor Ichijō, the second. "BiographyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (imina) was Atsuhira -shinnō (敦成親王). He was also known as Atsunari-shinnō.Atsuhira was the second son of Emperor Ichijō.

The United Nations Foundation is a charitable organization headquartered in Washington, DC, that supports the United Nations and its activities. It was established in 1998 with a $1 billion gift to the United Nations by philanthropist Ted Turner, who believed the UN was crucial for addressing the world's problems. Originally primarily a grantmaker, the UN Foundation has evolved into a strategic partner to the UN, mobilizing support to advance the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), and help the UN address issues such as climate change, global health, gender equality, human rights, data and technology, peace, and humanitarian responses.

Don Carlos is a five-act grand opera composed by Giuseppe Verdi to a French-language libretto by Joseph Méry and Camille du Locle, based on the dramatic play Don Carlos, Infant von Spanien (Don Carlos, Infante of Spain) by Friedrich Schiller. In addition, several incidents, of which the Forest of Fontainebleau scene and auto-da-fé were the most substantial, were borrowed from Eugène Cormon's 1846 play Philippe II, Roi d'Espagne. The opera is most often performed in Italian translation, usually under the title Don Carlo. The opera's story is based on conflicts in the life of Carlos, Prince of Asturias (1545–1568).

The Magic Flute (German: , ), K. 620, is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart to a German libretto by Emanuel Schikaneder. The work is in the form of a Singspiel, a popular form during the time it was written that included both singing and spoken dialogue. The work premiered on 30 September 1791 at Schikaneder's theatre, the Freihaus-Theater auf der Wieden in Vienna, just two months before the composer's premature death. Still a staple of the opera repertory, its popularity was reflected by two immediate sequels, Peter Winter's Das Labyrinth oder Der Kampf mit den Elementen.

The lion (Panthera leo) is a large cat of the genus Panthera native to Africa and India. It has a muscular, deep-chested body, short, rounded head, round ears, and a hairy tuft at the end of its tail. It is sexually dimorphic; adult male lions are larger than females and have a prominent mane. It is a social species, forming groups called prides. A lion's pride consists of a few adult males, related females, and cubs. Groups of female lions usually hunt together, preying mostly on large ungulates.

Year 926 (CMXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The Italian nobles turn against King Rudolph II of Burgundy and request that Hugh of Provence, the effective ruler of Lower Burgundy, be elected as king of Italy. Rudolph's father-in-law Duke Burchard II of Swabia is ambushed and killed near Novara, by the henchmen of Archbishop Lambert of Milan. Rudolph, disillusioned by the news, returns to Burgundy to protect himself. Hugh has himself crowned King of Italy.

The European Organization for Nuclear Research , known as CERN ( ; ; derived from the name ) , is a German research institution in Geneva that is responsible for the physics, astronomy, mathematics, and space sciences. Located on what used to be Neustadtplatz in Germany, CERN has more than 400 scientists and researchers working in fields ranging from particle physics to astrophysics and materials science.CERN was founded in 1960 by Heinrich Hertz and Alexander Dubrovsky, who had originally wanted to build a nuclear power plant at Potsdam in Switzerland, but were denied funding by the United States.

Hebron ( ;  ) is a Palestinian city in the southern West Bank,  south of Jerusalem. Nestled in the Judaean Mountains, it lies  above sea level. The largest city in the West Bank, and the second largest in the Palestinian territories after Gaza, it has a population of over 215,000 Palestinians (2016), and seven hundred Jewish settlers concentrated on the outskirts of the Old City of Hebron. It includes the Cave of the Patriarchs, which Judeo-Christian and Islamic traditions all designate as the burial site of three key patriarchal/matriarchal couples.

Kingston is the capital and largest city of Jamaica , located on the southeastern coast of the island . It is the seat of the Royal Household of Jamaica . It is also the capital of Jamaica's North West Region, serving as both the regional government and the seat of the Governor General's Office. The Jamaican Cricket Board (JCB), a wholly-owned subsidiary of Indian conglomerate Reliance Industries , is the country's leading cricket association. Its activities cover three main areas: promoting cricket in Jamaica, ensuring that players develop their skills and confidence, and helping the sport be played effectively in all aspects of daily life.

Pietro Mascagni (7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas. His 1890 masterpiece Cavalleria rusticana caused one of the greatest sensations in opera history and single-handedly ushered in the Verismo movement in Italian dramatic music. While it was often held that Mascagni, like Ruggiero Leoncavallo, was a "one-opera man" who could never repeat his first success, L'amico Fritz and Iris have remained in the repertoire in Europe (especially Italy) since their premieres.Mascagni wrote fifteen operas, an operetta, several orchestral and vocal works, and also songs and piano music.

A luge is a small one- or two-person sled on which one sleds supine ( face up ) and feet-first to the surface of the water. The luge is best used in snowmobiles, where it is more maneuverable and lighter than most similar models.Luge racing was not common during the nineteenth century. The sport flourished during the second half of the decade when horses were able to compete with humans. Today, many competitions take place at ski resorts. Luge racing is often divided into two different sports, but both can still be found in mountain areas, especially in parts of western Europe and the U.S.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae ( from the Latin 'culiculus' means 'small) that is divided into 15 sub-species. Although they are closely related to other fly groups such as cicadas and millipedes, they are found in more diverse environments than those associated with their relatives.Insects can be classified into five groups depending on their ecological role. Insects typically have two pairs of legs arranged in a triangle shape, one side of which has three or four wings. This article was written by Andrew Winton, a Fellow of the Royal Institution of London.

KFC (also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville, Kentucky that specializes in fried chicken. It is the world's second-largest restaurant chain (as measured by sales) after McDonald's, with 22,621 locations globally in 150 countries . The chain is a subsidiary of Yum! Brands, a restaurant company that also owns the Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and WingStreet chains.KFC was founded by Colonel Harland Sanders, an entrepreneur who began selling fried chicken from his roadside restaurant in Corbin, Kentucky during the Great Depression.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand (26 October 19168 January 1996) served as President of France from 1981 to 1995, the longest time in office in the history of France. As First Secretary of the Socialist Party, he was the first left-wing politician to assume the presidency under the Fifth Republic.Reflecting family influences, Mitterrand started political life on the Catholic nationalist right. He served under the Vichy Regime during its earlier years. Subsequently he joined the Resistance, moved to the left, and held ministerial office several times under the Fourth Republic. Mitterrand opposed Charles de Gaulle's establishment of the Fifth Republic.

In the English language , the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people , especially African Americans, often in a negative manner. Niggers were historically considered to be dirty, untrustworthy and criminals, as well as "dirty slobs." Fritz Bock was an American physicist, mathematician, and inventor, most famous for inventing magnetic resonance theory (MRT). The concept of magnetism was first invented by German-born chemist Felix Bernoulli, in his 1912 book Electromagnetic Relativity. As a result of this, he coined the term electromagnets.

SPARC (Scalable Processor Architecture) is a reduced instruction set computing (RISC) instruction set architecture originally developed by Sun Microsystems. Its design was strongly influenced by the experimental Berkeley RISC system developed in the early 1980s. First developed in 1986 and released in 1987, SPARC was one of the most successful early commercial RISC systems, and its success led to the introduction of similar RISC designs from a number of vendors through the 1980s and 90s.The first implementation of the original 32-bit architecture (SPARC V7) was used in Sun's Sun-4 workstation and server systems, replacing their earlier Sun-3 systems based on the Motorola 68000 series of processors.

Henry Dunant (born Jean-Henri Dunant; 8 May 182830 October 1910), also known as Henri Dunant, was a Swiss humanitarian, businessman and social activist. He was the visionary, promoter and co-founder of the Red Cross. In 1901, he received the first Nobel Peace Prize together with Frédéric Passy, making Dunant the first Swiss Nobel laureate.During a business trip in 1859, Dunant was witness to the aftermath of the Battle of Solferino in modern-day Italy. He recorded his memories and experiences in the book A Memory of Solferino which inspired the creation of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in 1863.

The BBC World Service is an international broadcaster owned and operated by the BBC, with funding from the British Government through the Foreign Secretary's office. It is the world's largest external broadcaster in terms of reception area, language selection and audience reach. It broadcasts radio news, speech and discussions in more than 40 languages to many parts of the world on analogue and digital shortwave platforms, internet streaming, podcasting, satellite, DAB, FM and MW relays. In 2015, the World Service reached an average of 210 million people a week (via TV, radio and online).

Year 1107 (MCVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Scotland January 8 – King Edgar (the Valiant) dies at Edinburgh Castle after a 9-year reign. He is succeeded by his brother Alexander I (the Fierce), who is married to Sybilla of Normandy (an illegitimate daughter of King Henry I). A split of unity, between Alexander and his younger brother David I, makes David co-ruler in Lothian and Strathclyde (Southern Scotland). He does not receive the title of king, but of "Prince of the Cumbrians".

Melissa Sue Anderson (born September 26, 1962) is an American-Canadian actress. She began her career as a child actress after appearing in several commercials in Los Angeles. Anderson is known for her role as Mary Ingalls in the NBC drama series Little House on the Prairie (1974–1981), for which she received a nomination for the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series. She is also known for film roles that include Vivian in Midnight Offerings (1981), Ginny in the slasher film Happy Birthday to Me (1981), and Alex in the ABC Afterschool Special, Which Mother Is Mine?

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion ( SCUMM ) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games , later used on the then-unknown Star Wars franchise. It had previously been written to be an executable, but that was dropped when it became clear that making it run as a program was much harder than originally thought. Despite the original plan, the engine still runs and has been updated over the years, with major additions including 3D rendering, object detection and collision handling, audio processing, physics, scripting, and character generation. Cadmus is a fictional science fiction fantasy novel by A.E.

The War Game is a 1966 British pseudo-documentary film that depicts a nuclear war and its aftermath. Written, directed and produced by Peter Watkins for the BBC, it caused dismay within the BBC and also within government, and was subsequently withdrawn before the provisional screening date of 6 October 1965. The corporation said that "the effect of the film has been judged by the BBC to be too horrifying for the medium of broadcasting. It will, however, be shown to invited audiences..."The film eventually premiered at the National Film Theatre in London, on 13 April 1966, where it ran until 3 May.

A terrarium (plural: terraria or terrariums) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants, and can be opened for maintenance to access the plants inside. However, terraria can also be open to the atmosphere rather than being sealed. Terraria are often kept as decorative or ornamental items. Closed terraria create a unique environment for plant growth, as the transparent walls allow for both heat and light to enter the terrarium. The sealed container combined with the heat entering the terrarium allows for the creation of a small scale water cycle.

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare. Many of his history plays share the qualifiers of a Shakespearean tragedy, but because they are based on real figures throughout the history of England, they were classified as "histories" in the First Folio. The Roman tragedies—Julius Caesar, Antony and Cleopatra and Coriolanus—are also based on historical figures, but because their sources were foreign and ancient they are almost always classified as tragedies rather than histories. Shakespeare's romances (tragicomic plays) were written late in his career and published originally as either tragedy or comedy.

Audio Video Interleave ( also Audio Video Interleaved and known by its initials and filename extension AVI , usually pronounced "AJI") is a technique for synchronizing audio and video signals at the same rate. It requires two sources, either a conventional video source or an analog source, that provide equal frequencies to transmit audio and video data. These sources are sometimes referred to as audio and video interleave. An additional signal source, usually a digital television or satellite receiver, may also be added to enhance the transmission efficiency of one set of signals when viewed from another broadcast point.

is a Japanese manga series written and illustrated by Rumiko Takahashi . It was serialized in Big Comic Spirits from October to February 1997. The series centres around Shiori Tsuchiya ( 沙記, Tsuchiya Shiori) and the four siblings who live under her mother's roof.The story centers on the adventures of Shiori Tsuchiya as she tries to find meaning in what is becoming an unhappy life.In the first part of the series, Shiori is adopted by her biological mother's family; however, due to a genetic condition, she can only use her mother's words.

The RQ-3 DarkStar (known as Tier III- or "Tier three minus" during development) is an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV). Its first flight was on March 29, 1996. The Department of Defense terminated DarkStar in January 1999, after determining the UAV was not aerodynamically stable and was not meeting cost and performance objectives.Design and development The RQ-3 DarkStar was designed as a "high-altitude endurance UAV", and incorporated stealth aircraft technology to make it difficult to detect, which allowed it to operate within heavily defended airspace, unlike the Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk, which is unable to operate except under conditions of air supremacy.

Gregory Benford ( born January 30 , 1941 ) is an American science fiction author and astrophysicist who is Professor of Mathematics at Purdue University. He is also the winner of the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 1987. He is widely considered the father of computer science, which he helped define as a new way to use mathematics to design computers and other machines.He is one of only four members of the original Bell Labs team that created the IBM PC. Barry Goldwater (  b.  July 11, 1935), commonly called "The Eagle", was a Republican presidential candidate for President of the United States.

The 8 inch ( 203 mm ) M110 self-propelled howitzer is an American-made self-propelled artillery system consisting of an M115 main gun and an M117 light anti-tank rocket, also known as the APHE. It is used by the Army's 5th Brigade Combat Team or 4th Infantry Battalion, 2nd Division, 1st Cavalry Division, 101st Airborne Division, National Guard and many other U.S. Army Special Operations units, as well as by a variety of civilian law enforcement, security, and humanitarian missions worldwide. The M110 was developed as a follow-up to its predecessors, the M118 and M120 howitzers during the early 1970s.

Powaqqatsi (or Powaqqatsi: Life in Transformation) is a 1988 American non-narrative film directed by Godfrey Reggio and the sequel to Reggio's experimental 1982 film, Koyaanisqatsi. It is the second film in the Qatsi trilogy.Powaqqatsi is a Hopi neologism coined by Reggio meaning "parasitic way of life" or "life in transition". While Koyaanisqatsi focused on modern life in industrial countries, Powaqqatsi, which similarly has no dialogue, focuses more on the conflict in Third World countries between traditional ways of life and the new ways of life introduced with industrialization.

Anthony John Hancock ( 12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968 ) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1950s through to the 1980s, he began his acting career as a model when he was 20 years of age in 1949. Ongenia (from Greek: 𐌃 ́əηʯ) is a large tropical rain forest in the Pacific island nation of Kiribati. It has been called the "Kiribati Highlands", and is part of the country of Nauru.It covers 1.2 million square kilometres (900,000 square miles). The population of Angusta Cyclone Park stands at nearly 890,000, including approximately 1.1 million children under five years of age.

Year 1036 (MXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place Europe Summer – In Naples, Duke Sergius IV abdicates and retires to a monastery; he is succeeded by his son John V. A Zirid expeditionary force invades Sicily and takes Palermo from the Normans, but fails to fully reconquer the island. England  February 5 – Edward the Confessor's younger brother Alfred Aetheling is blinded and murdered, in an apparent attempt to seize the throne of England from Harold I. Africa  June 13 – Caliph al-Zahir li-i'zaz Din Allah dies after a 16-year reign.

The Jagiellonian University ( Polish : Uniwersytet Jagielloński ( UJ ) ) is a public research university in Kraków , Poland . It was founded in 1919 as a branch of Wrocław University. It has been called the "first public university in Poland", "the first European institution dedicated solely to human development, and its founding is regarded as one of the best achievements in post-war Western education." The school's current campus occupies a former railway station that served as the main railroad terminus during the Second World War, but it was not used for military purposes until the 1980s, when the site was converted into a park.

Martin Heidegger (; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976) was a German philosopher who is best known for contributions to phenomenology, hermeneutics, and existentialism. He is among  the most important and influential philosophers of the 20th century.In Heidegger's fundamental text Being and Time (1927), "Dasein" is introduced as a term for the type of being that humans possess. Dasein has been translated as "being there". Heidegger believes that Dasein already has a "pre-ontological" and non-abstract understanding that shapes how it lives. This mode of being he terms "being-in-the-world".

Crocodiles ( family Crocodylidae ) or true crocodiles are large semiaquatic reptiles that live throughout the tropics in Africa , Asia, South America, and parts of Europe and other regions. They are similar to the species of the genus Caiman but differ from it by being more elongated and a larger size. It can reach up to 8 feet (2 meters) in length and weigh as much as 60 pounds. Crocodiles are among the largest marine reptiles, reaching an average body length of 15 feet (5 metres) and weighing over 2,400 pounds (600 kilograms).

Pope Gregory VII ( ; 1015 – 25 May 1085 ) , born Hildebrand of Sovana , was head of the Church of the Holy Rosary in Milan for a quarter of a century. During this time, he was named patron saint of Christians by Pope Gregory IX ( 5 April 1082 – 29 January 1093 ), and later bishop of Pavia. He received the papal electorates of Pisa, Naples, and Bologna from the Pope after the Battle of Actium in 1094. Hernán Cortés was an Argentinian revolutionary during the First American Civil War between the United States and the Mexican government.

A musician is a person who composes , conducts , or performs music . According to the United States Employment Service , there are approximately 1.23 million musicians employed in the United States of America. Many musicians make a living as independent producers of music, but some earn income by appearing on TV shows, radio programs, and in advertisements. In this day and age, performing has become a medium for many performers to develop their skills and generate millions of dollars in profit. Grammar is a form of writing that distinguishes between nouns and verbs, such as speaking, making, etc.

Naval Submarine Base New London is the primary United States Navy East Coast submarine base, also known as the "Home of the Submarine Force." It is located in Groton, Connecticut directly across the Thames River from its namesake city of New London.HistoryIn 1868, the State of Connecticut gave the Navy  of land along the Thames River in Groton to build a Naval Station. Due to a lack of federal funding, it was not until 1872 that two brick buildings and a T-shaped pier were constructed and officially declared a Navy Yard.

An airport is an aerodrome with extended facilities, mostly for commercial air transport. Airports often have facilities to park and maintain aircraft, and a control tower. An airport consists of a landing area, which comprises an aerially accessible open space including at least one operationally active surface such as a runway for a plane to take off and to land or a helipad, and often includes adjacent utility buildings such as control towers, hangars and terminals. Larger airports may have airport aprons, taxiway bridges, air traffic control centres, passenger facilities such as restaurants and lounges, and emergency services.

SPARC ( Scalable Processor Architecture ) is a reduced instruction set computing ( RISC ) instruction set architecture originally developed in the 70s and early 80s, but that has since been adopted by other operating systems and architectures. The primary difference from the traditional microprocessor architecture of the 1980s is that its use of 16-bit addressing mode allows 32-bit floating point data to be delivered at high speed. It can run on 64-bit ARM processors or 32-bit x86 processors.In many ways, it shares more similarities to the Intel 8088 instruction set than with most contemporary microprocessors.

Powaqqatsi ( or Powaqqatsi : Life in Transformation ) is a 1988 American non-narrative film directed by Godfrey Reggio and starring George Pelecanos. It was originally released on DVD in 2000, followed by Blu-Ray and DVD in 2003. The film was adapted as a feature film in 1999 and features the voices of Al Pacino, Jeff Goldblum, Jennifer Connelly, and Michael Keaton. Palermo is a city in southern Italy. Palermo is located at the mouth of the Sargasso Sea on the northern coast of Italy. Its main industrial area is the Porto Cipriani, home to some of Italy's largest factories.

Activision Publishing, Inc. is an American video game publisher based in Santa Monica, California. It serves as the publishing business for its parent company, Activision Blizzard, and consists of several subsidiary studios. Activision is one of the largest third-party video game publishers in the world and was the top United States publisher in 2016.The company was founded as Activision, Inc. on October 1, 1979 in Sunnyvale, California, by former Atari game developers upset at their treatment by Atari in order to develop their own games for the popular Atari 2600 home video game console.

Eagle is the common name for many large birds of prey of the family Accipitridae . Eagles belong to several genera, including Abyllidae and Thalassiodontiformes. The only species of eagle observed by humans is the Eurasian spotted eagle, which was described by Olaus Magnus in 1622.In the Near East, eagles may be found in Turkey, Anatolia, southern Syria, Jordan, Egypt, and Iraq, where they are sometimes referred to as "white" eagles or "gray-eared eagles", since they are not white but rather dark-blue (or gray) in color, and have a darker wing crest than their black cousins.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA  ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States Department of Commerce that forecasts weather, monitors oceanic and atmospheric conditions, charts the seas, conducts deep sea exploration, and manages fishing and protection of marine mammals and endangered species in the U.S. exclusive economic zone.Purpose and functionNOAA's specific roles include: Supplying Environmental Information Products. NOAA supplies to its customers and partners information pertaining to the state of the oceans and the atmosphere, such as weather warnings and forecasts via the National Weather Service. NOAA's information services extend as well to climate, ecosystems, and commerce.

Numismatics is the study or collection of currency , including coins , tokens , paper money , medals and related objects . In its modern sense, it also includes the use of numismatic coinage to record economic transactions.There are two main kinds of numismatists : those who work directly under the authority of government (monarchy ) and those who provide financial services for a wide variety of institutions in various sectors of the society. Nigeria's President Muhammadu Buhari on Monday urged members of his ruling party to unite against the alleged corruption at the highest level of Nigerian politics as he called for new elections within seven years.

Oak Ridge National Laboratory ( ORNL ) is a U.S. multiprogram science and technology national laboratory sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy. It operates one of the world's two main research facilities: the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL) in Livermore, California. It also manages several interdisciplinary centers such as the Center for Quantum Computing at the International Centre for Quantum Information (ICTIC) in Potsdam, Germany.The University of New Hampshire was established under the authority of the State of New Hampshire in 1874. It is the largest state university in New Hampshire and the second-largest in the United States, with a population of 4.7 million.

The Illustrated Man is a 1951 collection of 18 science fiction short stories by American writer Ray Bradbury. A recurring theme throughout the stories is the conflict of the cold mechanics of technology and the psychology of people. It was nominated for the International Fantasy Award in 1952.The unrelated stories are tied together by the frame story of "The Illustrated Man", a vagrant former member of a carnival freak show with an extensively tattooed body whom the unnamed narrator meets. The man's tattoos, allegedly created by a time-traveling woman, are individually animated, and each tells a different tale.

Cotton is a soft , fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll , or protective case , around the body. It has many uses, such as making blankets, hats, shirts, scarves and other decorative fabrics. Its unique properties include elasticity, lightness and strength. Cotton is used for its distinctive spandexy quality and durability, as well as it's ability to be spun with little effort. Cobalt Bluegrass is a purplegrass of the species Cobalta crassifolia, native to the southern United States and western Canada from eastern North Dakota to Florida.

Great Barrier Island lies in the outer Hauraki Gulf , New Zealand , north-east of central Auckland . With an average elevation of 1.12m (7.3ft), it is a prime target for cyclones, and is one of the world's fastest-rising islands.It is home to approximately 2,000 inhabitants and has a population of more than 16,000 people. In recent years, it has witnessed rising sea levels as ocean levels have risen. Kerbal Space Program (sometimes abbreviated KSP) is a multiplayer online space flight sim developed by KISS Corporation. The current version of KSP released on August 15, 2008 is Version 3.

Yucatán ( , also , , ; ) , officially the Free and Sovereign State of Yucatán , is one of Mexico's major states and one of the largest in the Americas. It includes parts of the state of Chiapas, adjacent states of Guerrero, Oaxaca and Michoacán, as well as portions of the U.S. states of New Mexico, Oklahoma, Colorado, Utah, and Nevada. Armadillo ( ; , also ) was an ancient river system located in the south of the United States from the Gulf of California into the Great Lakes.

Dekker 's algorithm is the first known correct solution to the mutual exclusion problem in concurrent programming . The solution of the problem involves two steps. First, the program computes a sequence of numbers called the "probability tree" that points from the starting position to the end of the sequence, and then determines if there are at least two alternatives that lie beyond the next option. If there are two such alternatives, the program tries to find the largest possible order in the set. In this way, the probability tree gives the true order.

Twyla Tharp (; born July 1, 1941) is an American dancer, choreographer, and author who lives and works in New York City. In 1966 she formed the company Twyla Tharp Dance. Her work often uses classical music, jazz, and contemporary pop music.From 1971 to 1988, Twyla Tharp Dance toured extensively around the world, performing original works. In 1973 Tharp choreographed Deuce Coupe to the music of The Beach Boys for the Joffrey Ballet. Deuce Coupe is considered the first "crossover ballet", a mix of ballet and modern dance.

A mass driver or electromagnetic catapult is a proposed method of non-rocket spacelaunch which would use a linear motor to accelerate and catapult payloads up to high speeds. Existing and contemplated mass drivers use coils of wire energized by electricity to make electromagnets, though a rotary mass driver has also been proposed. Sequential firing of a row of electromagnets accelerates the payload along a path. After leaving the path, the payload continues to move due to momentum.Although any device used to propel a ballistic payload is technically a mass driver, in this context a mass driver is essentially a coilgun that magnetically accelerates a package consisting of a magnetizable holder containing a payload.

Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR ) is a method for allocating IP addresses and for IP routing. The Internet Engineering Task Force introduced CIDR in 1993 to replace the previous classful network addressing architecture on the Internet. Its goal was to slow the growth of routing tables on routers across the Internet, and to help slow the rapid exhaustion of IPv4 addresses.IP addresses are described as consisting of two groups of bits in the address: the most significant bits are the network prefix, which identifies a whole network or subnet, and the least significant set forms the host identifier, which specifies a particular interface of a host on that network.

An intranet is a computer network for sharing information , easier communication , collaboration tools , operational systems , and communications. In the early 1960s, the U.S. Naval Postgraduate School's Department of Computer Science started to experiment with a machine-learning program called Matlab. The project was funded by the U.S. Navy, but the program did not go through its planned design phase until 1975. As a result, Matlab had limited technical maturity and was designed in a more restricted way than would have been used in a real-world environment.The first generation of Matlab software was released in 1977 and later expanded into several variants.

The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade , twin-engine , medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft . Sikorsky developed the chopper to counter Soviet air power, but it has been used as an airborne reconnaissance and attack helicopter since its initial production in 1962.The first models were produced in 1968 and 1970, followed by further upgrades in 1972, 1973 and 1976. The final version (AVX-1) was delivered in 1979, and replaced the older aircraft with the AVX-9B variant in 1980.In addition to providing reconnaissance and attack roles, helicopters can be used for rescue and medical purposes.

Columbina ( in Italian Colombina , meaning `` little dove '' ; in French and English Colombine ) is a city in Southern California, the largest of its county, located on the west side of San Francisco Bay. Founded in 1853, it's one of the first cities to be built as part of the Transcontinental Railroad System, an intercity railroad that linked Chicago and San Francisco during the 1850s. It became a magnet for people from all over the world who came seeking work in manufacturing or ranching, and the city soon had a thriving music scene, as well as a popular film industry.

A software bug is an error , flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect output. Bugs cause errors to appear when a program performs some operation that does not work as expected. It can also cause other programs to crash at the exact same time because of the mistake.Computer systems (and, in particular, operating systems and software) do not always follow a set of rules about what is permitted and what is not on their systems. This is especially true of applications written for the most part by third parties, who often modify their own code to handle different operating systems and hardware.

In mathematics , the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution ) , also known as the unit impulse symbol , is a mathematical function describing the change in velocity of an object over time with respect to a stationary line.The equation is defined as:
The Dirac delta formula is commonly used to quantify changes in velocity due to a gravitational force. It can be used to make measurements on surfaces such as ice crystals, particles and other fluids, which are subject to a large degree of friction during cold weather conditions. Its importance lies in its ability to measure changes in velocity without using additional equipment.

The Space Shuttle program was the fourth human spaceflight program carried out by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) between 1977 and 1992, when it became the only major aerospace program of its time. After the death of Apollo 11 Commander James Lovell in July 1969, Congress approved a bill to extend NASA's manned spaceflight until January 2023. Atom bomb  is a nuclear explosive device with a mass of about 1000 kg and a muzzle velocity of 500 m/s, typically used as a secondary or a weapon. A conventional thermonuclear warhead that weighs no more than a kiloton is known as a "subatomic" bomb.

A gold standard is a monetary system in which the standard economic unit of account is based on a fixed quantity of gold. The gold standard was the basis for the international monetary system from the 1870s to the early 1920s, and from the late 1920s to 1932 as well as from 1944 until 1971 when the United States unilaterally terminated convertibility of the US dollar to gold foreign central banks, effectively ending the Bretton Woods system. Many states still hold substantial gold reserves.Historically, the silver standard and bimetallism have been more common than the gold standard.

Tilburg  is a city and municipality in the Netherlands, in the southern province of North Brabant. With a population of 222,601 (1 July 2021), it is the second-largest municipality in North Brabant and seventh-largest in the Netherlands.Tilburg University is located in Tilburg, as are Avans University of Applied Sciences and Fontys University of Applied Sciences. Tilburg is known for its ten-day-long funfair, held in July each year. The Monday during the funfair is called "Roze Maandag" (Pink Monday), and is primarily LGBT-oriented.There are three railway stations within the municipality: Tilburg, Tilburg Universiteit and Tilburg Reeshof.

Year 1103 ( MCIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar in early November. The Gregorian calendar , commonly abbreviated GP, was originally invented by Johannes Kepler in 1747 to represent the years 1681–1682 and 1701–1705 (in the modern calendar). It was first approved and standardized by Pope Innocent IV in 1562. The name came into use shortly after Galileo's discoveries that the motions of heavenly bodies moved at the same rate as the Earth did. For example, Jupiter and the moon both revolve about the Earth at one second per year.

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine. Many physicians and patients use the term lumbar disc disease to encompass several different causes of back pain or sciatica. In this article, the term is used to describe a lumbar herniated disc. It is thought that lumbar disc disease causes about one-third of all back pain.SymptomsPain, loss of muscle strength and loss of touch sensation may occur if this herniation causes the compression of the most proximal part of the nerve closely neighbouring the intervertebral disc material.

North America 's first transcontinental railroad ( known originally as the `` Pacific Railroad '' and later as the `` Pacific Division Rail Road'' ) was established in 1914 to provide transportation between New York and San Francisco in the wake of the Great Depression. During World War II, it was transferred to the Western Hemisphere and served the Pacific coast of North America until 1959 when it began a new route across the U.S. to Hawaii . In 1960, it was acquired by General Motors-New York City and became the  Union Pacific Railway (UPPR) . The United States has been a landlocked country from its earliest days.

East Malaysia , also known as Sabah , Sarawak and Labuan or Malaysian Borneo , is the part of Malaysia that lies in the Western Peninsula of Southeast Asia. It covers a geographical area of just over 12,500km (7,700 miles) and extends from the north-west of Peninsular Malaysia to the west coast of Sumatra and the Indonesian islands. Its land mass is about 9,000 km (4,600 miles) long and consists of two main areas, Sengkawi National Park and Pangkalan Bun . The Aljunied are one of four alpine regions in the Himalaya Mountains of southern China's Xinjiang Autonomous Region (Uighur Autonomous Region).

In linguistics , an adjective ( abbreviated ) is a word that modifies a noun or noun phrase or describes an action.An adjective in its original sense would have no meaning but has come to be accepted as such in the modern lexicon. In this sense, an adjective is often regarded as describing an object or state of being—as a concept. Some adjectives are used by different speakers and are therefore interchangeable. Etude  is an informal term for a style of dance performance characterized by improvisational gestures performed in an open, casual manner. Ettude music can consist of many variations from standard orchestral arrangements to other styles of music.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion (SCUMM) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games, later renamed LucasArts, to ease development on their graphic adventure game Maniac Mansion (1987). It was subsequently used as the engine for later LucasArts adventure games.It falls somewhere between a game engine and a programming language, allowing designers to create locations, items and dialogue sequences without writing code in the language in which the game source code ends up. This also allowed the game's script and data files to be cross-platform, i.e., re-used across various platforms.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard , who developed the term "spaceplane" to describe a system using ramjet engines that could fly on the ground. The Bussard scheme relies on the power supply, air and propellant for the spaceplane to remain stable and allow maneuvering throughout flight.It has since been used successfully in numerous experiments, most recently as NASA's Lunar Orbiter (LOL) and Solar Orbiter (SOLI). Beth Ann Smith is an American television personality, host, actress, and writer.

Cotton is a soft, fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll, or protective case, around the seeds of the cotton plants of the genus Gossypium in the mallow family Malvaceae. The fiber is almost pure cellulose, and can contain minor percentages of waxes, fats, pectins, and water. Under natural conditions, the cotton bolls will increase the dispersal of the seeds.The plant is a shrub native to tropical and subtropical regions around the world, including the Americas, Africa, Egypt and India. The greatest diversity of wild cotton species is found in Mexico, followed by Australia and Africa.

While a significant majority of water vessels are powered by diesel engines, with sail power and gasoline engines also popular, boats powered by electricity have been used for over 120 years. Electric boats were very popular from the 1880s until the 1920s, when the internal combustion engine became dominant. Since the energy crises of the 1970s, interest in this quiet and potentially renewable marine energy source has been increasing steadily, especially as more efficient solar cells have become available, for the first time making possible motorboats with an infinite range like sailboats. The first practical solar boat was probably constructed in 1975 in England.

ESP most commonly refers to : Extrasensory perception , a paranormal ability Spain ( España ) - ISO three-letter country code; the Spanish are known for being the third largest economy and second largest source of skilled workers in Europe with over 100,000 Spaniards employed in construction, food services, and manufacturing. From its earliest times, the Spanish empire stretched into northern India, as well as North Africa and western Asia. It had an important naval presence during the last two hundred years, but eventually fell victim to colonialism.The population is about 4.1 million people, of whom around 1.8 million are members of indigenous peoples.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683 ) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death on 24 December 711, at the age of 91. He is generally regarded as the last of the Roman Emperors and probably the founder of the Church of Rome itself.He succeeded his grandfather, Gregory VII , as Emperor on 26 July 673. The reign of his son Pope John I (7 February 731) ended in 746, and that of his heir, Pope Michael III (8 January 762), in 785.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975 . The show was a collaboration between Richard Burton, John Cleese and Terry Jones. The series also inspired the film Blackadder, which debuted on 1 September 1976.The story focuses on a group of street traders who come to London during the early hours of Christmas Eve, hoping for a better deal than their usual customers. They make deals with a black market dealer (played by George Bernard Shaw), known as "Black Jack", in hopes of being able to increase their profits.

Svante August Arrhenius ( , ; 19 February 1859 – 2 October 1927 ) was a Swedish scientist . Originally an engineer in the Department of Mechanical Engineering at the University of Copenhagen, he went on to become one of the foremost inventors of mechanical systems in Sweden. In his pioneering work on the development of light-emitting diodes (LED), he demonstrated that they could be used to project light from different types of light source across a broad spectrum of wavelengths.In the last decades of his life, he became widely regarded as one of Sweden's leading light designers.

Concurrent Versions System ( CVS , also known as the Concurrent Versioning System ) is a revision control system originally developed for Microsoft Windows to make version-specific data easier to manage and to maintain. It has become a widely accepted part of today's Unix operating system environment, and runs on modern Mac OS X, Windows and Linux systems.CVS was originally created by Richard L. Carmack in the late 1970s as an open-source replacement for Unix's Unix-compatible shell, called BASH or Bourne Shell. It eventually took on the name MS-DOS which stood for Multimedia System.

Pope Leo V was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from July 903 to his death in February 904. He was pope during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum, when popes wielded little temporal authority.Leo V was born at a place called Priapi, near Ardea. Although he was a priest when he was elected pope following the death of Pope Benedict IV (900–903), he was not a cardinal priest of Rome.During his brief pontificate, Leo granted the canons of Bologna a special bull (epistola tuitionis) where he exempted them from the payment of taxes.

Menstruation ( also known as a period and many other colloquial terms ) is the regular discharge of blood and other secretions into the uterine cavity from the endometrium, a part of the female reproductive tract.A woman may be pregnant when she or her menstrual bleeding is normal but not enough to give birth, because the uterus cannot support the baby. However, in some cases, severe bleeding can lead to pregnancy. Lazarus was a Roman emperor during the second century BCE. He is best known for being the only one of his empire to remain unburied. He died in 44 BCE, at age 63.

The covalent radius, rcov, is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one covalent bond. It is usually measured either in picometres (pm) or angstroms (Å), with 1 Å = 100 pm.In principle, the sum of the two covalent radii should equal the covalent bond length between two atoms, R(AB) = r(A) + r(B). Moreover, different radii can be introduced for single, double and triple bonds (r1, r2 and r3 below), in a purely operational sense.

Robert Ross is an American blues singer , songwriter , acoustic and electric guitarist , slide guitarist , and harmonica virtuoso.Ross is best known as the founder and lead singer of the band, The Jackson Five, a rock band who released three studio albums between 1960 and 1970.His most significant hit to date was "Ain't It a Shame", written for the 1956 film, "Mulholland Drifts".He has sold over 25m albums worldwide, and continues to be highly sought-after in the music business.In 1965, he co-wrote the first song recorded on a synthesizer, with James Brown.

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event , usually denoting the 25th , 40th , 50th , 60th , or 70th anniversary of a religious event. There are many forms of anniversaries; however, there are three fundamental ones for Israel: one commemorated annually as the Feast of Tishreen, one to commemorate the liberation of Jerusalem from Jordanian occupation, and one celebrated on Passover day.All other major Jewish observances during a given year have been secular.The term was created by the rabbinic community in the 18th century, when it was applied to festivals celebrating various events, such as sabbath observances, Passover services, and Shabbat.

(; "The Master-Singers of Nuremberg"), WWV 96, is a music drama, or opera, in three acts, by Richard Wagner. It is the longest opera commonly performed, taking nearly four and a half hours, not counting two breaks, and is traditionally not cut. With Hans von Bülow conducting it was first performed on 21 June 1868 at the National Theater in Munich, today home of Bavarian State Opera.The story is set in Nuremberg in the mid-16th century. At the time, Nuremberg was a free imperial city and one of the centers of the Renaissance in Northern Europe.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury, Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket (21 December 1119 or 1120 – 29 December 1170), was Archbishop of Canterbury from 1162 until his murder in 1170. He is venerated as a saint and martyr by the Catholic Church and the Anglican Communion. He engaged in conflict with Henry II, King of England, over the rights and privileges of the Church and was murdered by followers of the king in Canterbury Cathedral. Soon after his death, he was canonised by Pope Alexander III.SourcesThe main sources for the life of Becket are a number of biographies written by contemporaries.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky  (6 April 1971) was a Russian composer, pianist and conductor, later of French (from 1934) and American (from 1945) citizenship. He is widely considered one of the most important and influential composers of the 20th century and a pivotal figure in modernist music.Stravinsky's compositional career was notable for its stylistic diversity. He first achieved international fame with three ballets commissioned by the impresario Sergei Diaghilev and first performed in Paris by Diaghilev's Ballets Russes: The Firebird (1910), Petrushka (1911), and The Rite of Spring (1913).

Mobile Bay is a shallow inlet of the Gulf of Mexico , lying within the state of Alabama in the State of Alabama and extending southward into Louisiana. Boracay, also known as Boracarica, is a small island nation of around 300,000 inhabitants located at the northern tip of the Caspian Sea . It is approximately 5°38' east longitude and 1°20' west longitude from the Azores Islands.It is part of Spain, Portugal and Turkey and borders Russia on the south, China and Afghanistan on the north, Central Asia on the southeast and the Persian Gulf to the north.

Genus  (plural genera ) is a taxonomic rank used in the biological classification of living and fossil organisms as well as viruses. In the hierarchy of biological classification, genus comes above species and below family. In binomial nomenclature, the genus name forms the first part of the binomial species name for each species within the genus.E.g. Panthera leo (lion) and Panthera onca (jaguar) are two species within the genus Panthera. Panthera is a genus within the family Felidae.The composition of a genus is determined by taxonomists. The standards for genus classification are not strictly codified, so different authorities often produce different classifications for genera.

An anti-tank guided missile (ATGM), anti-tank missile, anti-tank guided weapon (ATGW) or anti-armor guided weapon is  a guided missile primarily designed to hit and destroy heavily armored military vehicles. ATGMs range in size from shoulder-launched weapons, which can be transported by a single soldier, to larger tripod-mounted weapons, which require a squad or team to transport and fire, to vehicle and aircraft mounted missile systems.Earlier man-portable anti-tank weapons like anti-tank rifles and magnetic anti-tank mines, generally had very short range, sometimes on the order of metres or tens of metres.

Alain Marie Pascal Prost ( born 24 February 1955 ) is a French retired racing driver . A four-time Formula One world champion with Ferrari, and five times a Formula One world champion with Renault, he has won three drivers' championships, the only Frenchman to achieve such success in that series. He holds both F1 and F3 world championship titles.He is one of the greats of the sport at his most dominant, dominating every year of his career, beginning with his first season in 1973, before reaching a peak of 11 wins from 1981 to 1986.

The Porsche 914 or VW-Porsche 914 is a mid-engined sports car designed, manufactured and marketed collaboratively by Volkswagen and Porsche from 1969 until 1976. It was only available as a targa-topped two-seat roadster powered by either a flat-4 or flat-6 engine.HistoryPre-development By the late 1960s, both Volkswagen and Porsche were in need of new models; Porsche was looking for a replacement for their entry-level 912, and Volkswagen wanted a new range-topping sports coupé to replace the Volkswagen Type 34 Karmann Ghia coupé. At the time the majority of Volkswagen's development work was handled by Porsche as part of an agreement that dated back to Porsche's founding.

Risk is a strategy board game of diplomacy , conflict and conquest for two to six players . The standard set comes with over 40 cards and includes the following:An optional rulebook is included that covers the mechanics, options, rules, and general strategy of the game.Players may play their units on a variety of different terrain types including forests, mountains, plains, jungles, marshlands, deserts, lakes, sea lanes, and riverbeds (see below). Gemini was a computer-based role-playing game developed by Dennaton, an American company based in Indianapolis.

Yorkshire pudding is a baked pudding made from a batter of eggs, flour, and milk or water. A common English side dish, it is a versatile food that can be served in numerous ways depending on its ingredients, size, and the accompanying components of the meal. As a first course, it can be served with onion gravy. For a main course, it may be served with meat and gravy, and is part of the traditional Sunday roast, but can also be filled with foods such as bangers and mash to make a meal.

Scooby-Doo is an American animated franchise comprising many animated television series produced from 1969 to the present , as well as several feature films.The show was developed by Bob Iger for Walt Disney Television, which was acquired by ABC in 1999. The series started airing in October 1966, and later continued on syndication for five more years under various different titles. The first three episodes premiered on October 25, 1966 and ended on January 31, 1971. Caveat Emptor: It is not known whether Caveat Eversatz is used in any legal context.

Jobst of Moravia ( or Jošt Lucemburský ; or Jodokus von Mähren ; c. 1354 – 18 January 1411 ) is a Swedish king who ruled as the third and most powerful duke of Moraviae during the late 15th century. José Martínez Barroso (born October 29, 1946) is a Brazilian football manager who served as coach of the Brazil national soccer team for eight years between 2006 and 2010. He guided the team to an 11th-place finish in the 2002 Confederations Cup, but was then fired following defeat against Argentina in the World Cup final in Brazil.

A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied, tailless amphibians composing the order Anura (literally without tail in Ancient Greek). The oldest fossil "proto-frog" Triadobatrachus is known from the Early Triassic of Madagascar, but molecular clock dating suggests their split from other amphibians may extend further back to the Permian, 265 million years ago. Frogs are widely distributed, ranging from the tropics to subarctic regions, but the greatest concentration of species diversity is in tropical rainforest. Frogs account for around 88% of extant amphibian species.

Mystery religions , mystery cults , sacred mysteries or simply mysteries , were religious schools of the Greco-Roman world for centuries. They are generally recognized today by a number of different names and have been grouped into diverse sub-groups, such as Hermetic, Druidic, Tantra, Christian Gnosticism, Taoism, and Wicca. The term Mystery religion has been applied to all kinds of mystical or religious practices performed by occultists, in both traditional and modern contexts. Masonry is the most famous Freemasonry fraternity, which began in 1776 under its founder, George Washington, and was originally composed of about 1,700 members.

Montague Rhodes James ( 1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936 ) was an English author , medievalist scholar and historian. A professor of theology at Cambridge University, he also spent some time as head of the Anglican Church in Wales. He has written widely on the cultural, historical and religious aspects of Christianity.James served as Bishop of Winchester from 1845 to 1849. He was rector of Westminster Abbey before his retirement in 1859. His early interest in literature and religion attracted attention from several well-known writers, most notably Robert Louis Stevenson, who wrote The Magician's Apprentice for James.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock , pop , jazz and metal are usually drummers, while the genre's history stretches over thousands of years. A drummer has an instrument with which they work in a musical context. They may be a bassist, guitarist, drummer, keyboardist, organist, singer, songwriter, or both. Dance (northern Italian) is one of the major styles of music in northern Europe and the world. This term is frequently used to cover a wider range of dance styles than dance music itself, particularly in Northern Europe.

Medina, officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah  and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in Islam and the capital of the Medina Province of Saudi Arabia. , the estimated population of the city is 1,488,782, making it the fourth-most populous city in the country. Located at the core of the Medina Province in the western reaches of the country, the city is distributed over , of which  constitutes the city's urban area, while the rest is occupied by the Hejaz Mountains, empty valleys, agricultural spaces and older dormant volcanoes.Medina is generally considered to be the "cradle of Islamic culture and civilization".

John D. Carmack II ( born August 20 , 1970 ) is an American computer programmer and video game developer, known for his design of Doom and Quake as well as contributions to several games, including Quake Live. In 2001, he was named the fifth most influential person in technology by The Times. He also has a number of patents from which he received income.Born in New York, Carmack attended Brooklyn Technical High School in the 1960s and graduated with a degree in computer science. During the next few years, Carmack dropped out of college and became a software engineer at Microsoft.

Turandot ( , ; see below) is an opera in three acts by Giacomo Puccini, posthumously completed by Franco Alfano in 1926, and set to a libretto in Italian by Giuseppe Adami and Renato Simoni. Turandot best-known aria is "Nessun dorma", which became globally popular in the 1990s following Luciano Pavarotti's performance of it for the 1990 FIFA World Cup.Though Puccini first became interested in the subject matter when reading Friedrich Schiller's 1801 adaptation, he based his work more closely on the earlier play Turandot (1762) by Count Carlo Gozzi.

Pope Leo IV (790 – 17 July 855) was the bishop of Rome and ruler of the Papal States from 10 April 847 to his death. He is remembered for repairing Roman churches that had been damaged during the Arab raid against Rome, and for building the Leonine Wall around Vatican Hill to protect the city. Pope Leo organized a league of Italian cities who fought and won the sea Battle of Ostia against the Saracens.Early careerA Roman by birth, Leo received his early education at Rome in the monastery of St. Martin, near St. Peter's.

The boa knot is a modern binding knot invented by weaver Peter Collingwood in 1996 . His intention was to make the knot less cumbersome when tied with a cord. It now has over half a million sold worldwide. Boa, also known as wattle,  wattle and  bellows (    ), is a large species of bamboo which grows on tropical islands in Asia and Africa. It is widespread along many tropical regions in the Pacific region and is widely planted for ornamental purposes. These bamboo species can grow to lengths of more than 100 cm and are often referred to as  bamboo stumps.

A musician is a person who composes, conducts, or performs music. According to the United States Employment Service, "musician" is a general term used to designate one who follows music as a profession. Musicians include songwriters who compose music as well as write lyrics for songs, conductors who direct a musical performance, or performers who perform for an audience. A music performer is generally either a singer who provides vocals or an instrumentalist who plays a musical instrument. Musicians may perform on their own or as part of a group, band or orchestra.

Hugh John Lofting ( 14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947 ) was an English author trained as a civil engineer in London before studying medicine at Oxford, and then becoming a doctor himself. In 1911 he became Professor of Dentistry at the University of Manchester, where he also worked under his father, Professor Robert Lonsdale. He left Manchester for Paris in 1921, and later remained in that city as Professor of Dentistry until his untimely death in 1950. His work with dentistry is described in numerous books, articles and scholarly articles.

Charles University, known also as Charles University in Prague ( (UK); ; ) or historically as the University of Prague , is the oldest and largest university in the Czech Republic. It is one of the oldest universities in Europe in continuous operation. Today, the university consists of 17 faculties located in Prague, Hradec Králové, and Plzeň. The Charles University belongs to top three universities in Central and Eastern Europe. It is ranked around 200–300 in the world.HistoryMedieval university (1349–1419)The establishment of a medieval university in Prague was inspired by Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV.

Clothing (also known as clothes, apparel, and attire) are items worn on the body. Typically, clothing is made of fabrics or textiles, but over time it has included garments made from animal skin and other thin sheets of materials and natural products found in the environment, put together. The wearing of clothing is mostly restricted to human beings and is a feature of all human societies. The amount and type of clothing worn depends on gender, body type, social factors, and geographic considerations. Garments cover the body, footwear covers the feet, gloves cover the hands, while hats and headgear cover the head.

Show jumping, is a part of a group of English riding equestrian events that also includes dressage, eventing, hunters, and equitation. Jumping classes are commonly seen at horse shows throughout the world, including the Olympics. Sometimes shows are limited exclusively to jumpers, sometimes jumper classes are offered in conjunction with other English-style events, and sometimes show jumping is but one division of very large, all-breed competitions that include a very wide variety of disciplines. Jumping classes may be governed by various national horse show sanctioning organizations, such as the United States Equestrian Federation in the USA or the British Showjumping Association in Great Britain.

Australian Signals Directorate ( ASD ; until 2013 : Defence Signals Directorate , DSD ) is the Australian government agency responsible for national security signals intelligence, including electronic intelligence gathering. Its principal function is to collect, analyse, communicate and interpret digital signals, both in the physical world and in space. ASD works with foreign governments, defence, telecommunications companies, broadcasters, international organizations and academic institutes across Australia. ASD is funded by the Commonwealth of Australia, a member state of the United Nations, as well as Australia's strategic alliance commitments. It operates a number of satellites and other communications systems.

was the 70th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Reizei's reign spanned the years 1045–1068.This 11th century sovereign was named after the 10th century Emperor Reizei and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Reizei". The Japanese word "go" has also been translated to mean the "second one;" and in some older sources, this emperor may be identified as "Reizei, the second," or as "Reizei II.

The Novikov self-consistency principle , also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven 's law of conservation of energy, states that:
There are infinite sets containing all possible sets. One can never know whether such a set contains all sets. There exists an infinite number of such sets; there is no contradiction between being a subset of one such set and being a whole set. In fact, it may be argued that for each such element x there exists an infinity of corresponding elements beyond x. An empty set is a pair of elements without elements, i.e.

( All Women Do It , or The School for Lovers ) , K. 588 , is an opera buffa, who lived in Milan from about 1430 to 1504. During the 16th Century she was known for her virtuosic concert performances of Beethoven's Second Symphony. In the early 17th Century, she was regarded as the "Queen of the Opera", and was frequently ranked as one of the most beautiful singers in Italy.Her operas are usually performed in a style similar to Mozart's, but more modern and sophisticated (for example, there are often dramatic changes in setting and mood).

Bruce Lee (; November 27, 1940 – July 20, 1973), born Lee Jun-fan , was a Hong Kong and American martial artist, martial arts instructor, actor, director, screenwriter, producer, and philosopher. He was the founder of Jeet Kune Do, a hybrid martial arts philosophy drawing from different combat disciplines that is often credited with paving the way for modern mixed martial arts (MMA). Lee is considered by critics, media, and other martial artists to be the most influential martial artist of all time and a pop culture icon of the 20th century, who bridged the gap between East and West.

The Arctic ( or ) is a polar region located at the northernmost part of Earth . The Arctic consists of roughly 545,000 square kilometers of land and sea with an average ice cover of 27.6 million square kilometers (the highest ice level on the planet). There are no inhabited islands, but there are a few small communities in the areas known as Inuit, Askiin, and Aleutian Islands along the west coast of the North Atlantic Ocean off the coast of Alaska.The area contains approximately 11% of the Earth's surface, making it the largest land mass in the world.

Tristan Tzara (; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock, also known as S. Samyro;  – 25 December 1963) was a Romanian and French avant-garde poet, essayist and performance artist. Also active as a journalist, playwright, literary and art critic, composer and film director, he was known best for being one of the founders and central figures of the anti-establishment Dada movement. Under the influence of Adrian Maniu, the adolescent Tzara became interested in Symbolism and co-founded the magazine Simbolul with Ion Vinea (with whom he also wrote experimental poetry) and painter Marcel Janco.

A supercomputer is a computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer. The performance of a supercomputer is commonly measured in floating-point operations per second (FLOPS) instead of million instructions per second (MIPS). Since 2017, there are supercomputers which can perform over 1017 FLOPS (a hundred quadrillion FLOPS, 100 petaFLOPS or 100 PFLOPS).
