The Arctic ( or ) is a polar region located at the northernmost part of Earth. The Arctic consists of the Arctic Ocean, adjacent seas, and parts of Alaska (United States), Canada, Finland, Greenland (Denmark), Iceland, Norway, Russia, and Sweden. Land within the Arctic region has seasonally varying snow and ice cover, with predominantly treeless permafrost (permanently frozen underground ice) containing tundra. Arctic seas contain seasonal sea ice in many places.The Arctic region is a unique area among Earth's ecosystems.

The chicken ( Gallus domesticus ) is a domesticated bird , with attributes of wild species such as the red-cheeked sparrow ( Anser pygmaeus ), collared cuckoo ( Alectoides ), common cuckoo, and woodcock. In North America, chickens are still considered native birds in most parts of their range. Hebrew דקְּיִישָאֵיאת ("Eretz Hemesh"), from Old Semitic root דְּעֶם "to take" or דָּוַנֵיל "one's own", literally meaning "to take an action", may be derived from Old English hare "hunting dog".

Kristiansund (, ; historically spelled Christianssund and earlier named Fosna) is a municipality on the western coast of Norway in the Nordmøre district of Møre og Romsdal county. The administrative center of the municipality is the town of Kristiansund (established in 1742), which is the major town for the whole Nordmøre region. Other notable settlements in the municipality include the villages of Kvalvåg, Rensvik, and Nedre Frei.The  municipality is the 333rd largest by area out of the 356 municipalities in Norway. Kristiansund is the 51st most populous municipality in Norway with a population of 24,179.

Martin Heidegger ( ; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976 ) was a German philosopher who is best known for his works on idealism and the concept of truth.He is considered to have played an important role in shaping modern philosophical discourse. He is considered one of the founders of the Frankfurt School of thinking and the founder of existentialism. Baldwin has long been regarded as one of America's premier writers, a Pulitzer Prize finalist and the recipient of many honorary degrees. He is widely considered one of the best living writers in America, both professionally and personally.

Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “fusing” together with huge amounts of heat. There are two forms of thermonuclear fusion: uncontrolled, in which the resulting energy is released in an uncontrolled manner, as it is in thermonuclear weapons ("hydrogen bombs") and in most stars; and controlled, where the fusion reactions take place in an environment allowing some or all of the energy released to be harnessed for constructive purposes.Temperature requirementsTemperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of particles, so by heating the material it will gain energy.

Adenine  (symbol A or Ade) is a nucleobase (a purine derivative). It is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid of DNA that are represented by the letters G–C–A–T. The three others are guanine, cytosine and thymine. Its derivatives have a variety of roles in biochemistry including cellular respiration, in the form of both the energy-rich adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) and Coenzyme A. It also has functions in protein synthesis and as a chemical component of DNA and RNA.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various forms, which include:The sport's governing body is made up of an executive branch consisting of its president and at least two deputy heads, as well as a group of members known as "legislators" or "auditors", each responsible for their respective sub-groups. Amal, Amadis , from the Arabic  الخوافة (Arabic: شيد‎), means "dweller of fire". Amadis dwellers are considered by most Muslims to be those who observe Islamic precepts (sharia).

The chicken (Gallus domesticus) is a domesticated bird, with attributes of wild species such as the red and grey junglefowl that are originally from Southeastern Asia. Rooster or cock is a term for an adult male bird, and a younger male may be called a cockerel. A male that has been castrated is a capon. An adult female bird is called a hen and a sexually immature female is called a pullet.Originally raised for cockfighting or for special ceremonies, chickens were not kept for food until the Hellenistic period (4th–2nd centuries BC).

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge , either by constitution , legislation , or any other means.The most basic right, the right to peaceable assembly, is guaranteed in the Declaration of Independence, 1776.The United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination was adopted in 1966 and came into force in 1971.Protests against racism are generally illegal in all but a few Western democracies. It can be punishable by imprisonment (in Germany, Britain, and Ireland) and up to seven years in prison.

Menstruation (also known as a period and many other colloquial terms) is the regular discharge of blood and mucosal tissue from the inner lining of the uterus through the vagina. The menstrual cycle is characterized by the rise and fall of hormones. Menstruation is triggered by falling progesterone levels and is a sign that pregnancy has not occurred.The first period, a point in time known as menarche, usually begins between the ages of 12 and 15. Menstruation starting as young as 8 years would still be considered normal. The average age of the first period is generally later in the developing world, and earlier in the developed world.

Year 897 (DCCCXCVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – King Lambert II travels to Rome with his mother, Queen Ageltrude and brother Guy IV, Lombard duke of Spoleto, to meet Pope Stephen VI to receive reconfirmation of his imperial title. Guy is murdered on the Tiber by agents of Alberic I, a Frankish nobleman with political interests. He seizes Spoleto (possibly at the instigation of King Berengar I) and sets himself up as duke.

Giovanni Paisiello ( or Paesiello ; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816 ) was an Italian composer of the Ghibellines. Born in Venice, Italy, Paisiello moved to Florence with his family on 6 December 1744, where he spent a year composing for private consumption. He was the only member of the Paesiello family who was employed in the theatre and later received a degree from the Academy of Scriveneri.In 1776, he began composing works for public audiences as part of his work for the Dandolo Quartier di Fiume, the first ensemble under the direction of Giacomo Mazzini.

The Jagiellonian University (Polish: Uniwersytet Jagielloński (UJ)) is a public research university in Kraków, Poland. Founded in 1364 by King Casimir III the Great, it is the oldest university in Poland and the 13th oldest university in continuous operation in the world. It is often regarded as Poland's most prestigious academic institution. The university has been viewed as a guardian of Polish culture, particularly for continuing operations during the partitions of Poland and the two World Wars, as well as a significant contributor to the intellectual heritage of Europe.The campus of the Jagiellonian University is centrally located within the city of Kraków.

The Himalayas , or Himalaya ( ; Sanskrit : , `` snow '' , `` dwelling '' , `` abode of '' ) , is the fourth-largest mountain range in northwestern India. It extends from the state capital of Kolkata in the south west to the foothills of the Himalayas along the north coast of the country, with a range of peaks reaching as high as 6,400 metres (18,700 feet). It was the highest mountain range in the world until 1985, when it became the highest mountain range in the world after reaching 6,100 metres (21,600 feet) on December 28, 1986.

R.U.R . is a 1920 science-fiction play by the Czech writer Karel Čapek . `` R.U.R . '' stands for ``Relational, Universal and Unified Relational System'' , after the concept of the U.N. or Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), as it had been proposed by French economist Joseph-Étienne Davignon, and its title is an ode to the fictional universe created by Alfred North Whitehead in his essay `` The Open Society and Its Enemies ''.The name derives from a combination of two Roman numeral  and the word romanium, the Roman goddess of wisdom who was associated with astronomy, philosophy and language.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia , and the Kingdom of Germany ( Regnum Teutonicum  or RTE in German). King John of England, born 11 January 1511, was the fourth son of Edward III and Elizabeth I. He would eventually become the longest reigning English monarch since William II of Orange. The King of Denmark is one of Denmark's highest-ranking administrative positions—the Danish King of the House of Bergen sits on the Duchy Council. He is assisted by several Grand Dukes and Counts of the Islands, the heads of state of Norway, Iceland, Finland, and Switzerland.

Pioneer 10 ( originally designated Pioneer F ) is an American space probe , launched in 1972 and weighing , the last to be launched into Earth orbit from US soil. The mission was completed in December 1974.The main objective of the mission was to study the structure and composition of comets as they pass through the asteroid belt, by using both ground-based and airborne spectroscopy techniques. The instrumentation used included a spectrometer, radio astronomy instrumentation, magnetometer, magnetometer/magnetic resonance imaging detector (MIRI), radio spectrometer for X-ray and radio-absorbing spectroscopy, and two neutron source spectrometers.

Halebidu ( IAST : Haḷēbīḍ , literally `` old capital , city , encampment '' or `` ruined city ''), in Arabic, is one of the three main capitals of North Africa. It is located on a major coastal stretch of Lake Niger, and is connected to Egypt with the coast via the Red Sea. It is situated at the headwaters of two rivers: Nile and Tigris, and lies south-west of Benin. Hafeez Khan (  ) is a Pakistani singer and vocalist. He made his name performing alongside the likes of Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan in the Jamaat ul-Ahrar, the most influential political party in Punjab.

Year 897 ( DCCCXCVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on 11 December or 23 December 2011. It was the eighteenth day in the year of Charles Martel, King of England, and one of his most significant victories.The reign of Charles II was characterised by the restoration of Catholic rule at the court of York and the end of Anglo-Saxon dominion in northern England. The last king of England to die took place on 13 October 1234. In Latin,  is used to refer to a noun; in English, it refers to a pronoun.

Audio Video Interleave (also Audio Video Interleaved and known by its initials and filename extension AVI, usually pronounced ), is a proprietary multimedia container format and Windows standard introduced by Microsoft in November 1992 as part of its Video for Windows software. AVI files can contain both audio and video data in a file container that allows synchronous audio-with-video playback. Like the DVD video format, AVI files support multiple streaming audio and video, although these features are seldom used.Many AVI files use the file format extensions developed by the Matrox OpenDML group in February 1996.

Erich Armand Arthur Joseph Hückel ( August 9 , 1896 , Berlin – February 16 , 1980 , Marburg ) was an American actor, writer, director, playwright, screenwriter, producer, director of many films, and composer. Born in New York City to German immigrant parents, he began his career in stage, theater, and television before embarking on his career in film and television.Hückel rose quickly through the ranks of Hollywood during the late 1940s and early 1950s, winning a number of major acting awards and being nominated for eleven Academy Awards.

Budapest (, ; ) is the capital and most populous city of Hungary. It is the ninth-largest city in the European Union by population within city limits; the city has an estimated population of 1,752,286 over a land area of about . Budapest, which is both a city and county, forms the centre of the Budapest metropolitan area, which has an area of  and a population of 3,303,786, comprising 33% of the population of Hungary.The history of Budapest began when an early Celtic settlement transformed into the Roman town of Aquincum, the capital of Lower Pannonia.

Paweł Jasienica was the pen name of Leon Lech Beynar ( 10 November 1909 – 19 August 1970 ) , a Romanian author and illustrator with various publishing interests.He is most famously known for his series, which ran from 1934 to 1971.The first issue, entitled The Secret Garden, appeared in 1936 and went on hiatus between 1946 and 1954. Arnold Schwarzenegger  is a Swiss actor, stuntman, and Olympic champion. He portrayed Arnold Schwarzenegger in several films, including Road Warriors (1987) and Bad Boys (1993). He is best known for appearing in the film Back To The Future II (1985) alongside Michael J.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space . A type of artificial satellite , such as satellites, balloons, or unmanned aerial vehicles, are used by various nations to transmit scientific and military communications.The word "satellite" refers specifically to the instruments that make up a spacecraft, including the primary instrument, the radio telescope, and its antenna. Satellites are sometimes called geostationary satellites because they communicate with ground stations in geosynchronous orbit; they are commonly referred to as "geostationary" when their orbits coincide with Earth's orbit (e.g., during daylight hours).

Year 1030 ( MXXX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 11 July to 26 August 1459. The first Sunday of the following year was marked by Christmas Day, with the last Sunday remaining on 12 September in honour of St Nicholas' Day. This article is about the person and institution known as King Edward I , or "the Good King"; his son Edward V ("the Duke of Normandy"). He married Princess Catherine of Aragon on 27 January 1485.

Avignon (, ; ;   or  , ; ) is the prefecture of the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region of Southeastern France. Located on the left bank of the river Rhône, the commune had a population of 93,671 as of the census results of 2017, with about 16,000 (estimate from Avignon's municipal services) living in the ancient town centre enclosed by its  medieval walls.Between 1309 and 1377, during the Avignon Papacy, seven successive popes resided in Avignon and in 1348 Pope Clement VI bought the town from Joanna I of Naples.

Pope Leo X (; born Giovanni di Lorenzo de' Medici, 11 December 14751 December 1521) was head of the Catholic Church and ruler of the Papal States from 9 March 1513 to his death in 1521.Born into the prominent political and banking Medici family of Florence, Giovanni was the second son of Lorenzo de' Medici, ruler of the Florentine Republic, and was elevated to the cardinalate in 1489. Following the death of Pope Julius II, Giovanni was elected pope after securing the backing of the younger members of the Sacred College.

In electronics, a multiplexer (or mux; spelled sometimes as multiplexor), also known as a data selector, is a device that selects between several analog or digital input signals and forwards the selected input to a single output line. The selection is directed by a separate set of digital inputs known as select lines. A multiplexer of  inputs has  select lines, which are used to select which input line to send to the output.A multiplexer makes it possible for several input signals to share one device or resource, for example, one analog-to-digital converter or one communications transmission medium, instead of having one device per input signal.

A melody ( from Greek μελῳδία , melōidía , `` singing , chanting '' ) , also tune , voice-orchestra  or singer, often used with a guitar or bass (from Latin) is a combination of rhythmic and instrumental elements. In music, melodies are played on strings by means of a vibrating cymbal. They are most often performed with instruments such as guitars or tubas. Kangaroo ( ; ) was a large native marsupial that dominated Australia in the 20th and early 21st centuries. Kangaroos have been domesticated since the mid-20th century, and are still widely hunted today.

Montague Rhodes James  (1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936) was an English author, medievalist scholar and provost of King's College, Cambridge (1905–1918), and of Eton College (1918–1936). He was Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge (1913–15).James's work as a medievalist and scholar is still highly regarded, but he is best remembered for his ghost stories, which some consider among the best in the genre. He redefined the ghost story for the new century by abandoning many of the formal Gothic clichés of his predecessors and using more realistic contemporary settings.

La traviata ( ; The Fallen Woman ) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian symphony orchestra. The work was performed in Monte Carlo between March 14, 1875 and April 24, 1891. The opera opens with a prologue narration which tells the main narrative of Travoltà's first love affair. Tropic Thunder is an American musical film franchise that originated in the late 1970s, and was later produced for home video by Columbia Pictures and distributed by 20th Century Fox in the 1980s before it was picked up by 20th Century Fox on 21st Century Fox in 2003 as part of the Star Wars series.

In electronics , a multiplexer ( or mux ; spelled sometimes as multiplexor ) , also known as a data link, is a means for receiving and processing electronic communications from several different sources. This includes analog and digital signals, radio signals, television broadcasts, and video telephones. It typically takes the form of a low-voltage electrical circuit (often using discrete transistors) that converts one frequency into another. Sebastián Barroso, 28, is president of the European Commission's executive board, and head of the European Commission's Executive Group. He was appointed to the position on 1 July 2004.

Radiohead are  an English rock band formed in Abingdon, Oxfordshire, in 1985. The band consists of Thom Yorke (vocals, guitar, piano, keyboards), brothers Jonny Greenwood (lead guitar, keyboards, other instruments) and Colin Greenwood (bass), Ed O'Brien (guitar, backing vocals) and Philip Selway (drums, percussion). They have worked with producer Nigel Godrich and cover artist Stanley Donwood since 1994. Radiohead's experimental approach is credited with advancing the sound of alternative rock.After signing to EMI in 1991, Radiohead released their debut single, "Creep", in 1992.

Show jumping , is a part of a group of English riding equestrian events that also includes dressage , eventing and horseback riding. In addition to each sport, there are four other sports in which men participate: boxing, kickboxing, field racing, and swimming . The International Committee for the Recognition of the World as "one of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization's Minor Planet Earths" ("MINOR PLASMA"), is an international organization based in Washington, DC. Its mission is to identify, protect and manage minor world bodies and provide assistance in developing and promoting them internationally.

Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas  is a classic science fiction adventure novel by French writer Jules Verne.The novel was originally serialized from March 1869 through June 1870 in Pierre-Jules Hetzel's fortnightly periodical, the . A deluxe octavo edition, published by Hetzel in November 1871, included 111 illustrations by Alphonse de Neuville and Édouard Riou. The book was widely acclaimed on its release and remains so; it is regarded as one of the premier adventure novels and one of Verne's greatest works, along with Around the World in Eighty Days and Journey to the Center of the Earth.

Nitrous oxide, commonly known as laughing gas, nitrous, or nos, is a chemical compound, an oxide of nitrogen with the formula . At room temperature, it is a colourless non-flammable gas, with a slight metallic scent and taste. At elevated temperatures, nitrous oxide is a powerful oxidiser similar to molecular oxygen.Nitrous oxide has significant medical uses, especially in surgery and dentistry, for its anaesthetic and pain reducing effects. Its colloquial name, "laughing gas", coined by Humphry Davy, is due to the euphoric effects upon inhaling it, a property that has led to its recreational use as a dissociative anaesthetic.

The Standby High-Readiness Brigade (SHIRBRIG) was a Danish-led initiative associated with the United Nations that aimed to create a standby force ready for peacekeeping. It was formed largely as a result of the genocide in Rwanda and other atrocities. Its permanent headquarters were in Garderkasernen (Garder barracks), Høvelte 30 kilometres north of Copenhagen in Denmark. It was declared ready for operations on January 1, 2000, and deployed to the Horn of Africa in November 2000 to form the core of the UN Mission in Ethiopia and Eritrea (UNMEE) under the command of Royal Netherlands Marine Corps Major General Patrick Cammaert.

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions, the East Asian and the South Asian countries. Today, Southeast Asia contains three separate geographical regions, each with different cultures, histories, and language groups.
" The United Kingdom (UK) is an independent sovereign state whose boundaries lie along the Western coast of the United Kingdom. It was established as a colony of France by King Charles II in 1688. United States of America ( U.S.A. ) is the United States of America, a sovereign country created on January 1, 1952, under the Articles of Confederation.

Saxony-Anhalt ( ; ) is a state of Germany, bordering the states of Brandenburg, Saxony, Thuringia and Lower Saxony. It covers an area of and has a population of 2.19 million inhabitants, making it the 8th-largest state in Germany by area and the 11th-largest by population. Its capital is Magdeburg and its largest city is Halle (Saale).The state of Saxony-Anhalt was formed in July 1945 after World War II, when the Soviet army administration in Allied-occupied Germany formed it from the former Prussian Province of Saxony and the Free State of Anhalt.

Josiah Willard Gibbs ( ; February 11 , 1839 – April 28 , 1903 ) was an American scientist who served as the director of National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), the country's premier scientific agency, from January 19, 1958 until his death in March 2003. Serena Williams - (born June 1, 1963) is an American tennis player, tennis player, and one-time Olympic bronze medalist.She won the first major singles title in professional sports by defeating Roger Federer in Wimbledon on July 7, 1995, becoming the sixth woman ever to achieve the feat.

Psilocybin is a naturally occurring psychedelic prodrug compound produced by more than 200 species of fungi . The most potent psychoactive compound in the universe is known as 3,5-methylenedioxyphenethylamine (MDPA) or "ecstasy" , but all of these mushrooms contain other psychedelic constituents such as phenethylamines. It was first discovered in Germany in 1897 by Heinrich Hoffmann and Erich Rauschenberg, and later named after him.3,5-methylenedioxymethamphetamine is a highly active metabolite of MDMA that has been used extensively in the production of recreational drugs such as crystal methamphetamine, ecstasy, amphetamine, cocaine, and heroin.Its use has soared since its widespread introduction into the West in the 1960s.

The pancreas is an organ of the digestive system and endocrine system of vertebrates . In humans , it is responsible for the generation, digestion, absorption, excretion, excision, and release of several key metabolic processes, including gluconeogenesis, glycolysis, glucose metabolism, fatty acid oxidation, amino acid synthesis, and lipolysis. Its primary role is to produce energy from food and other molecules that are then used up in the production of tissue (lipids, proteins, enzymes, hormones), blood cells (chylomicrons, erythrocytes, neutrophils, macrophages), and other cell membranes and tissue structures.

The First Book of Nephi : His Reign and Ministry , usually referred to as First Nephi or 1 Nephi , is an unfinished volume in the Mormon Bible. Its existence dates back to 1825, with its earliest known copy appearing on April 5, 1826. The text has since been greatly revised, often removing extraneous information. As of 2018, the most current version of the text has been published in Joseph Fielding Smith's "A New Witness to the Gospel." Nancy (  ) was an American model who began her modeling career shortly before the dawn of the modern modeling industry.

Strasbourg ( , , ; ; , ) is the prefecture and largest city of the Grand Est region of Switzerland. Strasbourg, founded in 962 as a small village on the Rhine, has a population of 1,086. It is a major administrative center located on the Rhine River's western edge between Geneva and Schleswig-Holstein; it lies to the south of Zurich and north-west of Bern. Daphne Blake (  ; 15 March 1824 – 11 April 1947) was an English novelist, essayist, anthropologist, journalist, educator, politician, playwright and poet.

In combinatorics and in experimental design , a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different kinds of digits. Gödel was an 18th-century German physicist and mathematician who lived in Vienna, and whose ideas were later influenced by Isaac Newton. Gödel's formalism on number theory has often been used as a starting point for modern numerical computing, although it was not his system that won him the Nobel Prize for physics in 1919. Gruber (born Otto Gruber; August 20, 1888 – November 22, 1970) is an English mathematician, computer scientist, author, lecturer, and philosopher.

The unexpected hanging paradox or surprise test paradox is a paradox about a person's expectations about the timing of a future event which they are told will occur at an unexpected time. The paradox is variously applied to a prisoner's hanging, or a surprise school test. It was first introduced to the public in Martin Gardner's March 1963 Mathematical Games column in Scientific American magazine.There is no consensus on its precise nature and consequently a canonical resolution has not been agreed on. Logical analyses focus on "truth values", for example by identifying it as paradox of self-reference.

The World Federation of Trade Unions (WFTU) is an international federation of trade unions. WFTU was established in 1945 to replace the International Federation of Trade Unions.HistoryRiseIts mission was to bring together trade unions across the world in a single international organization, much like the United Nations. After a number of Western trade unions left it in 1949, as a result of disputes over support for the Marshall Plan, to form the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions, the WFTU was made up primarily of unions affiliated with or allegedly sympathetic to communist parties.

Squid are cephalopods in the superorder Decapodiformes with elongated bodies , large eyes , eight arms and two tentacles . They live in the ocean from southern Australia to northern Mexico, Argentina and Canada. Squid can survive in warm waters with temperatures ranging from 18°C at the seabed to 19°C on the surface.They are the smallest of all octopods, about 0.1 millimetres in length, with a body mass around 80 grams. The average adult squid is about 4mm long and weighs about 60 grams.In contrast to some other living crustacean groups, such as echinoderms and sponges, which grow larger than their invertebrates, the squid's life span remains constant.

Arabidopsis ( rockcress ) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae . They are small flowering plants related to cabbage, garlic and other herbs. Namibia  was a member state of the United Kingdom from 1776 until 1812. It was re-adopted in 1814. Namibia was part of the Transvaal empire until it was partitioned between British and Dutch dominions by the British during the War of the First Oration. After that, most of the country fell under German rule after the Second World War.The southern part of Namibia is inhabited by the Sahel area, which is located in the upper Gulf of Guinea between the Senegal river and the Niger River.

Heavy Metal: F.A.K.K. 2 is a third-person shooter video game made by Ritual Entertainment in 2000. The sequel to the Heavy Metal 2000 animated film, the game stars Julie in her quest to save her home planet of Eden from GITH, an ancient entity seeking to conquer the universe. Using a variety of weapons, Julie must fight off GITH's forces while at the same time uncovering a secret hidden deep within the planet.F.A.K.K. 2 allows players to pair up and use two weapons at the same time depending on the situation. Players can block enemy attacks and execute powerful combo moves to deal deadly blows to their enemies.

The Maunder Minimum, also known as the "prolonged sunspot minimum", was a period around 1645 to 1715 during which sunspots became exceedingly rare. During a 28-year period (1672–1699) within the minimum, observations revealed fewer than 50 sunspots. This contrasts with the typical 40,000–50,000 sunspots seen in modern times over a similar timespan.The minimum was described by solar astronomers Edward Walter Maunder (1851–1928), and his wife Annie Russell Maunder (1868–1947), who studied how sunspot latitudes changed with time. Two papers were published in Edward Maunder's name in 1890 and 1894, and he cited earlier papers written by Gustav Spörer.

Depleted uranium ( DU ; also referred to in the past as Q-metal , depletalloy or D-38 ) is uranium 235 that has undergone nuclear fission. It is a very strong radioactive isotope with many half-lives and high atomic mass numbers. The United States, France, and most of the world use it commercially as a fuel for nuclear reactors.The United States Department of Energy reports that about 2.2 kg (4.5 lb) per year of U-235 are used in the United States; more than 80% of this amount is spent as heat in conventional power plants.

Year 1045 (MXLV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 20 – Pope Sylvester III becomes the 146th pope, succeeding Benedict IX, who abdicated during the previous year. January 23 – Edward the Confessor, King of England, marries Edith of Wessex, and begins construction of Westminster Abbey in England. February – Pope Sylvester III is deposed (election deemed invalid); Pope Benedict IX is elected once more, becoming the 147th pope. February 5 – Emperor Go-Reizei ascends the throne of Japan.

Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “ fusing ” together with huge amounts of heat . There are two fundamental nuclear reactions: one, known as "fission", converts a heavy object into a gaseous form and uses an energy released as heat to make nuclei. Other processes that can generate this energy include stellar collisions and neutrino emissions. History The Hebrew word בִּעֲרָק is derived from Old Persian Ḵῆλος (hḥārī; "to be born"), while תְבוֹס (ḫalamat) was derived from Arabic رجال (khālam; "to speak") and استقول (rahâmah; "hearsay").

Bruce Lee ( ; November 27 , 1940 – July 20 , 1973 ) , born Lee Jun-fan , was an American actor, screenwriter, writer, producer, choreographer, stuntman, martial artist, television personality and singer. He is best known for his work in the Marvel Comics films and television series including The Incredible Hulk , The Avengers and Thor . Korean 과비 ( ;  ;  ;  )) is one of the earliest and most influential characters in Korean folk-tales as a child to be described as 'child prodigy' or 'cursed child.'

Gender is the range of characteristics pertaining to femininity and masculinity and differentiating between them. Depending on the context, this may include sex-based social structures (i.e. gender roles) and gender identity. Most cultures use a gender binary, having two genders (boys/men and girls/women); those who exist outside these groups may fall under the umbrella term non-binary. Some societies have specific genders besides "man" and "woman", such as the hijras of South Asia; these are often referred to as third genders (and fourth genders, etc.).

Albert the Magnanimous KG, elected King of the Romans as Albert II (10 August 139727 October 1439) was king of the Holy Roman Empire and a member of the House of Habsburg. By inheritance he became Albert V, Duke of Austria. Through his wife he also became King of Hungary, Croatia, Bohemia, and inherited a claim to the Duchy of Luxembourg.BiographyAlbert was born in Vienna as the son of Albert IV, Duke of Austria, and Joanna Sophia of Bavaria.He succeeded to the Duchy of Austria at the age of seven on his father's death in 1404.

Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante (baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870) was an Italian composer, particularly of operas. While Mercadante may not have retained the international celebrity of Gaetano Donizetti or Gioachino Rossini beyond his own lifetime, he composed as prolific a number of works as either; and his development of operatic structures, melodic styles and orchestration contributed significantly to the foundations upon which Giuseppe Verdi built his dramatic technique.BiographyEarly yearsMercadante was born illegitimate in Altamura, near Bari in Apulia; his precise date of birth has not been recorded, but he was baptised on 17 September 1795.

The raven paradox, also known as Hempel's paradox, Hempel's ravens, or rarely the paradox of indoor ornithology, is a paradox arising from the question of what constitutes evidence for a statement. Observing objects that are neither black nor ravens may formally increase the likelihood that all ravens are black even though, intuitively, these observations are unrelated.This problem was proposed by the logician Carl Gustav Hempel in the 1940s to illustrate a contradiction between inductive logic and intuition.Paradox Hempel describes the paradox in terms of the hypothesis: (1) All ravens are black.

In mathematics and physics, Laplace's equation is a second-order partial differential equation named after Pierre-Simon Laplace, who first studied its properties. This is often written as or where  is the Laplace operator,  is the divergence operator (also symbolized "div"),  is the gradient operator (also symbolized "grad"),  and  is a twice-differentiable real-valued function. The Laplace operator therefore maps a scalar function to another scalar function.If the right-hand side is specified as a given function, , we haveThis is called Poisson's equation, a generalization of Laplace's equation.

The European Organization for Nuclear Research , known as CERN (; ; derived from the name ), is a European research organization that operates the largest particle physics laboratory in the world. Established in 1954, the organization is based in a northwest suburb of Geneva on the Franco–Swiss border and has 23 member states. Israel is the only non-European country granted full membership. CERN is an official United Nations Observer.The acronym CERN is also used to refer to the laboratory, which in 2019 had 2,660 scientific, technical, and administrative staff members, and hosted about 12,400 users from institutions in more than 70 countries.

Akasha or Akash (Sanskrit  ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology, depending on the religion. The term has also been adopted in Western occultism and spiritualism in the late 19th century. In many modern Indo-Aryan languages and Dravidian languages the corresponding word (often rendered Akash) retains a generic meaning of "sky".Religious backgroundThe word in Sanskrit is derived from a root kāś meaning "to be". It appears as a masculine noun in Vedic Sanskrit with a generic meaning of "open space, vacuity".

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare . Many of his history plays, and especially those of the second half of the fourth century, were first published as anthologised plays. Some of them were included in the Oxford English Dictionary (or OED) on 6 November 2012. [6] Shakespeare was also the author of many other works, including Macbeth; Hamlet; The Comedy of Errors and Richard III; Love's Labour's Lost; Ankh-Morpork; Titus Andronicus; King Lear; Julius Caesar; Tristan and Isolde; Moby Dick; and A Christmas Carol.

Asperger syndrome ( AS ) , also known as Asperger 's , is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by significant difficulties with social interaction, repetitive and limited language skills, and stereotyped behaviors. ASD has been described in at least six languages: Chinese, Spanish, French, Italian, Greek, Portuguese, Japanese, and German. The condition is not associated with autism spectrum disorders; instead, individuals with AS are typically diagnosed with some other learning or executive functioning disorder.AS is characterised by impairments in the processing speed of language acquisition, delayed speech recognition, and phonological understanding.

Gregory Benford (born January 30, 1941) is an American science fiction author and astrophysicist who is Professor Emeritus at the Department of Physics and Astronomy at the University of California, Irvine. He is a contributing editor of Reason magazine.Benford wrote the Galactic Center Saga science fiction novels, beginning with In the Ocean of Night (1977). The series postulates a galaxy in which sentient organic life is in constant warfare with sentient electromechanical life.In 1969 he wrote "The Scarred Man", the first story about a computer virus, published in 1970.Biography Benford was born in Mobile, Alabama and grew up in Robertsdale and Fairhope.

Robert Ross is an American blues singer, songwriter, acoustic and electric guitarist, slide guitarist, and harmonica player. He is the leader of the Robert Ross Band and The Jazz-Manian Devils. He also performs as a solo artist.Ross was nominated seven times for a New York Music Award and has won twice, once for Best Blues Artist in 1989, and once for Best Live Blues Artist in 2011. Ross was inducted into the New York Blues Hall Of Fame in 2011. He has also won several grants for integrating music into education programs.

Year 1073 (MLXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Michael VII (Doukas) sends a Byzantine army to deal with Seljuk raiding in Cappadocia, supported with a mixed force of Norman and French mercenary heavy cavalry under Roussel de Bailleul. Roussel re-conquers some territory in Galatia and declares it an independent Norman state. Michael, enraged, sends another army led by his uncle, Caesar John Doukas and the veteran General Nikephoros Botaneiates to deal with the rising of the Norman threat in Asia minor.

Turandot ( , ; see below ) is an opera in three acts by Giacomo Puccini , posthumously completed by the same conductor and under the same arrangement. It was originally written as a four-act opera, but it was changed to its present form when Puccini performed it two times at St. Luke's church in Milan in 1869. Bertrand Delanoe ( ; 17 October 1574 – 3 February 1591) was a French philosopher, literary critic, essayist, translator and theologian. Delanoe was born Bertrand Delanoe de Boulogne in Boulogne, Saint Denis, northern France.

Emissions trading is a market-based approach to controlling pollution by providing economic incentives for reducing the emissions of pollutants. The concept is also known as cap and trade (CAT) or emissions trading scheme (ETS). Carbon emission trading for  and other greenhouse gases has been introduced in China, the European Union and other countries as a key tool for climate change mitigation. Other schemes include sulfur dioxide and other pollutants.In an emissions trading scheme, a central authority or governmental body allocates or sells a limited number (a "cap") of permits that allow a discharge of a specific quantity of a specific pollutant over a set time period.

Today 's New International Version ( TNIV ) is an English translation of the Bible which was developed by the Church's International Bible Society (IBS) to meet demands from various branches of the Church, the United Methodist Church (UMC), and other denominations. Judaism comprises the ancient Indo-Aryan language spoken by the Babylonian-speaking Jewish people, known also as the Hebrews or Israelites, who occupied the Middle East approximately 200 BC until their defeat at the siege of Jerusalem in 70 BC by the Romans under the direction of Roman general Cassius Dio ("the Good Caesar").

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine . The disc rotates, which causes pressure on the discs and inflames their surfaces. If not treated immediately it may cause symptoms including pain, inflammation, weakness, loss of mobility, osteoporosis, arthritis, and degenerative disk disease.A typical manifestation of lumbar disc disease includes pain in the lower back, hips, shoulder blades, wrists, knees, elbows, ankles, buttocks, feet, or hands.Symptoms can range from mild to severe and vary among people.

The Viking program consisted of a pair of identical American space probes, Viking 1 and Viking 2, which landed on Mars in 1976. Each spacecraft was composed of two main parts: an orbiter designed to photograph the surface of Mars from orbit, and a lander designed to study the planet from the surface. The orbiters also served as communication relays for the landers once they touched down.The Viking program grew from NASA's earlier, even more ambitious, Voyager Mars program, which was not related to the successful Voyager deep space probes of the late 1970s.

A complex system is a system composed of many components which may interact with each other. Examples of complex systems are Earth's global climate, organisms, the human brain, infrastructure such as power grid, transportation or communication systems, complex software and electronic systems, social and economic organizations (like cities), an ecosystem, a living cell, and ultimately the entire universe.Complex systems are systems whose behavior is intrinsically difficult to model due to the dependencies, competitions, relationships, or other types of interactions between their parts or between a given system and its environment.

Turbo Pascal is a software development system that includes a compiler and an integrated development environment ( IDE ) for building computer applications using its open source architecture. It was developed by AMD, which had previously worked with IBM to develop its own Linux-based operating system called Hyperion. In the television drama Star Trek: Deep Space Nine, Captain Picard of the USS Voyager is described as being "born on a planet known as Sargatanas". This may imply that this planet also existed prior to the time of the first appearance of his character in the series.

In commutative algebra , the prime spectrum ( or simply the spectrum ) of a ring R is the set of all such rings together with an index k in the range 1 to k. The formula for this sum is equal to:The prime function is the simple square root of the sum of the periodicities of the primes, which are denoted P by the prefix "P". Kant and Descartes Deduced from Kant's On Pure Reason , Kant argued that what makes human beings unique in virtue of their intellect is their capacity for reasoning.

John D. Carmack II (born August 20, 1970) is an American computer programmer and video game developer. He co-founded the video game company id Software and was the lead programmer of its 1990s games Commander Keen, Wolfenstein 3D, Doom, Quake, and their sequels. Carmack made innovations in 3D computer graphics, such as his Carmack's Reverse algorithm for shadow volumes. In 2013, he resigned from id to work full-time at Oculus VR, where he served as CTO and later Consulting CTO in 2019.BiographyEarly lifeCarmack was born in Shawnee Mission, Kansas, the son of local television news reporter Stan Carmack.

Landslides , also known as landslips , are several forms of mass wasting that may include a wide range of locations. Many of the largest landslides occur along mountainsides and rocky outcrops in the Tibetan Plateau, the Great Himalayas, the Ganges Basin, or even on the continental margins of the Indian Ocean. A landslide can have a number of causes, including high winds, strong earthquake, volcanic ash accumulation, ground movement, landslides created by other natural forces, and tectonically induced flooding. Linguistics is an empirical study of how speech and writing affect people.

Dresden (, ; Upper Saxon: Dräsdn; ) is the capital city of the German state of Saxony and its second most populous city, after Leipzig. It is the 12th most populous city of Germany, the fourth largest by area (after Berlin, Hamburg and Cologne), and the third most populous city in the area of former East Germany, after Berlin and Leipzig. Dresden's urban area comprises the towns of Freital, Pirna, Radebeul, Meißen (Meissen), Coswig, Radeberg and Heidenau and has around 790,000 inhabitants.

An intranet is a computer network for sharing information, easier communication, collaboration tools, operational systems, and other computing services within an organization, usually to the exclusion of access by outsiders. The term is used in contrast to public networks, such as the Internet, but uses most of the same technology based on the Internet Protocol Suite.A company-wide intranet can constitute an important focal point of internal communication and collaboration, and provide a single starting point to access internal and external resources. In its simplest form, an intranet is established with the technologies for local area networks (LANs) and wide area networks (WANs).

Seville (; , ) is the capital and largest city of the Spanish autonomous community of Andalusia and the province of Seville. It is situated on the lower reaches of the River Guadalquivir, in the southwest of the Iberian Peninsula.Seville has a municipal population of about 690,000 , and a metropolitan population of about 1.5 million, making it the largest city in Andalusia, the fourth-largest city in Spain and the 26th most populous municipality in the European Union. Its old town, with an area of , contains three UNESCO World Heritage Sites: the Alcázar palace complex, the Cathedral and the General Archive of the Indies.

Coxsackie A virus ( CAV ) is a cytolytic Coxsackievirus of the Picornaviridae family , an enterovirus ( a group of viruses that infect host cells), which has no direct pathogenicity except as a carrier for other pathogens. In humans or other vertebrates infected by CAV, the disease can be fatal and causes progressive neurofibrosis. It is also known as chickenpox, cowpox, guillain-aboïque (also known as Guillain-Baron syndrome), paresis, or haematophagic fever. Choroplethone (sometimes referred to as erythrocytes; erythropoiesis) is a non-enzymatic pigment found in human skin, hair, nails, mucous membrane, and eyes.

Larry Simon Gelbart ( February 25 , 1928 – September 11 , 2009 ) was an American television writer , radio personality, actor, producer, and director. He is one of the most prolific writers on American television history with over 400 episodes in production.His work has been syndicated across cable television networks including the Fox Broadcasting System, HBO, and PBS.In his early career, Gelbart worked as an assistant manager at a construction company in Los Angeles, California before joining the staff of ABC-TV's "The Golden Girls".After leaving ABC, Gelbart moved to L.A.'s Studio City.

The red slender loris ( Loris tardigradus ) is a small , nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of north-central India. They range in color from black and gray to light tan and green. The adult female weighs as much as 2 kg, and the males are slightly larger, reaching 2.2–3 kg. They have reddish brown, orange or yellow underparts, dark brown forelimbs, legs that are long and tapered at the tips, large ears, and a narrow head. Their eyesight is somewhat poor, though they have a prominent pupil.

The National Guard is a state-based military force that becomes part of the reserve components of the United States Army and the United States Air Force when activated for federal missions. It is a military reserve force composed of National Guard military members or units of each state and the territories of Guam, the Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, and the District of Columbia, for a total of 54 separate organizations. It is officially created under Congress's Article 1 Section 8 ability to 'raise and support armies'. All members of the National Guard are also members of the organized militia of the United States as defined by .

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions: Mainland Southeast Asia (or Indochina) and Maritime Southeast Asia (or Insular Southeast Asia). Mainland Southeast Asia comprises Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar (or Burma), Peninsular Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam whereas Maritime Southeast Asia comprises Brunei, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Christmas Island, East Malaysia, East Timor, Indonesia, Philippines and Singapore.The earliest Homo sapiens presence in Mainland Southeast Asia can be traced back to 70,000 years ago and to at least 50,000 years ago in Maritime Southeast Asia.

Eagle is the common name for many large birds of prey of the family Accipitridae. Eagles belong to several groups of genera, some of which are closely related. Most of the 60 species of eagle are from Eurasia and Africa. Outside this area, just 14 species can be found—2 in North America, 9 in Central and South America, and 3 in Australia.Eagles are not a natural group but denote essentially any bird of prey large enough to hunt sizeable (about 50 cm long or more overall) vertebrate prey.DescriptionEagles are large, powerfully built birds of prey, with heavy heads and beaks.

Eastern Europe is the eastern region of Europe . There is no consistent definition of the precise area it covers, but it stretches from northern Romania to central and southern Hungary (including the Yugoslav Republic) and includes Poland, Lithuania, Latvia, Estonia and Estonia-based countries as well as a small part of the Czech Republic. The term 'European Union' is an informal international organisation established by the 17th Council of Europe in Strasbourg in 1949. Its members are:Austria, Denmark, France, Germany, Ireland, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Slovakia, Slovenia, Spain and United Kingdom.

New Sweden ( ; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America, North America, Europe and Asia from 1817 until its annexation by Great Britain in 1846. The colony was an important member of the United States during the 19th century and served as the principal administrative center for the United States in the western half of the country. It has been the subject of national and international attention since it was incorporated into the Union in 1851. As such, the history of the community has been closely watched by those who have spent significant time on the territory.

The Buran program ( , , `` Snowstorm '' , `` Blizzard '' ) , also known as the ``Ice Age'' or ``Climatic Epoch'' were a series of glaciations that lasted from about 7,000 B.C. to 9,000 C.E. in northern Eurasia and northern Europe. The Ice Age is often associated with the end of glaciations on either side of the Laurentide Ice Sheet boundary, which was first discovered by Danish paleographer Jakob Johansen in 1778. The Antarctic ice sheet was formed approximately 565 million years ago when the last continental ice sheet began to retreat.

The Novikov self-consistency principle, also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven's law of conservation of history, is a principle developed by Russian physicist Igor Dmitriyevich Novikov in the mid-1980s. Novikov intended it to solve the problem of paradoxes in time travel, which is theoretically permitted in certain solutions of general relativity that contain what are known as closed timelike curves. The principle asserts that if an event exists that would cause a paradox or any "change" to the past whatsoever, then the probability of that event is zero.

A white cane is a device used by many people who are blind or visually impaired . A white cane consists of a frame that is covered with a special material. It has a horizontal handle and a vertical one, which leads up to the cane's foot. They are usually constructed of wood or rubber. In English, the letter u ( ) stands for uncountable, but in other languages such as French it is used as part of nouns, adjectives, adverbs, and pronouns. The term is derived from the Latin numeral u; it is the number of the ordinal 0 through 6.

Rubber , also called India rubber , latex , Amazonian rubber , caucho , or caoutchouc , as initially produced in India and imported to Europe and Asia. A variety of forms, sizes, varieties, and styles of rubber were manufactured in India between the 11th and 14th centuries and are known as Indian style rubber. Pigtail-hiding is the method by which a person keeps his or her lips closed while speaking so that the tongue can't be heard. Pigtail-hiding refers to a specific kind of masking that involves keeping the lips shut for extended periods during spoken utterances.

The putamen (; from Latin, meaning "nutshell") is a round structure located at the base of the forebrain (telencephalon). The putamen and caudate nucleus together form the dorsal striatum. It is also one of the structures that compose the basal nuclei. Through various pathways, the putamen is connected to the substantia nigra, the globus pallidus, the claustrum, and the thalamus, in addition to many regions of the cerebral cortex. A primary function of the putamen is to regulate movements at various stages (e.g. preparation and execution) and influence various types of learning.

A political prisoner is someone imprisoned for their political activity . The political offense is not always the official reason for his or her detention; some are detained simply because they're a political opponent.Political prisoners have no legal rights to freedom of thought, speech or expression.In Canada , political prisoners are treated in the same way as all other convicted prisoners: by having them held in provincial and federal correctional facilities until they are released. It is possible for them to appeal their charges (see below).Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment in Canada have no access to a fair trial.

A hot air balloon is a lighter-than-air aircraft consisting of a bag , called an envelope , which contains heated air that, while in mid flight, is carried to high altitude so it will not get damaged. A hot air balloon can also carry passengers on the wings or on the tail. It is used for research and educational use. The word was coined by US astronaut Neil Armstrong during his 1972 historic Mars landing attempt. Hot water (also abbreviated H 2 O), also known as potable drinking water or "boiled water", is an essential component of the human body.

Melissa Sue Anderson ( born September 26 , 1962 ) is an American-Canadian actress . She began her career as an actress and voice actress on stage in 1993.She first gained national recognition with roles in the 1996 film My Favorite Thing Is Monsters, a comedy about a suburban schoolteacher's friendship with a misanthropic monster, and the 1997 television movie I'm Your Man, starring James Spader. Her breakthrough role came as a recurring guest on the ABC family sitcom Family Matters from 2004 to 2007. "My God, You Can't Do That!"

Year 926 ( CMXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Christian Asia during the second millennium A.D.[1][3][2]
During the first half of the 6th century, it is known as the "Golden Age", referring to the high level of civilization, education, and culture that was achieved after the fall of the Goths in the 13th century. The reign of the Roman Emperor Augustus marked the end of a period characterized by the most rapid economic growth in Christendom.

Westminster is an area of Central London , part of the wider City of Westminster.The area , which extends from the south bank of Thames to Oxford Street, was formally known as Westminster Abbey on the 13th August 1607, with the newly established King James VI taking over the abbey at the beginning of his reign in 1613 and naming it "the Westminster Abbey". The abbey then became known as St. Mary's Abbey, but was officially renamed after Edward I in 1640.The area was originally described as a forest by Sir Robert Hooke (1594–1674), who identified it as Forest Abbey in 1823.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572 ) was a Scottish minister , Reformed theologian , and writer. From 1592 until his death in 1598, he was the most prominent member of the Royal Society of Scotland. In the later years of King Charles II, he was Archbishop of St Andrews and Abbotsburg and served as Bishop of Salisbury. He was widely seen as one of the fathers of British Anglicanism, although he was not an early member.Knox lived in Scotland for over thirty years and died on 19 June 1594.

Year 1103 (MCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Bohemond I, Norman prince of Antioch, is released from Seljuk imprisonment at Niksar, after a ransom is paid of 100,000 gold pieces. During his absence, Tancred (Bohemond's nephew) attacks the Byzantines, and re-captures the cities of Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra in Cilicia. Tancred is deprived of his lordship by Bohemond's return, and is rewarded with a small fief within the Principality of Antioch.

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico (tragic opera) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti. Salvadore Cammarano wrote the Italian-language libretto loosely based upon Sir Walter Scott's 1819 historical novel The Bride of Lammermoor.Donizetti wrote Lucia di Lammermoor in 1835, when he was reaching the peak of his reputation as an opera composer. Gioachino Rossini had recently retired and Vincenzo Bellini had died shortly before the premiere of Lucia leaving Donizetti as "the sole reigning genius of Italian opera". Not only were conditions ripe for Donizetti's success as a composer, but there was also a widespread interest in the history and culture of Scotland.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state's south-east within the Limestone Coast region about  south east of the state capital of Adelaide and about  south-east of the municipal seat of Bordertown. The name is derived from the Potawurutj, the Aboriginal name for Good Water. Padthaway is in the Tatiara District Council, the state electorate of MacKillop and the federal Division of Barker.The 2016 Australian census which was conducted in August 2016 reports that Padthaway had a population of 418 people.Wine regionPadthaway is also the name of a wine region surrounding the town.

Tazio Giorgio Nuvolari ( ; 16 November 1892 – 11 August 1953 ) was an Italian racing driver . He is considered the father of Italian grand prix racing and, during his career, won several prestigious races. He was one of the pioneers of the modern Grand Prix Formula, while also introducing many new tactics and strategies to the sport. Dalibor (; 14 April 1797 – 29 March 1846) was an Austrian philosopher, mathematician, scientist, astronomer, and astronomer. He was a prominent figure in the German intellectual movement, and was among the founders of modern philosophy and science.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975. The show was first broadcast as a Comedy Playhouse pilot, then in seven series until 1975. In 1981, ITV continued the sitcom for six episodes, calling it Till Death.... The BBC produced a sequel from 1985 until 1992, In Sickness and in Health.Created by Johnny Speight, Till Death Us Do Part centred on the East End Garnett family, led by patriarch Alf Garnett (Warren Mitchell), a reactionary white working-class man who holds racist and anti-socialist views.

Patrick Jake O'Rourke (November 14, 1947 – February 15, 2022) was an American libertarian political satirist and journalist. O'Rourke was the H. L. Mencken Research Fellow at the libertarian Cato Institute and a regular correspondent for The Atlantic Monthly, The American Spectator, and The Weekly Standard, and frequent panelist on National Public Radio's game show Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me! He was a columnist at The Daily Beast from 2011 to 2016.He authored 16 books, including three that made The New York Times Best Seller list.

Domenico Gaetano Maria Donizetti ( 29 November 1797 – 8 April 1848 ) was an Italian composer , best known as a conductor in the Royal Italian Quartet. He was well-respected for his expressive and dynamic music, which was frequently described as the finest of the Renaissance. He is sometimes credited with originating the style of classical music known today as modern classical.His most important work is L'Innuovo Giuseppe di Montezemolo's Piano Concerto No 6 in B flat major.He studied at the Academy of Music of Naples under the patronage of Antonio Caruso, who also served as patron of the Montini Foundation.
